\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Microeconomics I.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Victor H.
 Aguiar 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
This version: August 2021
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Order Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preliminaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Order theory is essential to understand some decision theoretical aspects
 of consumer theory.
 In particular, the modeling preferences is done using order theory tools.
 However, the applicability of order theory in economics is not limited
 to this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Binary Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty set.
 A 
\series bold
binary relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in R$
\end_inset

 we will write 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $xRyRz$
\end_inset

 will mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(y,z)\in R$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be defined by for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb\iff a\geq b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,1)\in R$
\end_inset

 we can write this equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $2\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
(Alternate on the Reals: I am going to define now 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b\iff\frac{1}{a}\geq\frac{1}{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2
\end{array}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, the Lexicographic ordering says that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb\iff a_{1}>b_{1}$
\end_inset

 or (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=b_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}\geq b_{2}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
WTS: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 lexicographic is complete.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not in relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $bRa$
\end_inset

.
 If not 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb$
\end_inset

 this means that either 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}>a_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=b_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}\geq a_{2}$
\end_inset

, but this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $bRa$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is complete because the previous argument holds for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2
\end{array}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, the canonical ordering says that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb\iff a_{i}\geq b_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Lemma: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 canonical vector order is not complete.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
I want to construct a counter-example, take 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

, notice that neither 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $(\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
1
\end{array}\right))\in R$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $(\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
1
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
2
\end{array}\right))\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Lemma: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Take any three vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in X$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yRz$
\end_inset

 we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $xRz$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Proof: if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\geq y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\geq y_{2}$
\end_inset

; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $yRz$
\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\geq z_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}\geq z_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
This implies (because the scalar ranking on the reals 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq$
\end_inset

 is transitive) that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\geq y_{1}\geq z_{1}\implies x_{1}\geq z_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the same happens with the second entry and we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\geq z_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $xRz$
\end_inset

.
 In conclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $xRyRz$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $xRz$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Properties of Binary Relations 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Reflexivity: We say 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is reflexive if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRx$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Counterexample: 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in R\equiv$
\end_inset

(being different) when 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq y$
\end_inset

, not reflexive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Completeness (Totality): We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is complete if either 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

 holds for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Symmetry: We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is symmetric if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Asymmetry: We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is asymmetric if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot yRx$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Antisymmetric 
\begin_inset Formula $xRyRx$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Transitiviy: We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yRz$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $xRz$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Acyclic: 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}Rx_{2}R\cdots Rx_{n}$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\neq x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Acyclicity.
 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $bRd$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dRe$
\end_inset

 This is acyclic but it's not transitive.
 
\begin_inset Formula $aRbRdRe$
\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq e$
\end_inset

 hence acyclic.
 But since 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bRd$
\end_inset

 transivity requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $aRd$
\end_inset

 however this is not in the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Symmetry and not complete.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $aRb\iff a=b$
\end_inset

, take 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{4}{2}=2$
\end_inset

 this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $2=\frac{4}{2}$
\end_inset

, however it is not complete because 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 are not in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (aka not equal) and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 either.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Classes of Relations 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use this properties to define useful relations that are usually applied
 to describe preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Equivalence Relations) We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation if and only if it is reflexive, symmetric and
 transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equivalence relation is an important concept in economics, usually we
 use it to model 
\series bold
indifference
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Preorder) We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 is a preorder if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is reflexive and transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most known application of a preorder to economics is modelling decision
 maker preferences.
 But usually we impose also completeness or totality.
 We say that a consumer has a rational preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\in X\times X$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is a total/complete preorder.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Partial Order) We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 is a partial order if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, transitive, and antisymmetric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that the partial order rules out the existence of an equivalence
 relation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we define a linear order.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Linear Order) We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 is a linear order if and only if it is a complete partial order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Ordered Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to study now some tuples of sets and binary relations that
 are also very useful in economic modelling.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Poset) We say that the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,R)$
\end_inset

 is a poset if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a partial order.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The prime example of a Poset for economists is a consumer environment where
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the choice set and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a strict preference (albeit possibly incomplete).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Loset) We say that the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,R)$
\end_inset

 is a loset if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a linear order.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we can think of a consumer environment where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the choice set and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a (complete) strict preference.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Equivalent class) An equivalence class of any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 with respect to an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]_{I}=\{y\in X|yIx\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 where all items are considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equivalent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 to the element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The typical example of an equivalent class in economics is an 
\series bold
indifference curve.
 
\series default
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 be a consumption bundle and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be an indifference preference relation for a consumer then 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]_{\sim}$
\end_inset

 is the set of consumption bundles that the consumer is indifferent about.
 In the eyes of this particular consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in[x]_{\sim}$
\end_inset

 is exactly the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we define an important concept that is derived from the equivalence
 relation notion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Quotient Set) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an equivalence relation.
 The set of equivalence classes of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is called the quotient set of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $X/I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This requires an example to fix ideas.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 be an equivalence relation such that 
\begin_inset Formula $aIb$
\end_inset

, now 
\begin_inset Formula $X/I=\{[a]_{I},[c]_{I}\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $[a]_{I}=\{a,b\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[c]_{I}=\{c\}$
\end_inset

 by reflexivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
dd
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Quotient Set.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 set of rational numbers, endowed with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq$
\end_inset

 (same as the reals).
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{4}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}/=$
\end_inset

 (to do).
 Application: Well-defined functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f(\frac{p}{q})=p-q$
\end_inset

.
 Well-defined means that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=f(y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Important Concepts in Ordered Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First let's note that any binary relation can be separated into its symmetric
 and asymmetric part.
 Formally for every 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, there is a symmetric part called 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and a asymmetric part called 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a preorder order (preference relation), 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is an indifference relation and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a transitive, asymmetric and irreflexive order (strict preferences).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For binary relations we can define the concepts of maximal element and upper
 bound.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symmetric part of a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $xIy$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

.
 The asymmetric part of a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $xPy$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Maximum element) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be defined as a binary relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: the maximal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 according to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max(X,R)=\{x\in X|\text{there is no}\mbox{\quad y\in X:yPx}\},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 its the asymmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also we can define an upper bound of an ordered set as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Upper bound/maximal element) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be defined as a binary relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

: the upper bound elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 according to 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M(X,R)=\{x\in X|xRy\forall y\in X\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $M(X,\succ)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Max(X,\succ)=\{a,c\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is complete and transitive such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b\succ c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $M(X,\succeq)=Max(X,\succeq)=\{a\}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Transitive Closure and Extensions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we define what is a 
\series bold
closure 
\series default
of a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

-Closure) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation property.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C(R)\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 is a closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $xC(R)y$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $C(R)$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

 and is the smallest relation that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{P}$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $C(R)=\cap_{i\in\mathcal{C}}C_{i}(R)$
\end_inset

 it is the intersection of all relations 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}(R)\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $xC_{i}(R)y$
\end_inset

 in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}=\{M\subseteq X\times X|xRy\implies xMy|;Msatisfies\mathfrak{P}\}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be clear that a closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a binary relation that usually adds a property such as transitivity,
 symmetry or reflexivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Transitive Closure) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T(R)$
\end_inset

 is a transitive closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 if and only if it is a closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that satisfies transitivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are going to observe the following fact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
(Existence of Transitive Closure) Every binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has a transitive closure 
\begin_inset Formula $T(R)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is trivial because there is always a transitive order that contains
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, the trivial relation 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $xTy$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $aC_{1}bC_{1}c$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $cC_{2}aC_{2}b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $cI_{3}aI_{3}b$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another useful concept is an 
\series bold
extension.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a preorder on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 An extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a preorder 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\subset\succeq
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\subset\succ.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are the asymmetric parts of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We have our first result at hand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(Sziplrajn) For any non-empty set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and a partial order 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 there exists a linear order 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ^{*}$
\end_inset

 that is an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Omitted.
 Check Efe Ok Real Analysis book for details.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\succeq)$
\end_inset

 be a preordered set.
 There exists a complete preorder on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 to obtain its symmetric part, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

, defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y\iff x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succeq x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pick any item 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, and build its equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $[x]_{\sim}=\{y\in X|y\sim x\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quotient set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=X\setminus\sim=\{[x]_{\sim}\}_{x\in X}$
\end_inset

 removing repetitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,>)$
\end_inset

 is partially ordered set (Poset), when 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in Y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a>b$
\end_inset

 if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in b$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

.
 We note that 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

 is a partial order because it is reflexive, transitive and antisymmetric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We apply Sziplrajn theorem, to conclude that there exists a linear order
 
\begin_inset Formula $>^{*}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that is extends 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to build a total or complete preorder 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq^{*}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (the original set), as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x,y\in X:x\succ^{*}y\iff[x]_{\sim}>^{*}[y]_{\sim},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the symmetric part is going to be 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim*y\iff x\sim y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Existence of Extremal Elements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\succeq)$
\end_inset

 be a total preordered set and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 a non-empty finite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 .
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\cap(S\times S)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 (complete in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) then 
\begin_inset Formula $M(S,\succeq)=max(S,\succeq)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max(\succeq,S)=\{y\in S|\not\exists x\in S:x\succ y\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First step: 
\begin_inset Formula $|S|=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{a\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max(\succeq,S)=\{a\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second step: 
\begin_inset Formula $|S|=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{a,b\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $max(\succeq,S)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succ a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By totality/completeness these 2 cases are not possible, because a total
 preorder has to satisfy that either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succeq a$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\succeq$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $(b,a)\in\succeq$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\iff$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(b,a)\in\succeq$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in\succeq$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that for 
\begin_inset Formula $|S|=k$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 fixed and 
\begin_inset Formula $k>2$
\end_inset

, it follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max(S,\succeq)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, I want to show that for 
\begin_inset Formula $|S'|=k+1$
\end_inset

 it has to be that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max(S',\succeq)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S'=S\cup\{a\}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the induction hypothesis there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}\in max(S,\succeq)$
\end_inset

 from the previous step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition I know that, 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}\succeq b$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By totality or completeness it has to be that either 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq a^{*}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}\succeq a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the former case, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in max(S',\succeq)$
\end_inset

, in the latter case 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}\in max(S',\succeq)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max(S',\succeq)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Basics of Consumer Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preliminaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heart of the classical Microeconomic Theory is the rational consumer.
 We are going to learn how to model decision making under the assumption
 of rationality.
 Of course, along the way we will try to understand also what economists
 mean when they say a consumer is rational.
 The rational decision maker theory that we are going to study is limited
 to a very specific environment that we are going to present next, but be
 wary that most of the concepts we are going to learn in this chapter can
 be extended to other situations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Environment: Commodities and Budget Set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we describe formally the goods and services that a consumer may consume.
 We call the object of consumption 
\series bold
commodity.
 
\series default
We assume that the
\series bold
 commodity space
\series default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq1$
\end_inset

 is the number of commodities.
 We refer to any commodity by 
\begin_inset Formula $l\in\{1,\cdots,L\}$
\end_inset

 and to the quantity of the commodity by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}_{l}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
consumption bundle or commodity bundle 
\series default
is given by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}=(\overline{x}_{1},\cdots,\overline{x}_{L})')$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the commodity space may be to 'generic' for some modeling purposes
 (e.g., the situation at hand may rule out extremely large quantities of some
 commodities, or negative quantities are impossible) we use from now on
 the 
\series bold
consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\series default
Remember that the consumption set is an abstract concept that can be defined
 according to each modeling situation, but for now on we will let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In real life, the consumer cannot consume anything he likes from the consumption
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 He is constrained either by his available wealth or by other reasons.
 Here we focus in cases where the only constraint is given by his wealth.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\mathbb{R}_{+}$
\end_inset

 be the consumer's wealth (broadly defined).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 be the price vector associated with each commodity.
 The consumer is then limited to choose from his budget set.
 The budget set is a subset of the choice set 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and it is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)=\{x\in X|p'x\leq w\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Demand Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After studying the consumer environment, we need to establish what is the
 
\series bold
primitive 
\series default
or what is the data that we are going to try to model.
 The primitive is the demand function.
 The demand function is a mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $x:\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}\backslash\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}_{+}\mapsto X$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $((p,w)\mapsto\overline{x})$
\end_inset

 that takes as inputs price-wealth pairs and produces a commodity bundle
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)\in B(p,w)$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p,w)\leq w$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 denotes the quantity of commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 consumed at prices and wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an empirical object, we have not explained yet how it came to be.
 Also note that we have made a very strong assumption when taking a function
 as our primitive.
 Observing a demand function means that we know what the consumer is going
 to choose at all possible price-wealth pairs which is clearly impossible
 to do.
 But do not fret, there are ways to deal with this in a reasonable way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Cobb-Douglas Demand Function.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)=(\frac{\alpha w}{p_{1}},\frac{(1-\alpha)w}{p_{2}})'$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Consistency in Consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have established the ingredients, so to speak, (i.e., the environment
 and the primitive of our study), we are going to proceed to the modeling
 part of our study of consumption.
 The first approach to 'model' consumption is to talk about consistency
 in consumption choices.
 This is a somewhat different approach to modeling consumption to what you
 may have studied at the undergraduate level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will impose a set of restrictions or axioms over the Marshallian demand
 function that we expect to hold in all situations irrespective of the details.
 Here we understand modeling consumption as restricting the set of allowable
 behaviors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You may not want to call this 'modeling', but in any case, economists like
 to think of these axioms as the minimal requirements that a demand function
 has.
 Sadly, we must underline that these restrictions are the product of the
 introspection of theorist and not the result of careful empirical work
 that has established them as stylized facts.
 However, the theoretical principle of requiring minimal conditions or imposing
 minimal restrictions on the set of allowable behaviors is very important
 if we want to understand any behavioral phenomenon.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Walras' law) A demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is said to satisfy Walras' law if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p,w)=w$
\end_inset

 for all price-wealth pairs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You may find little objection to Walras' law, but this simple restriction
 rules out a lot of consumption behaviors that we do not want to pay attention
 when thinking about the consumer problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(No money illusion/ Homegeneity of Degree Zero (HD0)) A demand function
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is said to satisfy Homogeneity of Degree Zero if and only if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\alpha p,\alpha w)=x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The HD0 restriction is clearly stronger and here we are assuming that the
 consumer is intelligent enough so that he is not fooled by spurious changes
 in wealth that are countered by a change in prices of the same magnitude.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Weak Axiom of Revealed Preference -WARP) A demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is said to satisfy the WARP if and only if for any two distinct price-wealth
 pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p*,w*)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)\neq x(p*,w*)$
\end_inset

 it follows that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p*,w*)\leq w$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $(p*)'x(p,w)>w*$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The WARP is the most interesting of the restrictions presented until this
 point.
 It captures the idea that there is stability in the choices that consumers
 make.
 Notice the 'revealed preference' in the name of the WARP, it comes from
 the idea that by observing demand behavior underlying consumer preferences
 are revealed to the observer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's define a revealed preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{D}$
\end_inset

 that stands for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directly revealed preferred to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, this is a binary relation on the consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{D}\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

) defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{1},x^{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{2},x^{2})$
\end_inset

 be observed consumption bundles with its corresponding price, then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}\iff p^{1\prime}x^{1}\geq p^{1\prime}x^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the hypothesis in the WARP says 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p*,w*)\leq w$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x(p*,w*)$
\end_inset

 and recall that by Walras' law 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p,w)=w$
\end_inset

, also let 
\begin_inset Formula $z=x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $w=p'z\geq p'y$
\end_inset

 which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $zR^{D}y$
\end_inset

, or in words, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is directly revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The WARP is then the requirement that if 
\begin_inset Formula $zR^{D}y$
\end_inset

 then it has to be the case that we do not allow 
\begin_inset Formula $yR^{D}(P^{D})z$
\end_inset

.
 This means that we are not allowing that 
\begin_inset Formula $(p')'z\leq(p')'y$
\end_inset

 or equivalently it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $(p*)'x(p,w)>w*$
\end_inset

.
 The binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{D}$
\end_inset

 is declared to satisfy the weak axiom.
 Recall that this relation is not necessarily representing actual tastes/prefere
nces, we do not need them to do that.
 We are only establishing a condition that for many economists (back in
 the time of Samuelson) was the minimal requirement that all consumers fulfilled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Comparative Statics and Slutsky Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After establishing the axioms of behavior, the nest step is to study its
 implications in terms of the parameters of the model.
 The parameters of the model in our study of consumer behavior are prices
 and wealth pairs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We need some preliminaries and notation.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}x(p,w)=(\partial_{p_{k}}x_{l}(p,w))_{l,k\in\{1,\cdots,L\}}\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times L}$
\end_inset

 the matrix of price effects of the demand function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We let 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{w}x(p,w)=(\partial_{w}x_{l}(p,w))_{l\in\{1,\cdots,L\}}$
\end_inset

 be the vector of wealth effects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We say that the 
\series bold
Slutsky Matrix
\series default
 of a demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)=D_{p}x(p,w)+D_{w}x(p,w)x(p,w)'$
\end_inset

 or the total change of demand with respect to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Slutsky compensated variation of prices
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 A Slutsky compensated variation of prices is a price change that leaves
 the previously commodity bundle (at the original price situation) affordable
 at the new price situation.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{lk}=\partial_{p_{k}}x_{l}(p,w)+\partial_{w}x_{l}(p,w)x_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Think of the Slutsky compensated demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,p'q)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 a commodity bundle I want to make affordable then the derivative with respect
 to prices of this compensated demand is 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}x(p,p'q)=D_{p}x(p,p'q)+D_{w}x(p,p'q)q'$
\end_inset

, when we fix 
\begin_inset Formula $q=x$
\end_inset

 to the original commodity bundle we get the Slutsky matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)=D_{p}x(p,w)+D_{w}x(p,w)x'=D_{p}x(p,p'q)|_{q=x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Implications of Walras' law for the the Slutsky Matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfy Walras' law then: (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $p'D_{w}x(p,w)=1$
\end_inset

, (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $p'D_{p}x(p,w)=-x(p,w)'$
\end_inset

, (iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $p'S(p,w)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous fact part (i) implies that there exists at least one normal
 good, the reason is that there has to be at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{w}x_{l}(p,w)>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{l}p_{l}'\partial_{w}x_{l}(p,w)=1$
\end_inset

.
 In general, you can see that the Walras' law also restricts the behavior
 of the wealth effects.
 The previous fact part (iii) are restrictions on the behavior of the consumptio
n changes to Slutsky compensated price changes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Implications of Homogeneity of Degree Zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfy Walras' law and homogeneity of degree zero then 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)p=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By HD0 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\lambda p,\lambda w)=x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

, we derive by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and obtain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}x(\lambda p,\lambda w)p+D_{w}x(\lambda p,\lambda w)w=0$
\end_inset

.
 We let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, and recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p,w)=w$
\end_inset

 by Walras' law then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}x(p,w)p+D_{w}x(p,w)p'x=S(p,w)p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Implications of WARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main implication of the WARP while assuming Walras' law is the Compensated
 Law of Demand (CLD).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(CLD) We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Compensated Law of Demand if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(p*-p)'(x(p*,w*)-x(p,w))<0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p*,w*)\neq x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w*=(p*)'x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to establish that WARP implies the Law of Demand.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfy the Walras' law and WARP then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfies the CLD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z=x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x(p^{*},w^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}x(p,w)=w^{*}$
\end_inset

 and by Walras' law we have that:
\begin_inset Formula $p'z=w$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p*)'z=w*$
\end_inset

.
 Also we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(p*)'y=w*$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(p*)'(y-z)=0$
\end_inset

.
 By WARP since 
\begin_inset Formula $(p*)'z\leq w*$
\end_inset

 it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'y>w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have then 
\begin_inset Formula $p'y-p'z>0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p'(y-z)>0$
\end_inset

 subtract this from that 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{*})'(y-z)=0$
\end_inset

 to obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(p^{*}-p)'(y-z)<0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are going to establish a corollary of this result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Walras' law and WARP then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is negative semi-definite (
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)\leq0$
\end_inset

) for all price-wealth pairs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Walras' law and WARP then, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(p^{*}-p)'[x(p^{*},p^{*}x(p,w))-x(p,w)]\leq0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I consider a case such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $dp=(p^{*}-p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The differential version of the CLD is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dp'dx\leq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I compute 
\begin_inset Formula $dx=D_{p}x(p,w)dp+D_{w}x(p,w)dw$
\end_inset

, notice that by Slutsky compensation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dw=x(p,w)'dp=dp'x(p,w).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dp'dx=dp'[D_{p}x(p,w)+D_{w}x(p,w)x(p,w)]dp,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dp'dx=dp'S(p,w)dp\leq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Write down a Giffen goods demand function.
 Compute the Slutsky and the substitution matrix compare.
 Write down a utility function that produces giffen goods, compute the demand,
 slutsky matrix and substition matrix.
 Show that the Slutsky matrix is NSD for the giffen good.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)'=(x_{1}^{G}(p,w),x_{2}(p,w))'$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{G}(p,w)=p_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}=w$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(p,w)=\frac{w}{p_{2}}-p_{1}^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}x=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-2p_{1} & -\frac{w}{p_{2}^{2}}
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $D_{w}x=\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
\frac{1}{p_{2}}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-2p_{1} & -\frac{w}{p_{2}^{2}}
\end{array}\right)+\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
\frac{1}{p_{2}}
\end{array}\right][p_{1}\quad(\frac{w}{p_{2}}-p_{1}^{2})]=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
-2p_{1} & -\frac{w}{p_{2}^{2}}
\end{array}\right)+\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}} & \frac{w}{p_{2}^{2}}-\frac{p_{1}^{2}}{p_{2}}
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Ramen noodles vs.
 meat.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a consumer that has to decide how much to consume of two goods
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 (Ramen noodles) and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 (meat).
 The consumer utility function for the two goods is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x_{1},x_{2}):=\alpha_{1}ln(x_{1}-\gamma_{1})-\alpha_{2}ln(\gamma_{2}-x_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{1}ln(x_{1}-\gamma_{1})+\alpha_{2}ln(\frac{1}{\gamma_{2}-x_{2}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}>\alpha_{1}>0$
\end_inset

 are positive numbers, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 are positive numbers that represent a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

basic need
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 level of consumption of the goods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to assume that the solution to the problem has to satisfy that
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq x_{2}<\gamma_{_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 refer the the quantities of Ramen noodles and meat respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea here is that Ramen noodles provide a subsistence level of categories
 and the consumer gets positive utility from being above this level.
 In contrast, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a luxury good, so the consumer will not go over the level 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

, however she gets positive utility from consuming meat.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The marginal rate of substitution between good 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{dx_{1}}{dx_{2}}=\frac{\alpha_{1}(\gamma_{2}-x_{2})}{\alpha_{2}(x_{1}-\gamma_{1})}>0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The demand functions for this model are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}=\gamma_{1}-\frac{\beta_{1}}{p_{1}}(w-p_{1}\gamma_{1}-p_{2}\gamma_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}=\gamma_{2}+\frac{\beta_{2}}{p_{2}}(w-p_{1}\gamma_{1}-p_{2}\gamma_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}=\frac{\alpha_{1}}{(\alpha_{2}-\alpha_{1})}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}=\frac{\alpha_{2}}{(\alpha_{2}-\alpha_{1})}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for 
\begin_inset Formula $w-p_{2}\gamma_{x2}<p_{1}\gamma_{1}<w-p_{2}\gamma_{x2}+\frac{p_{2}\gamma_{2}}{\beta_{2}}$
\end_inset

 that ensure that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq x_{2}<\gamma_{_{x2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix a point in this domain (in the interior of the domain) of prices and
 wealth, such that we have the solution above and obtain the Slutsky matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Price Effects:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{p}x(p,w)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
-\frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}(w-\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}2}\text{p2})}{\text{p1}^{2}(\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2})} & \frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}2}}{\text{p1}(\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1})}\\
\frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}1}}{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}\text{p2}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}\text{p2}} & \frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}(w-\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}1}\text{p1})}{\text{p2}^{2}(\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2})}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{p_{1}}x_{1}\geq0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $w-p_{2}\gamma_{2}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 The slope of the demand for Ramen noodles has upward slope! Why? When the
 price of Ramen increases then the consumer now is poorer than before.
 This is the Giffen Paradox, in which, under subsistence conditions, a rise
 in the price of a cheap foodstuff (Ramen noodles) can force poor families
 to consume more, rather than less of it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wealth Effects:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{w}x(p,w)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}}{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}\text{p1}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}\text{p1}}\\
\frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}}{\text{p2}(\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1})}
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumption of Ramen noodles will decrease as wealth increases.
 The richer the families are the lowest the consumption of Ramen noodles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Slutsky Matrix:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen that the price effects are an imperfect measure of the effects
 of prices in consumption.
 Due to the fact that prices determine the choice set by their effect in
 the budget constraint they have two effects.
 The first effect is the direct price effect on consumption, the second
 through wealth or purchasing power.
 The Slutsky matrix corrects for the second effect and gives you a net effect:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(p,w)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}(-\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}1}\text{p1}-\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}2}\text{p2}+w)}{\text{p1}^{2}(\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2})^{2}} & \frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}(\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}1}\text{p1}+\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}2}\text{p2}-w)}{\text{p1}\text{p2}(\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2})^{2}}\\
\frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}(\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}1}\text{p1}+\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}2}\text{p2}-w)}{\text{p1}\text{p2}(\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2})^{2}} & \frac{\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2}(-\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}1}\text{p1}-\text{\ensuremath{\gamma}2}\text{p2}+w)}{\text{p2}^{2}(\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}1}-\text{\ensuremath{\alpha}2})^{2}}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
- & +\\
+ & -
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By our conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $w-p_{2}\gamma_{x2}<p_{1}\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

 it must be that the Slutsky compensated effect of the Giffen good (Ramen
 noodles) is negative 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)_{11}\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Traditional Consumer Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The traditional approach to consumer theory is to assume that the consumer
 has well-defined preferences over all alternative bundles and that the
 consumer attempts to select the most preferred bundle from among those
 available to him.
 In other words, we are trying to write a model of how consumer decide and
 choose.
 The main practical benefit of this type of approach is that we can write
 tracktable/computable economic models that include 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

intelligent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 consumers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rational Preferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most powerful modelling technique to represent consumer tastes are binary
 relations.
 We say that a consumer is rational if his preferences can be represented
 by a binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

 that has two properties: (i) Completeness.
 (ii) Transitivity.
 Alternatively, this is a complete/total preorder (reflexive, transitive
 and complete).
 Observe that completeness implies reflexivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Rational Preferences) A binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to be a rational preference relation if and only if it is a complete/to
tal preorder on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at least as good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

 or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The asymmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 but no 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succeq x$
\end_inset

.
 The symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 is used to represent strict preferences or 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is strictly preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The symmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 represents indifference in preferences, when we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is indifferent to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succeq x$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Important Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to study three very important sets in consumer theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Upper contour set) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a rational preference on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The upper contour set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{\succeq}(x)=\{y\in X|y\succeq x\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This set captures the better than equal alternatives of any given commodity
 under the rational preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Lower contour set) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a rational preference on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The lower contour set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(x)=\{y\in X|x\succeq y\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And finally the well-known set (indifference curve/set).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Indifference set) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a rational preference on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The indifference set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{\succeq}(x)=\{y\in X|x\sim y\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For now we will just state the definitions, in a moment, we will use them
 to prove important results of consumer theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are going to state properties of the rational preferences, that we
 are going to impose across our study of the consumer theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Perhaps the most important one is 
\series bold
monotonicity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 monotonicity) A preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is monotone if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}>y_{l}$
\end_inset

 for all commodities 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 It is strongly monotone if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}\geq y_{l}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}>y_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Monotonicity and strong monotonicity correspond to the behavior idea of
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more is better
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preferences that are strongly monotone are monotone but not the other way
 around.
 If preference are monotone or strongly monotone it follows immediately
 that the consumer will choose something on the frontier of his budget constrain
t.
 Clearly, this implies Walras' law.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An even weaker condition on preferences that implies the Walras' law and
 is very useful in our upcoming results is local non-satiation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 local non-satiation) A preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 satisfies local non-satiation if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there is a point 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $||x-y||\leq\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The local non-satiation assumption also rules 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thick
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 indifference sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
If a demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the result of maximizing a locally non-satiated preference relation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p,w)=w$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $P\implies Q$
\end_inset

) , 
\begin_inset Formula $P=$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

-maximizing and affordable such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is LNS.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p,w)=w$
\end_inset

 (Walras' Law).
 I negate the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot Q$
\end_inset

, I will prove that this gives me a contradiction.
 (
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot Q$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 maximizing, affordable and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are LNS and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p,w)<w$
\end_inset

.
 By LNS I know that there exist and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 small enough such that there exist a 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B(p,w)$
\end_inset

 (affordable) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $||y-x||\leq\epsilon$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ x$
\end_inset

.
 But that implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 cannot be 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 maximizing because this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 I conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\implies Q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another very important assumption that we are going to use in the upcoming
 chapters is convexity of preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 Convexity) Preferences are convex whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\succeq y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)z\succeq y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Preferences are strictly convex if whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq z$
\end_inset

 then for every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)z\succ y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, we can say that consumers with convex preferences prefer
 averages to extremes.
 For example if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)y\succeq x$
\end_inset

.
 The preferences are strictly convex if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)y\succ x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $tx+(1-t)y\succ y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Utility Representation Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preferences are the most general way to represent consumer tastes.
 However, they are not particularly easy to work with when modeling complex
 economic problems.
 For this reason, and also because economists are more used to deal with
 real analysis/calculus than with order theory we usually use a utility
 function to represent consumer preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A utility function is a continuous mapping from the choice set to the reals,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 A utility function is a representation of a preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are complete and transitive and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is finite then there exists a continuous mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, that represents the preference 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(a)\geq u(b)\iff a\succeq b,\forall a,b\in X.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Necessity: (We want to show) If there is a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is rational (complete and transitive).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there is a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

 then I declare a preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is complete, this follows from the fact that either 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b)\geq u(a)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a),u(b)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is transitive, this follows from the fact that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b)\geq u(c)$
\end_inset

 then it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(c)$
\end_inset

, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 constructed above is transitive itself because it inherits the transitivity
 from the order 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sufficiency: If there is an ordering 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that is rational (complete and transitive) then there exist a utility mapping
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, such that if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 finite) then there is a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, I build the Lower Contour Set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L^{\succeq}(x)=\{y\in X|x\succeq y\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, I propose the following utility function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)=|L^{\succeq}(x)|,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 is the cardinality of a set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step is to check that the candidate utility function is well-defined:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $X\setminus\sim$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\pi\circ\hat{u}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is taking the canonical projection to the Quotient set 
\begin_inset Formula $X/\sim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}:X\setminus\sim\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, is defined used the linear order induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

, as follows 
\begin_inset Formula $[a]_{\sim}\succ^{*}[b]_{\sim}\iff a\succ b$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

, the linear order induces an ennumeration of items from best to worst,
 in fact use the strict lower counter set so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}(x)=|L^{\succ^{*}}(x)|$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X\backslash\sim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to check that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq x$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then 
\begin_inset Formula $|L^{\succeq}(x)|=|L^{\succeq}(y)|$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we know that by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(x)=\{y\in X|x\succ y\}\cup I^{\succeq}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{\succeq}(x)\equiv I^{\succeq}(y)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

, first if 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in I^{\succeq}(x)$
\end_inset

 it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $z\sim x$
\end_inset

, by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

, by transitivity I conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $z\sim y$
\end_inset

 therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in I^{\succeq}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $z'\in I^{\succeq}(y)$
\end_inset

 that means that 
\begin_inset Formula $z'\sim y$
\end_inset

 and by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim x$
\end_inset

, by transitivity I conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $z'\sim x$
\end_inset

 therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $z'\in I^{\succeq}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I know that this is the same set for both 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

, then the cardinality has to be the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second step is to prove that this particular construction represents
 the preference relation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b\implies|L^{\succeq}(a)|\geq|L^{\succeq}(b)|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $|L^{\succeq}(a)|\geq|L^{\succeq}(b)|$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(b)\subseteq L^{\succeq}(a)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in L^{\succeq}(b)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succeq c$
\end_inset

, I also know by assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

, 
\series bold
by transitivity, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq c$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\series default
that 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in L^{\succeq}(a)$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to the statement
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $|L^{\succeq}(a)|\geq|L^{\succeq}(b)|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude that in fact, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

, then there is a mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We must first remark that not all rational preferences can be represented
 by a utility function.
 The assumption that we need on preferences to guarantee that they can be
 represented by a utility function is 
\series bold
continuity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Counterexample.
 Show that the following preferences are not complete: 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\iff$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(a)\geq u_{i}(b)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b\iff min_{i\in\{1,2,3\}}(u_{i}(a)-u_{i}(b))\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 You need to find a counterexample where there is a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $min_{i\in\{1,2,3\}}(u_{i}(x)-u_{i}(y))<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $min_{i\in\{1,2,3\}}(u_{i}(y)-u_{i}(x))<0$
\end_inset

 this is equivalent to incompleteness.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}(a)=3,u_{1}(b)=2,u_{1}(c)=1$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}(a)=1,u_{2}(b)=2,u_{2}(c)=3$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}(a)=2,u_{3}(b)=1,u_{3}(c)=3$
\end_inset

.
 Now, since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}(a)-u_{2}(c)=-2,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}(c)-u_{1}(a)=-2$
\end_inset

, it means that neither 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq c$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $c\succeq a$
\end_inset

.
 So this consumer cannot rank 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

-Continuity) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\succeq y^{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in N$
\end_inset

 then if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{n}\rightarrow y$
\end_inset

 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are complete, transitive and continuous then there is a continuous mapping
 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq u(y)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to prove this result formally in what follows, for now let's
 take it as given.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Ordinal Meaning of the Utility Function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utility representation of a rational preference relation has only ordinal
 meaning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, then there exists a monotone mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v=f\circ u$
\end_inset

 also represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof is very simple and you should do it for practice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Utility Maximization Problem (UMP)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that preferences are well-behaved, in particular preferences are
 rational, continuous, strictly convex and locally nonsatiated.
 These assumptions imply that the consumer has a continuous utility function
 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and that the consumer choices will satisfy Walras' law.
 For now we will assume that the preferences are also differentiable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer's problem or utility maximization problem (UMP) is to choose
 the bundle that maximizes utility from among those available to him.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of available bundles is given by the Budget Constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)=\{x\in X|p'x\leq w\}$
\end_inset

.
 We will assume that prices are positive 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 and that wealth is strictly positive as well.
 The consumer's problem can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x\geq0}u(x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we establish that the problem has a solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
The UMP has a solution.
 Moreover, the solution is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is continuous, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is closed and bounded set (i.e., for 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is compact).
 By the Weiestrass theorem, we know that a continuous function on a compact
 set always achieves its maximum.
 Uniqueness follows from the strict convexity of preferences, this means
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is strictly quasi-concave and given that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is convex too then the solution to the maximization problem is also unique.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are going to see how to find the solution under the differentiability
 assumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write the KKT FOC necessary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}=u(x)+\lambda(w-p'x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{l}}u(x^{*})-\lambda^{*}p_{l}\leq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}[\partial_{x_{l}}u(x^{*})-\lambda^{*}p_{l}]=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $l\in\{1,\cdots,L\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $w-p'x^{*}\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{*}(w-p'x^{*})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a system with 
\begin_inset Formula $L+1$
\end_inset

 unknowns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to simplify a little bit the problem.
 By local non-satiation we know that the consumer is on the budget hyperplane
 (frontier).
 This means that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w-p'x^{*}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Also we are going to assume that the solution in interior, this means that
 the KKT conditions are reduced to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial_{x_{l}}u(x^{*})}{\partial_{x_{k}}u(x^{*})}=\frac{p_{l}}{p_{k}}\quad\forall l,k\in\{1,\cdots,L\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the budget line and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\partial_{x_{1}}u(x^{*})}{\partial_{x_{2}}u(x^{*})}$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the indifference curve, usually this is also referred as
 the MRS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=x_{1}+x_{2}$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}=w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}=x_{1}+x_{2}+\lambda(w-p_{1}x_{1}-p_{2}x_{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $1-\lambda p_{1}\leq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}[1-\lambda p_{1}]=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $1-\lambda p_{2}\leq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}[1-\lambda p_{2}]=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}=w$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Case 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=0$
\end_inset

;
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=w/p_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\lambda p_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\lambda p_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}\iff p_{2}\leq p_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Case 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\in[0,w/p_{1}]$
\end_inset

, this is a violation of my theorem because of lack of strict convexity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Case 3: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=\frac{w}{p_{1}},x_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\leq p_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=\min\{x_{1},x_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}=w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{2}$
\end_inset

, which implies the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=\frac{w}{p_{1}+p_{2}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Properties of the Marshallian Demand Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Marshallian demand function is the unique solution to the UMP problem
 above.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)=argmax_{x\geq0}u(x)$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Walras' Law: 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p,w)=w$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,w$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from local non-satiation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Homogeneity of degree zero in 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 The definition of homogeneity is the same as always.
 It is very easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)\equiv B(\alpha p,\alpha w)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

, thus changing 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 does not alter the constraint set.
 Check the FOC conditions also.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
WARP.
 The Marshallian demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 satisfies WARP.
 (
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1},x^{1}),(p^{2},x^{2})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1}x^{1}\geq p^{1}x^{2}$
\end_inset

 I conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 WARP requires that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}$
\end_inset

 then it cannot happen that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}P^{D}x^{1}$
\end_inset

 (i.e., it cannot be that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}x^{2}>p^{2}x^{1}$
\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}\in argmax_{x}u(x)$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{i\prime}x\leq p^{i\prime}x^{i}=w^{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

, then (
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1},x^{1}),(p^{2},x^{2})$
\end_inset

 satisfies WARP.
 Proof: If I observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1}x^{1}\geq p^{1}x^{2}$
\end_inset

, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{1})\geq u(x^{2})$
\end_inset

, assume towards contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}x^{2}>p^{2}x^{1}$
\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{2})>u(x^{1})$
\end_inset

, but this is a contradiction of the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{1})\geq u(x^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Slutsky Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is NSD, singular in prices and symmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(Strong Axiom of Revealed Preference, SARP) If there is a unique solution
 to the UMP it follows that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}R^{D}x^{3}\cdots R^{D}x^{n}$
\end_inset

 then it has to be that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}\neq x^{n}$
\end_inset

 (acyclicity).
 Equivalently, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}R^{D}x^{3}\cdots R^{D}x^{n}$
\end_inset

 then it cannot be that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}P^{D}x^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Suposse that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{n}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}R^{D}x^{3}\cdots R^{D}x^{n}$
\end_inset

 by utility maximization it has to be that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{1})\geq u(x^{2})\geq u(x^{3})\geq\cdots\geq u(x^{n})$
\end_inset

, by transitivity it has to be that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{1})\geq u(x^{n})$
\end_inset

, by the uniqueness of the solution assumption we strengthen the weak inequaliti
es to strong inequalities and conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{1})>u(x^{n})$
\end_inset

, this contradicts the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}=x^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implication of Rationality and Recoverability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that satisfy Walras' law and is cont.
 differentiable can be generated by the UMP if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and NSD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Properties of the the Indirect Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The indirect utility is the maximal utility achieved given the budget constraint
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=max_{x\geq0}u(x)$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively it is the utility evaluated in the Marshallian demand 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=u(x(p,w))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Homogeneity of degree zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and non-increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 due to local non-satiation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is quasiconvex in 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(p,w)|v(p,w)\leq\overline{v}\}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Roy's Identity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall the definition of indirect utility 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=u(x(p,w))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the Envelope's theorem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=max_{x\geq0}u(x)+\lambda(w-p'x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{w}v(p,w)=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{p}v(p,w)=-\lambda x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This provides the Roy's identity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(p,w)=-\frac{\nabla_{p}v(p,w)}{\partial_{w}v(p,w)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Expenditure Minimization Problem (EMP)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Expenditure Minimization Problem (EMP) asks the question, if prices
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, what is the minimum amount the consumer would have to spend to achieve
 utility level 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}$
\end_inset

.
 That is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
min_{x\geq0}p'x
\]

\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)\geq\overline{u}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian for this problem is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{EMP}=p'x-\lambda(u(x)-\overline{u}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming an interior solution, the FOC are given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p-\lambda\nabla_{x}u(x)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda(u(x)-\overline{u})=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is quasiconcave, increasing in each argument then the constraint will bind
 and we can write the second constraint as 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 and a unique solution for the problem will exists.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to this problem 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,\overline{u})=argmin_{x}p'x$
\end_inset

 s.t 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
Hicksian demand
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
expenditure function 
\series default
is the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,\overline{u})=p'h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 value attained at the given prices and target utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a 
\series bold
duality relation
\series default
 between the EMP and the UMP that we will not explore at this point.
 However, we will state the following relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(p,v(p,w))=x(p,w)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(p,e(p,u))=h(p,u).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{u}=v(p,e(p,\overline{u}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w=e(p,v(p,w)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Properties of the Hicksian Demand and Expenditure Functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Properties of the Hicksian Demand Function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Homogeneity of degree zero in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why? Because 
\begin_inset Formula $min_{x}\alpha p'x$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 is the same as optimizing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $min_{x}p'x$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq\overline{u}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 changes the minimum expenditure (objective function value) but not the
 minimizer, the hicksian demand.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 No excess utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u(h(p,\overline{u}))=\overline{u}$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from continuity.
 Suppose not, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(h(p,\overline{u}))>\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $h'$
\end_inset

 that is smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 on all dimensions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'h'(p,\overline{u})<p'h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

, this is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Under strict convexity recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 is unique.
 Without it, 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 is a set, and convexity makes it a convex set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Properties of the Expenditure Function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree one in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 and non-decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 is concave in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p',\overline{u})\geq\alpha e(p,\overline{u})+(1-\alpha)e(p',\overline{u})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\alpha}=\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p'$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})=p^{\alpha\prime}h(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\alpha p'h(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})+(1-\alpha)(p')'h(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\ge\alpha p'h(p,\overline{u})+(1-\alpha)(p')'h(p',\overline{u}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p'h(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})\geq\alpha p'h(p,\overline{u})=e(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 by optimality of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sheppard's Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again using the Envelope's theorem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(p,\overline{u})=p'h+\lambda(u(h)-\overline{u})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla_{p}e(p,\overline{u})=h(p,\overline{u})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Additional Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)=\mathcal{H}e(p,u)=(\partial_{p_{k}}\partial_{p_{l}}e(p,u))$
\end_inset

 the derivative with respect to prices of the Hicksian demand is the Hessian
 of the expenditure function.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)=\nabla_{p'}\nabla_{p}e(p,u)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)$
\end_inset

 is a NSD matrix this follows from the fact that a Hessian of a concave
 function is NSD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
 Young's theorem (continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

), i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{p_{k}}\partial_{p_{l}}e(p,u)=\partial_{p_{l}}\partial_{p_{k}}e(p,u)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)p=0$
\end_inset

 follows from HD0 of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and Euler's identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Slutsky Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We establish now a very useful equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(p,u)=x(p,e(p,u))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiating with respect ot 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{p}h(p,u)=D_{p}x(p,e(p,u))+D_{w}x(p,e(p,u))\nabla_{p}e(p,u)'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Sheppard's lemma and by the identities that relate the expenditure and
 wealth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Slutsky 
\series bold
Equation
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{p}h(p,v(p,w))=D_{p}x(p,w)+D_{w}x(p,w)x(p,w)'.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implications of Rationality 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that satisfy Walras' law and is continuously differentiable can be generated
 by the UMP if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and NSD (and 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)p=0$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full proof is beyond the reach of the course but we have already proved
 the necessity part.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Welfare Evaluation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will compare the wealth needed to achieve a certain level of utility
 at a given price-wealth pair.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u^{1}=v(p^{1},w)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u^{0}=v(p^{0},w).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in comparing the expenditure needed to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a fixed reference price and a given utility level 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, the needed expenditure to reach it is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(p^{ref},u).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the comparison in terms of expenditure is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(p^{ref},u^{1})-e(p^{ref},u^{0})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(p^{ref},v(p^{1},w))-e(p^{ref},v(p^{0},w)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression will be positive when it takes more wealth to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{1}$
\end_inset

 at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ref}$
\end_inset

 than to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This difference is measured in dollar terms.
 That is why 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p^{ref},v(p,w))$
\end_inset

 is often called money metric indirect utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can construct many money metric indirect utility functions with different
 reference price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ref}=p^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the original price situation then the change is expenditure is equal
 to the change in wealth such that the consumer would be indifferent between
 the new price with the old wealth and the old price and the new wealth.
 This asks what change is wealth would be equivalent to the change in price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
equivalent variation is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
EV(p^{0},p^{1},w)=e(p^{0},v(p^{1},w))-e(p^{0},v(p^{0},w))=e(p^{0},v(p^{1},w))-w,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
since 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p^{0},v(p^{0},w))=w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Equivalent variation is the amount of money the consumer is 
\series bold
willing to pay
\series default
 to avoid a price change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other case considered is the one where the new price is taken as the
 reference price, when 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ref}=p^{1}$
\end_inset

, the change is expenditure is equal to the change in wealth such that the
 consumer is indifferent between the original situation 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{0},w)$
\end_inset

 and the new situation 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{1},w+\Delta w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
compensating variation 
\series default
is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CV(p^{0},p^{1},w)=e(p^{1},v(p^{1},w))-e(p^{1},v(p^{0},w))=w-e(p^{1},v(p^{0},w)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How much must
\series bold
 I compensate you
\series default
 to make you as well-off as you were before the price change?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When is one concept more useful than the other?  Los Angeles decides to
 build a new freeway which cuts through a neighborhood.
 How much would the city have to pay the residents of this neighborhood
 to keep them as well off as they were before? CV  What is the most the
 residents would pay not to have the freeway? EV
\end_layout

