 Nolan Miller Illinois he has notes on Consumer Theory plus Partial Equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Micro Kreps Vol 1.
 Advanced Varian could be useful for the Revealed Preference Part.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Jehle & Reny Advanced Micro Theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Preference and Choice (MGW Cp 1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision Theory uses three languages: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Choice rules or correspondences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Preference relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Utility functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Choice structure/environment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be non-empty, choice set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Choice correspondence: 
\begin_inset Formula $c:2^{X}\backslash\emptyset\mapsto2^{X}\backslash\emptyset$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(A)\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in2^{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is infinite sometimes we don't want deal with the whole power set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}\subseteq2^{X}\backslash\emptyset$
\end_inset

 this set of menus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Choice Structure is pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{B},c)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c(A)\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-Rich dataset when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is finite: 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a,b\}\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a,b,c\}\in\mathcal{B}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{l1,l2,l3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{l1,l2\},\{l1,l2,l3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{l1,l2\})=\{l1\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{l1,l2,l3\}=\{l2,l3\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Rationalizable choice correspondence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
is rationalizable
\series default
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $c(A)=c^{*}(\succeq,A)=\{b\in A|b\succeq a,\forall a\in A\}$
\end_inset

, for any given 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is rational (i.e., complete and transitive).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preference Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 a binary relation is a subset of the cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\subseteq X\times X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An asymmetric part 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot b\succeq a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A symmetric part 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succeq a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(1.B.1 MWG) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is rational then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 is irreflexive and transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, transitive and symmetric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y\succeq z$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot x\succ x$
\end_inset

 irreflexive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ x$
\end_inset

 it implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot x\succeq x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transitivity 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succ c$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ b$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot b\succeq a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succ c$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succeq c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot c\succeq b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) and (ii) imply by trans.
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot c\succeq a$
\end_inset

 (neg.
 transitivity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim x$
\end_inset

 reflexive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim x$
\end_inset

 (symmetry)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y\succeq z$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ z$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case 1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y\succ z$
\end_inset

 this follows from (i).
 Transitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case 2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y\sim z$
\end_inset

 this follows from (ii).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot y\succeq x$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succeq z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\succeq y$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ruling out 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim z$
\end_inset

, by transitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Problems with transitivity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Just perceptible differences.
 Inattention or Missperception.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Framing effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Condorcet Paradox.
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $O\succ_{M}R\succ_{M}I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I\succ_{D}O\succ_{D}R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R\succ_{C}I\succ_{C}O$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine pairs competing for a majority.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $OvsR$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 wins.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $RvsI$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 wins
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $IvsO$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 wins
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude that the household preference relation is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $O\succ R\succ I\succ O$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\{O,R,I\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{F}(\{O,R,I\})=\emptyset.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Utility function is 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Utility represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)\geq u(b)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
A preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 can be represented by a utility function only if it rational (X is finite).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Choice Rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-Let the choice structure be 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{B},c)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Weak Axiom of Revealed Preference (WARP).
 If for some 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in B$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(B)$
\end_inset

, then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $B'\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in B'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in c(B')$
\end_inset

 we must also have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(B')$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Revealed Preferences) 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq^{D}:$
\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is directly revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq^{D}b$
\end_inset

) whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in c(B)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is directly and strictly revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ^{D}b)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in c(B),$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin c(B)$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is (indirectly) revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq^{*}b$
\end_inset

) if there is some sequence of items 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{1},a^{2},\cdots,a^{n}\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq^{D}a^{1}\succeq^{D}a^{2}\succeq\cdots\succeq a^{n}\succeq^{D}b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
WARP.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is directly revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 cannot be strictly revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
WARP.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{D}y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot y\succ^{D}x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a rational preference relation.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{B},c)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is rationalizable (with 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

) then 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 satisfies the WARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is rationalizable then 
\begin_inset Formula $c(A)=c^{*}(\succeq,A)=\{b\in A:b\succeq a\forall a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is complete and transitive).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $B,B'\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in B\cap B'$
\end_inset

: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c^{*}(\succeq,B)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in c^{*}(\succeq,B')$
\end_inset

, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succeq x$
\end_inset

, by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 that means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c^{*}(\succeq,B')$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq b\forall b\in B'$
\end_inset

 given that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succeq b\forall b\in B'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

, by transitivity it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c^{*}(\succeq,B')$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relation between preferences and choice correspondences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{l1,l2,l3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{l1,l2\},\{l1,l2,l3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{l1,l2\})=\{l1\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{l1,l2,l3\}=\{l2,l3\}$
\end_inset

.
 WARP fails.
 First, from 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{l1,l2\})=\{l1\}$
\end_inset

 we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $l1\succ^{D}l2$
\end_inset

, and from 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{l1,l2,l3\})=\{l2,l3\}$
\end_inset

 we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $l2\succ^{D}l1$
\end_inset

, this is a violation of WARP hence 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is not rationalizable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 rationalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $c(B)=c^{*}(B,\succeq)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{B},c)$
\end_inset

 is such that (i) WARP is satisfied and (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 includes all subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 up to three elements and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is finite (rich dataset).
 Then there is a rational 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 preference relation that rationalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, this is the only preference relation that does so.
 (With the implicit assumption that choice correspondence is nonempty.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My objective is to build a model: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we propose 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq\equiv\succeq^{D}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq^{D}$
\end_inset

 is the revealed preference relation defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{D}y\iff x\in c(B)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) Check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is complete.
 We want to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succeq x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
Because the data is rich
\series default
 we have that all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y\}\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 are included in the dataset.
 This means that either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(\{x,y\})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in c(\{y,x\})$
\end_inset

 (because the choice correspondence is assumed to be non-empty).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) Check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is transitive.
 We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succeq z$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(B\cup\{y\})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in c(B'\cup\{z\})$
\end_inset

, now say we have 
\begin_inset Formula $B''$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y,z\}\equiv B''$
\end_inset

.
 We have the following cases, 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in c(B'')$
\end_inset

 in this case by WARP we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in c(B'')$
\end_inset

 and by WARP again 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(B'')$
\end_inset

, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y\sim z$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is transitive).
 The other case is 
\begin_inset Formula $z\notin c(\{x,y,z\})$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{x,y,z\})\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 is non-empty by assumption we know that either 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(\{x,y,z\})$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is transitive, or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in c(\{x,y,z\})$
\end_inset

 in which case by WARP 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(\{x,y,z\})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y\succeq z$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}(\succeq)$
\end_inset

 rationalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(B)$
\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{D}y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c^{*}(B,\succeq)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c^{*}(B',\succeq)$
\end_inset

 then this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B'$
\end_inset

 this implies that there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{y}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(B_{y})$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $c(B')\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, the WARP implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in c(B')$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}(B,\succeq)\equiv c(B)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, for uniqueness, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 being rich includes all pairs thus we determine completely the preferences
 over pairs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What about general datasets (e.g., datasets that may not contain all triples
 and tuples).
 It turns out that WARP is not sufficient to guarantee that such a dataset
 can be rationalized by a rational preference function.
 We need a stronger version of WARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Generalized Axiom of Revealed Preference (GARP).
 We say that a dataset satisfies GARP if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{*}y$
\end_inset

 (x is revealed preferredindirectly to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, there exists a chain of items 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x^{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{D}x^{1}\succeq^{D}\cdots\succeq^{D}x^{n}\succeq^{D}y$
\end_inset

) it is not the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ^{D}x$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is directly and strictly revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we will prove the main result of this chapter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) The choice structure/dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{B},c)$
\end_inset

 satisfies GARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) The choice structure/dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{B},c)$
\end_inset

 can be rationalized by a rational preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Sufficiency.
 (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 (ii)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First define 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ^{*}$
\end_inset

 as the asymmetric part of the revealed preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq^{*}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ^{*}b$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succeq^{*}b$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succeq^{*}a$
\end_inset

.
 GARP implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ^{D}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice as well that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq^{*}$
\end_inset

 is in the transitive closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq^{D}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we can use Proposition 1 in Chapter 1 (order theory) to claim that
 there exists a complete and transitive preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{*}y$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ^{D}y$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in c(A)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{D}y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in A$
\end_inset

, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin c(A)$
\end_inset

 implies that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ^{D}x$
\end_inset

, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ x$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $c(A)=\{x\in A|x\succeq y\quad\forall y\in A\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Necessity.
 (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

(i)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume towards contradiction that GARP fails and the dataset is rationalized
 by a rational preference 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq^{*}y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ^{D}x$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

, but because this is the result of maximizing a rational preference 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ x$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, this implies there is a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1},x^{2},\cdots,x^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\succeq x^{1}\succeq x^{2}\succeq\cdots\succeq x^{n}\succeq y\succ x,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this is a violation of transitivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,d,e\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a,b\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b,d\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a,d\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{a,b\})=\{a\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{b,d\})=\{b\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{a,d\})=\{a\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ^{D}b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succ^{D}d$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $d\succ^{D}a$
\end_inset

 (GARP holds).
 My preference relation is 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ^{*}b\succ^{*}d$
\end_inset

.
 The previous theorem implies the existence of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 (complete and transitive on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

), in fact, we verify this by construction 
\begin_inset Formula $e\succ a\succ b\succ d$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Now generate a choice correspondence, that fails GARP.
 Generate a choice correspondence that satisfies WARP but fails GARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{a,b\})=\{a\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{b,c\})=\{b\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\{a,c\})=\{c\}$
\end_inset

 fails GARP because 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ^{D}b\succ^{D}c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\succ^{D}a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Consumer Theory: Utility Maximization.
 (Ch.
 3).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq1$
\end_inset

 is the number of goods and it fixed.
 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\mathbb{R}_{++}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Demand Correspondences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Walrasian demand correspondence is a mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $x:P\times W\mapsto2^{X}\backslash\emptyset$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $x\in x(p,w),x\in X)$
\end_inset

 they must be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\prime}x\leq w$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Observe that using Ch 4.
 notation a choice correspondence is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $c:\mathcal{B}\to2^{X}\setminus\emptyset$
\end_inset

, now we define the budget correspondence as 
\begin_inset Formula $B:P\times W\to X$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)=\{x\in X|p'x\leq w\}$
\end_inset

, now we define the demand correspondence as the composition of this two
 correspondences 
\begin_inset Formula $x=c\circ B$
\end_inset

, (
\begin_inset Formula $P\times W\to^{B}\mathcal{B}\to^{c}2^{X}\setminus\emptyset$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can illustrate this concept with the following example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(p_{1},p_{2},w)=w/p_{1}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}<p_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(p_{1},p_{2},w)=w/p_{2}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}<p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p_{1},p_{2},w)\equiv[0,w/p_{i}]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Continuity (notion): Continuity for functions was defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{n},w^{n})\rightarrow(p,w)$
\end_inset

 then the condition was 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p^{n},w^{n})\rightarrow x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Continuity for Correspondences: The map is closed, the graph of the corresponden
ce is closed and Upper Hemi-continuity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 be a choice correspondence.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{n},w^{n})\rightarrow(p,w)$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in x(p^{n},w^{n})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 Then it has to be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Properties of the image of the correspondence.
 
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is called compact valued if 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is a compact set for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is convex valued iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha z+(1-\alpha)y\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $z,y\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Utility Representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Continuity 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are continuous if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is a continuous rational preference on 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 then there is a continuous utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we provide the following intermediate result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y\iff u(x)\geq u(y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is a rational preference on 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{Q}^{L}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 the rational numbers) then there is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(x)=\{y\in\mathbb{Q}^{L}|x\succeq y\}$
\end_inset

 be the lower contour set of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(x)$
\end_inset

 is a countable set, moreover it is countably infinite, thus we can define
 an indexed set 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\succeq}(x)\subseteq\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that there is an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (bijection) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:L^{\succeq}(x)\twoheadrightarrow N^{\succeq}(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we define a candidate utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=0+\sum_{i\in N^{\succeq}(x)}\frac{1}{2^{i}}=\frac{1}{2^{1}}+\frac{1}{2^{2}}+\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq u(y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

, by transitivity, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(x)\supseteq L^{\succeq}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\succeq}(x)\supseteq N^{\succeq}(y)$
\end_inset

, then given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2^{i}}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq u(y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq u(y)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq u(y)$
\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)-u(y)\geq0$
\end_inset

, this in turn means 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in N^{\succeq}(x)\backslash N^{\succeq}(y)}\frac{1}{2^{i}}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in N^{\succeq}(x)\backslash N^{\succeq}(y)}\frac{1}{2^{i}}=0$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\succeq}(x)=N^{\succeq}(y)$
\end_inset

, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(x)=L^{\succeq}(y)$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in N^{\succeq}(x)\backslash N^{\succeq}(y)}\frac{1}{2^{i}}>0$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\succeq}(x)\supset N^{\succeq}(y)$
\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succ y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude that in general, it must be that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq u(y)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
E.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(x)=\{x,x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},\cdots\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\succeq}(x)=\{1,2,3,4,\cdots\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can prove the main result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the previous representation Theorem, I know that a rational preference
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{L}$
\end_inset

 have a utility representation 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\mathbb{Q}^{L}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, in fact, I can also think of the same utility restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\mathbb{Q}^{L}\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, also 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{L}$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that any point in 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is either in 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, or there is a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, it converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first try would be to define a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $v:\mathbb{\mathbb{R}}^{L}\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, in the following way 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)=lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}u(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x\in X$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\succeq x^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is defined as in the previous lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{n})\geq u(x^{n-1})$
\end_inset

 and second 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{n})\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (we have a monotone and bounded sequence).
 I define a new utility function as 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)=lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}u(x^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\succeq y$
\end_inset

 and pick a pair of sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\succeq y^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n},y^{n}\in\mathbb{Q}^{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{n}\rightarrow y$
\end_inset

.
 By continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 we are sure that such sequences exist, because the continuity assumption
 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}x^{n}\succeq lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}y^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By the previous lemma, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{n})\geq u(y^{n})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 By definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)=lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}u(x^{n})$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x)\geq v(y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rubinstein.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another candidate for a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $w:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 respresents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=sup\{u(y)|x\succeq y|y\in\mathbb{Q}^{L}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continuity follows from Debreu's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Gap Theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Utility Maximization Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is continuous and 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utility maximization problem (UMP) is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x\geq0}u(x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad p'x\leq w.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively we can define the restriction as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B(p,w)=\{x\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:p'x\leq w\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is continuous, then the UMP has a solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Check 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is compact, in this case it is equivalent to proving that it is closed
 and bounded.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is bounded because 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}\leq w/p_{l}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 It is closed because 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x^{n}\leq w$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

 it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}p'x^{n}\leq lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}w$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then by the maximum theorem we know that the UMP has a solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now prove further properties of the demand corespondence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The Marshallian demand correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)\equiv argmax_{y}\{u(y)|y\in B(p,w)\}$
\end_inset

 is non-empty, compact valued and upper hemi-continuous.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=u(x)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 (i.e., the indirect utility) is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The results follows trivially from Berge's Theorem if we verify that the
 correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a continuous correspondence.
 We already know that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is continuous and that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is a compact set, thus making the 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 correspondence compact valued.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{n}=(p^{n},w^{n})$
\end_inset

 now assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{n}\rightarrow z$
\end_inset

, now we want to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(z^{n})\rightarrow B(z)$
\end_inset

 where the convergence in in terms sets.
 Recall that, 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p^{n},w^{n})=\{x\in X|p^{n\prime}x\leq w^{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in B(z^{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

 then we prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B(z)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in B(z^{n})$
\end_inset

 it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n\prime}x\leq w^{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, applying the limits over this inequality we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{n},w^{n})\rightarrow(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B(z)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $z=(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B(z)$
\end_inset

 then there is a subsequence of the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{k}\in B(z^{n,k})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{k}\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

.
 The proof is more complicated and it can be seen in Border Example 30 p11.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://people.hss.caltech.edu/~kcb/Notes/Correspondences.pdf
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With that in hand we apply Berge's theorem to obtain our conclusion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need some definitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Local non-satiation.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are locally non-satiated whenever for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there exists another commodity bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $||x-y||\leq\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\succ x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Assume that the Marshallian demand correspondence is generated by maximizing
 a locally non-satiated utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 has the following properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) Homogeneous of degree zero in 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\alpha p,\alpha w)=x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 for any scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) Walras' law 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x=w$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) Convexity/uniqueness: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is convex (
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is quasiconcave), then 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is convex valued.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is strictly convex so that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is strictly quasiconcave then 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is a single element.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
KKT Conditions for the UMP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are going to see how to find the solution under the differentiability
 assumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write the KKT
\series bold
 FOC
\series default
 necessary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}=u(x)+\lambda(w-p'x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{l}}u(x_{l}^{*})\leq\lambda^{*}p_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}^{*}[\partial_{x_{l}}u(x_{l}^{*})-\lambda^{*}p_{l}]=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $l\in\{1,\cdots,L\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $w-p'x^{*}\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{*}(w-p'x^{*})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a system with 
\begin_inset Formula $L+1$
\end_inset

 unknowns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to simplify a little bit the problem.
 By local non-satiation we know that the consumer is on the budget hyperplane
 (frontier).
 This means that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w-p'x^{*}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Also we are going to assume that the solution in the interior (positive
 quantities), this means that the KKT conditions are reduced to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial_{x_{l}}u(x^{*})}{\partial_{x_{k}}u(x^{*})}=\frac{p_{l}}{p_{k}}\quad\forall l,k\in\{1,\cdots,L\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the budget line and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\partial_{x_{1}}u(x^{*})}{\partial_{x_{2}}u(x^{*})}$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the indifference curve, usually this is also referred as
 the MRS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Properties of the the Indirect Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The indirect utility is the maximal utility achieved given the budget constraint
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=max_{x\geq0}u(x)$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively it is the utility evaluated in the Marshallian demand 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=u(x(p,w))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a continuous utility function representing a locally nonsatiated preference
 relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 defined on the consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The indirect utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
1.
 Homogeneity of degree zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and non-increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is quasiconvex in 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(p,w)|v(p,w)\leq\overline{v}\}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
4.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 2.
 and 4.
 are consequences of previous results presented here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 is the only non-trivial part of the proof.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)\leq\overline{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p',w')\leq\overline{v}$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, consider then 
\begin_inset Formula $(p'',w'')=(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p',\alpha w+(1-\alpha)w')$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p'',w'')\leq\overline{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(p'')\cdot x\leq w''$
\end_inset

 it is the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\leq\overline{v}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $(p'')\cdot x\leq w''$
\end_inset

 then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p')\cdot x\leq\alpha w+(1-\alpha)w'.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that either 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x\leq w$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(p')\cdot x\leq w'$
\end_inset

 (it can be both).
 If the former inequality holds, then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\leq v(p,w)\leq\overline{v}$
\end_inset

, and we have the result.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(p')\cdot x\leq w'$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\leq v(p',w')\leq\overline{v}$
\end_inset

 then the same conclusion follow.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Roy's Identity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall the definition of indirect utility 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=u(x(p,w))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the Envelope's theorem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=max_{x\geq0}u(x)+\lambda(w-p'x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{w}v(p,w)=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{p}v(p,w)=-\lambda x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This provides the Roy's identity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(p,w)=-\frac{\nabla_{p}v(p,w)}{\partial_{w}v(p,w)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Imagine I want to model a data set 
\begin_inset Formula $((p_{l}^{t})_{l=1}^{L},(x_{l}^{t})_{l=1}^{L})_{t\in T}$
\end_inset

 with no income effects (quasilinear).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{l}(p_{1}^{t},\cdots,p_{l}^{t})=x_{l}^{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{l}=\alpha_{o}^{l}+\sum_{k=1}^{L}\alpha_{k}^{l}p_{k}^{\beta_{k}^{l}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model 2: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(p_{1}^{t},\cdots,p_{L}^{t})=\sum_{k}\sum_{l}\alpha_{l,k}p_{l}^{1/2}p_{k}^{1/2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{l}=\partial_{p_{l}}v(p_{1}^{t},\cdots,p_{L}^{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Expenditure Minimization Problem (EMP)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Expenditure Minimization Problem (EMP) asks the question, if prices
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, what is the minimum amount the consumer would have to spend to achieve
 utility level 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}$
\end_inset

.
 That is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
min_{x\geq0}p'x
\]

\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)\geq\overline{u}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a continuous utility function representing a locally nonsatiated preference
 relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 defined on the consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and the price vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

.
 We have.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 is optimal in the UMP when 
\begin_inset Formula $w>0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 is optimal in the EMP when the required level of utility is 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the minimized expenditure level 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x^{*}=w$
\end_inset

 is exacly the wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 is optimal in the EMP when the required level of utility is 
\begin_inset Formula $u>u(0)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 is optimal in the UMP when wealth is 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the maximized utility level 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{*})=u$
\end_inset

 is exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We omit the proof.
 For details go to Chapter of MGW.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Expenditure function is 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,u)=p'x^{*}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 is an element in the solution to the EMP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a continuous utility function representing a locally non-satiated preference
 relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 defined on the consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,u)$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) Homogeneous of degree one in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula $min_{x\geq}\alpha p'x$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\geq\overline{u}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) Strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and non-decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) Concave in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iv) Continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $p,u$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i),(ii) are omitted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) Concavity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,u)$
\end_inset

 is concave in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})\geq\alpha e(p,\overline{u})+(1-\alpha)e(p',\overline{u}),$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
when 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\alpha}=\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p'$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 be the minimizer of the EMP, we abuse notation and let it denote any element
 of the set of optimizers at the given prices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})=p^{\alpha}\cdot h(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\alpha p\cdot h(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})+(1-\alpha)(p')\cdot h(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,\overline{u})=p\cdot h(p,\overline{u})\leq p\cdot h(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})$
\end_inset

, and we can conclude that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e(p^{\alpha},\overline{u})\ge\alpha p\cdot h(p,\overline{u})+(1-\alpha)(p')\cdot h(p',\overline{u}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iv) Continuity in 
\begin_inset Formula $p,u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows from the Berge's Maximum Theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the problem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x\geq0}-p'x\quad s.t.\quad u(x)\geq\overline{u}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First note that the budget constraint is not a compact-valued correspondence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We observe that the above problem is equivalent to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x\geq0}-p'x\quad s.t.\quad u(x)=\overline{u}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
since the problem is minimizing the expenditure we can create a non-binding
 upper bound, and by continuity we can make it equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 (no excess utility).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{u}$
\end_inset

 (thus a continuous correspondence, that is singled valued and therefore
 compact valued).
 Given that 
\begin_inset Formula $-p'x$
\end_inset

 is also a continuous function in the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we conclude by the Berge's maximum theorem that 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,\overline{u})=p'x^{*}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}\in h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $p,\overline{u}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hicksian Compensated Demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hicksian Compensated Demand or Hicksian demand is 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,u)=argmin_{x\geq0,u(x)\geq\overline{u}}p'x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is continuous and it represents a locally non-satiated preference relation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 Then the Hicksian demand correspondence 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,u)$
\end_inset

 has the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) HD0 in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) No excess utility: For 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}\in h(p,u)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{*})=\overline{u}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) Convexity/Uniqueness: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,u)$
\end_inset

 is a convex set, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is strictly convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,u)$
\end_inset

 is a unique element.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
KKT Conditions for the EMP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is twice continously differentiable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian for this problem is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{EMP}=p'x-\lambda(u(x)-\overline{u}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FOC are given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\geq\lambda\nabla_{x}u(x^{*})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{l}^{*}[p_{l}-\lambda\nabla u(x^{*})_{l}]=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sheppard's Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{p}e(p,\overline{u})=h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We apply the envelope's theorem for constrained problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(p,\overline{u})=p'h+\lambda^{*}(u(h)-\overline{u})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We derive with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla_{p}e(p,\overline{u})=h(p,\overline{u})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Additional Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $L\times L$
\end_inset

 matrix of derivatives of prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The Hicksian demand function has the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)=\mathcal{H}e(p,u)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative with respect to prices of the Hicksian demand is the Hessian
 of the expenditure function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a NSD matrix.
 This follows from the fact that a Hessian of a concave function is NSD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Young's theorem (continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}h(p,u)p=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows from HD0 of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and Euler's identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Summary of Relationships between the EMP and UMP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
expenditure function 
\series default
is the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,\overline{u})=p'h(p,\overline{u})$
\end_inset

 value attained at the given prices and target utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a 
\series bold
duality relation
\series default
 between the EMP and the UMP that we will not explore at this point.
 However, we will state the following relations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(p,v(p,w))=x(p,w)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(p,e(p,u))=h(p,u).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{u}=v(p,e(p,\overline{u}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w=e(p,v(p,w)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Slutsky Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We establish now a very useful equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(p,u)=x(p,e(p,u))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiating with respect ot 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{p}h(p,u)=D_{p}x(p,e(p,u))+D_{w}x(p,e(p,u))\nabla_{p}e(p,u)'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Sheppard's lemma and by the identities that relate the expenditure and
 wealth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{p}h(p,v(p,w))=D_{p}x(p,w)+D_{w}x(p,w)x(p,w)'.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Summary of the Implications of Utility Maximization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If a demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is generated by maximizing rational preferences that are locally non-satiated
 subject to a linear budget constraint.
 Then: (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 satisfies Walras' law, (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Moreover, its Slutsky matrix function 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is: (i) Negative semidefinite.
 (ii) Singular in prices 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)p=0$
\end_inset

, (iii) Symmetric 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)=S(p,w)'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This proposition summarizes our previous results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Integrability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now interested in what are the sufficient conditions for integrability.
 That is given an observed demand function we want to be sure that there
 exists a utility function that generates the data.
 We saw in the first chapter that for rich data and finite choice sets.
 The WARP was necessary and sufficient for rationalizability of a choice
 correspondence.
 Here in the world of the consumer, where not all choice sets are allowed
 but only competitive budgets sets (linear budget constraints), we need
 further conditions.
 This conditions will be given in terms of the Slutsky matrix of the demand
 function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, we assume in this subsection that the demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is continously differentiable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the Slutsky matrix function is 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)=D_{p}x(p,w)+D_{w}x(p,w)x(p,w)'$
\end_inset

, or in the scalar version 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ij}(p,w)=\partial_{p_{j}}x_{i}(p,w)+\partial_{w}x_{i}(p,w)x_{j}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in\{1,\cdots,L\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(Hurwicz-Uzawa/Richter) Assume that (a) Walras' law holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 (b) The Slutsky matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,w$
\end_inset

, that is 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)=S(p,w)'$
\end_inset

.
 (c) The Slutsky matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)\leq0$
\end_inset

 negative semi definite.
 Then there exists a continous utility function, differentiable that generates
 the data (i.e., the demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x=argmax_{q\geq0}u(q)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $p'q=w$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

(Sketch) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Given condition (b) or the symmetry of the Slutsky matrix.
 We conclude that there is a solution to the differential equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\mu(p)}{\partial p_{i}}=x_{i}(p,\mu(p))\forall i\in\{1,\cdots,L\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For initial conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(p^{0})=w^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The solution depends on the initial conditions so it is written 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(p;p^{0},w^{0})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Use the solution to 1, to define a candidate indirect utility (a solution
 exists if 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric -Frobenious Theorem, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(p^{*};p,w)$
\end_inset

 is continuous on the second argument and differentiable).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(p,w)=\mu(p^{*};p,w).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Recall duality said that 
\begin_inset Formula $w=e(p,v(p,w))$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,e(p,u))=u$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I use the NSD restriction to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is HD0, and quasi-convex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Invert the demand function to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 Define the utility on the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)=\mu(p^{*},p(x),w(x))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
 Use the (c) or NSD condition to conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a good faith utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
Some textbooks require a boundedness condition on the elasticity of wealth,
 this is in general not required.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Examples and Applications of the Integrability of Demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two commodities 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2$
\end_inset

 and you estimate a demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(p,w)=\frac{\alpha w}{p_{1}}$
\end_inset

, and you know that the demand of good two is given as a residual.
 Furthermore, we have checked that this demand satisfies WARP and therefore
 it is HD0, we normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=(1-\alpha)w.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $L-1$
\end_inset

 differential equation is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu'(p_{1},1)=\frac{\alpha\mu(p_{1},1)}{p_{1}}=x_{1}((p_{1},1),\mu((p_{1},1))),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for short, we can write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu'(p_{1})=\frac{\alpha\mu(p_{1})}{p_{1}}=x_{1}(p_{1},\mu(p_{1})),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can write more simply:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mu'}{\mu}=\frac{\alpha}{p_{1}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simple integration provides a family of solutions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ln\mu=\alpha lnp_{1}+C,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and in levels:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=Kp_{1}^{\alpha},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $K=exp(C)$
\end_inset

 a constant of integration.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given some initial conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{1}^{0},w^{0})$
\end_inset

, we must have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w^{0}=K(p_{1}^{0})^{\alpha},\quad K=\frac{w^{0}}{(p_{1}^{0})^{\alpha}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(p_{1}^{*};p_{1}^{0},w^{0})=\frac{w^{0}}{(p_{1}^{0})^{\alpha}}(p_{1}^{*})^{\alpha}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's define the indirect utility, with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}^{*}=1$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(p_{1},w)=\mu(p^{*},p_{1},w)=\frac{w}{p_{1}^{\alpha}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recover the utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, we need to invert the demand, note that our primitive is indeed invertible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have to use the demand function and obtain the inverse demand:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}(p,w)=\frac{\alpha w}{p_{1}};\quad x_{2}(p,w)=(1-\alpha)w
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}=\frac{\alpha}{(1-\alpha)}\frac{1}{p_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}=\frac{\alpha}{1-\alpha}\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}},\quad w=\frac{x_{2}}{1-\alpha}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replacing back in the indirect utility we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x_{1},x_{2})=v\circ(p_{1},w)(x_{1},x_{2})=v(\frac{\alpha}{1-\alpha}\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}},\frac{x_{2}}{1-\alpha}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x_{1},x_{2})=\frac{\frac{x_{2}}{1-\alpha}}{\left(\frac{\alpha}{1-\alpha}\frac{x_{2}}{x_{1}}\right)^{\alpha}}=\left(\frac{x_{2}}{1-\alpha}\right)^{1-\alpha}\left(\frac{x_{1}}{\alpha}\right)^{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x_{1},x_{2})=\hat{c}x_{1}^{\alpha}x_{2}^{1-\alpha},\quad\hat{c}=(1-\alpha)^{\alpha}\alpha^{\alpha}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a a Cobb Douglas Utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Generalized Axiom of Revealed Preference (GARP)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up to this point this chapter has had very little concern about the dataset
 that we have at hand.
 It is time to solve this.
 We assume that we observe a dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}=\{p^{k},x^{k}\}_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}$
\end_inset

 is directly revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}R^{D}x)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{t\prime}x^{t}\geq p^{t\prime}x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, we define an (indirect) notion of revealed preference.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}$
\end_inset

 is (indirectly) revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{t}Rx)$
\end_inset

 if and only if there is a sequence of commodities such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}R^{D}x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}R^{D}\cdots x^{n}R^{D}x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using some ideas from order theory we can as well that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the transitive closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{D}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous treatment of rationality we did not allowed for correspondences,
 we only allowed for functions.
 But what happens for cases when we observe for the same prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{t}=p^{s}$
\end_inset

 different demand choices 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}\neq x^{s}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{t\prime}x^{t}=p^{s\prime}x^{s}$
\end_inset

, recall that this is a case where from the same budget set two different
 choice bundles are chosen (this can be seen as the case of a correspondence
 generating the data).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $O=\{p^{k},x^{k}\}_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

 is said to satisfies GARP if an only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 admits Only Weak Cycles (OWC), i.e., if 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}R\cdots R^{D}x^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}R^{D}x^{1}$
\end_inset

 then it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}Ix^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the symmetric part of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}Rx^{s}$
\end_inset

 then it cannot be that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s\prime}x^{s}>p^{s\prime}x^{t}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(Afriat's Theorem) Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}=\{p^{k},x^{k}\}_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

, the following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
1.
 There exists a locally nonsatiated utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 that rationalizes the data in the sense that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{k})\geq u(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k\prime}x^{k}\geq p^{k\prime}x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
2.
 The dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}=\{p^{k},x^{k}\}_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

 satisfies GARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
3.
 There exist a positive solution 
\begin_inset Formula $(u^{t},\lambda^{t})$
\end_inset

 to the set of linear inequalites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u^{t}\leq u^{s}+\lambda^{s}p^{s\prime}(x^{t}-x^{s})\forall s,t\in\{1,\cdots,K\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
4.
 There exists a continuous, concave, and strictly monotonic, utility function
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 that rationalizes the data in the sense that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{k})\geq u(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k\prime}x^{t}\geq p^{k\prime}x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we present the proof, notice that (4) implies (3) because of first-order-
conditions arguments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is concave then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{t})\leq u(x^{s})+\nabla u(x^{s})'(x^{t}-x^{s})$
\end_inset

.
 Given that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is assumed smooth 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla u$
\end_inset

 exists (super-gradient for concave functions).
 Now, by the FOC of the UMP we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla u(x^{s})\leq\lambda^{s}p^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{t})\leq u(x^{s})+\lambda^{s}p^{s\prime}(x^{t}-x^{s})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{t})=u^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(1)\implies(2),(2)\implies(3),(3)\implies(4),(4)\implies(1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

) implies (2), 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 is rationalized by a nonsatiated utility function and that GARP fails,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}Rx^{2}\cdots Rx^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}P^{D}x^{1}$
\end_inset

 with strict preference for the last one, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{1})\geq u(x^{2})\geq\cdots\geq u(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 and also that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n\prime}x^{n}>p^{n\prime}x^{1}$
\end_inset

 but this means that there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $||y-x^{1}||<\epsilon$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n\prime}x^{n}>p^{n\prime}y$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y)>u(x^{1})$
\end_inset

 by local nonsatiation.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y)>u(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}$
\end_inset

 cannot be a maximizer for budget 
\begin_inset Formula $B(p^{n},p^{n\prime}x^{n})$
\end_inset

, this is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(2)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(3)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Algorithm: Input: A set of price-quantity observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 satisfying GARP.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Output: Numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{t}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{T}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the inequalities in statement (i).
 
\begin_inset Formula $n=K$
\end_inset

 number of observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\{1,...,n\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\max(I)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\{i\in I:x^{i}\succeq^{R}x^{m}\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then set 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{m}=\lambda^{m}=1$
\end_inset

 and go to step 6; else go to step 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{m}=\min_{i\in E}\min_{j\in B}\min\{U^{j}+\lambda^{j}p^{j}(x^{i}-x^{j}),U^{j}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{m}=\max_{i\in E}\max_{j\in B}\max\{(U^{j}-U^{m}/(p^{i}(x^{j}-x^{i})),1\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I\setminus E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=B\cup E$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then stop; otherwise, go to step 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We now prove that this algorithm generates numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{t}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in K$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the inequalities in statement (i).
 From step 4, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U^{m}\le U^{j}+\lambda^{j}p^{j}(x^{m}-x^{j}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda^{m}\geq(U^{j}-U^{m})/p^{m}(x^{j}-x^{m}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m,j\in K$
\end_inset

.
 This implies: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U^{j}-U^{m}\leq\lambda^{m}p^{m}(x^{j}-x^{m}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m,j\in$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, this shows that the algorithm guarantees that there exist numbers
 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{t}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in K$
\end_inset

 satisfying the inequalities in statement (3).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(3)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(4)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=min_{t\in\{1,\cdots,K\}}\{u^{t}+\lambda^{t}p^{t\prime}(x-x^{t})\}$
\end_inset

, this function is continuous in 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and concave, it is also strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{t}>0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{t}>>0$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 rationalizes the dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First check that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{t})=u^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{t})=u^{m}+\lambda^{m}p^{m\prime}(x^{t}-x^{m})\leq u^{t}$
\end_inset

, but this means that the Afriat's inequality for 
\begin_inset Formula $m,t$
\end_inset

 fails.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{t})=u^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{m}-u^{t}\leq\lambda^{m}p^{m\prime}(x^{m}-x^{t})$
\end_inset

 this violates (3).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)\leq u(x^{s})$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s\prime}x^{s}\geq p^{s\prime}x\cdot$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s\prime}x^{s}\geq p^{s\prime}x$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s\prime}(x^{s}-x)\geq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=min_{t}\{u^{t}+\lambda^{t}p^{t\prime}(x-x^{t})\}\leq u^{s}+\lambda^{s}p^{s}(x-x^{s})\leq u^{s}=u(x^{s})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{s})\geq u(x)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s\prime}x^{s}\geq p^{s\prime}x\cdot$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(4)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is stricty monotononic then it is locally nonsatiated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Revealed Preference Theory / Strong Axiom of Revealed Preference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Strong Axiom of Revealed Preference -SARP-) The revealed preference relation
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is acyclic, i.e., If 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}Rx^{s}$
\end_inset

 then it is not the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}R^{D}x^{t}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $t\neq s$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a result by Afriat/Varian/Houtaker.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(Afriat's Theorem) Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}=\{p^{k},x^{k}\}_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

, the following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
1.
 There exists a continuous, nonsatiated utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, strictly concave that rationalizes the data in the sense that for all
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{k})>u(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq x^{k}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k\prime}x^{k}\geq p^{k\prime}x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
2.
 The dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}=\{p^{k},x^{k}\}_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

 satisfies SARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
3.
 There exist a positive solution 
\begin_inset Formula $(u^{t},\lambda^{t})$
\end_inset

 to the set of linear inequalites
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u^{t}<u^{s}+\lambda^{s}p^{s\prime}(x^{t}-x^{s})\forall s,t\in\{1,\cdots,K\},s\neq t
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(If am able to solve for: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=\{u^{t}\}_{t=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\lambda}=\{\lambda^{t}\}_{t=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Forecasting: Varian Support Set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Varian's Support Set.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p^{K+1},w^{K+1})=\{x\in X:\mathcal{O}\cup\{p^{K+1},x\},\quad satisfy\quad GARP;\quad p^{K+1}x=w^{K+1}\}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of demand observations that given a new price level 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{K+1}$
\end_inset

 is such that GARP still holds in the extended dataset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S(p^{K+1},w^{K+1})$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{K+1}x<p^{K+1}x^{t}$
\end_inset

 for all cases such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}Px$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{K+1}x=w^{K+1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Upper Bounds to Welfare Analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A money metric utility function is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $m(p,x)=e(p,u(x))$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the expenditure function that corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p,u)=minp'x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=u$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any given 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m(p,x)$
\end_inset

 is a utility function that represents the same preferences as 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 but is expressed in money units.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a finite dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 we Varian suggested an upper bound for the money metric utility using:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m^{+}(p,x)=min_{t}px^{t},\quad s.t.x^{t}Rx.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experiments about Testing Rationality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(This material is presented in Quah
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://www.johnquah.com/uploads/7/5/6/7/75676677/survey-qutweb.pdf
\end_layout

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Data from the portfolio choice experiment in Choi, Fisman, Gale, and Kariv
 (AER, 2007).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
93 undergraduate subjects participated in the experiment at UC Berkeley,
 each completing 50 decision problems under risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There were two states of the world, each occurring with a known probability,
 and two Arrow-Debreu securities, one for each state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In each decision problem, every subject was given a budget; income was normalize
d to one and state prices were chosen at random.
 47 subjects were subjected to the symmetric treatment, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}=\pi_{2}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The rest had the asymmetric treatment where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}=\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}=\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

 (or vice versa).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the symmetric treatment, 12/47 pass GARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the asymmetric treatment, 4/46 pass GARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Roughly 17% pass GARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../WesternAP/FirstYear/MicroI/notes/figures/rationality_experiment.png
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Subject 216 (symmetric treatment).
 Source: Quah.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Afriat's Cost Efficiency Index: Rationality Measures of Performance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose a dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 cannot be rationalized by any 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 (GARP/SARP fails).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider the case where we shrink budget sets implied by 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 by an efficiency index 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]:$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let me define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p^{t\prime}x^{t}\geq p^{t\prime}x^{s}\iff x^{t}R_{\alpha}^{D}x^{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I have a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 that fails rationality and in particular I observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}R^{D}x^{2}P^{D}x^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}/\{p^{1},x^{1}\}$
\end_inset

 this satisfies GARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that every dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

will satisfy GARP(
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

) for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, find the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{*}=\max\{\alpha:\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 satisfies GARP on 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

}.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then every dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 can be 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-rationalized if we find 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x^{t})\geq u(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B^{t}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $B^{t}(\alpha)=\{x\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}:p^{t\prime}x\leq\alpha p^{t\prime}x^{t}\}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The Critical Cost Efficiency Index (CCEI) of a data set 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{*}=sup\{\alpha:a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in A$
\end_inset

 if there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 that rationalizes the data 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\alpha)=\{B^{t}(\alpha),x^{t}\}_{t=0}^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 It amounts to checking SARP/GARP for a grid of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values and checking whether it rationalizes the data.
 The supremum of those 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 numbers is the CCEI.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, what is the CCEI distribution in the case of the above experiment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../WesternAP/FirstYear/MicroI/notes/figures/CCEI_Afriat_index.png
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
CCEI Source: Quah
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Measurement Error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar experiment of budget allocation but using 3 goods instead of 2,
 is in Ahn, D., Choi, S., Gale, D., & Kariv, S.
 (2014) (Estimating ambiguity aversion in a portfolio choice experiment.
 Quantitative Economics, 5(2), 195223).
 This experiment has 
\begin_inset Formula $n=154$
\end_inset

 individuals, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T=50$
\end_inset

 trials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The GARP test is successful 
\begin_inset Formula $12.99\%$
\end_inset

 of cases (individuals).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aguiar and Kashaev (2020, Restud) extend GARP to allow for measurement error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Measurement error can be either present in consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}=x_{t}^{*}+w_{t}^{c}$
\end_inset

 or in prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}=p_{t}^{*}+w_{t}^{p}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}^{*},p_{t}^{*}$
\end_inset

 being the correctly measured prices and consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GARP should hold for the (ideal), well-measured data set 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{t}^{*},x_{t}^{*})_{t=1}^{T}$
\end_inset

 but not necessarily for the mismeasured data set 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{t},x_{t})_{t=1}^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Without any knowledge about measurement error then rationality becomes untestabl
e.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We assume that measurement error is random across individuals and that the
 expectation is equal to zero: 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\boldsymbol{w}_{t}^{c}]=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\boldsymbol{w}_{t}^{p}]=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These assumptions are backed up by validation experimental data that shows
 that consumers may incur in trembling hand errors, or perception errors
 that are not systematic (see our paper).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The key is that we do not know the distribution of measurement error, we
 only know it's average behavior.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aguiar and Kashaev (2020) provide a methodology to test GARP in the ideal
 (correctly measured data) with knowledge about average behavior of measurement
 error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
They conclude that the null hypothesis that every individual in this experiment
 is consistent with GARP cannot be rejected at the 95 confidence level.
 They also find that misperception of prices seems to be the culprit of
 spurious violations of rationality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Does this confirm rationality? NO!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A theory cannot be confirmed by this exercise alone, but we say that current
 evidence is insufficient to reject rationality (at least in the context
 of this simple experiments).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Welfare Evaluation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will compare the wealth needed to achieve a certain level of utility
 at a given price-wealth pair.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u^{1}=v(p^{1},w)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u^{0}=v(p^{0},w).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in comparing the expenditure needed to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a fixed reference price and a given utility level 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, the needed expenditure to reach it is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(p^{ref},u).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the comparison in terms of expenditure is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(p^{ref},u^{1})-e(p^{ref},u^{0})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(p^{ref},v(p^{1},w))-e(p^{ref},v(p^{0},w)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expression will be positive when it takes more wealth to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{1}$
\end_inset

 at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ref}$
\end_inset

 than to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This difference is measured in dollar terms.
 That is why 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p^{ref},v(p,w))$
\end_inset

 is often called money metric indirect utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can construct many money metric indirect utility functions with different
 reference price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ref}=p^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the original price situation then the change is expenditure is equal
 to the change in wealth such that the consumer would be indifferent between
 the new price with the old wealth and the old price and the new wealth.
 This asks what change is wealth would be equivalent to the change in price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
equivalent variation is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
EV(p^{0},p^{1},w)=e(p^{0},v(p^{1},w))-e(p^{0},v(p^{0},w))=e(p^{0},v(p^{1},w))-w,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
since 
\begin_inset Formula $e(p^{0},v(p^{0},w))=w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Equivalent variation is the amount of money the consumer
\series bold
 is willing to pay 
\series default
to avoid a price change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other case considered is the one where the new price is taken as the
 reference price, when 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ref}=p^{1}$
\end_inset

, the change is expenditure is equal to the change in wealth such that the
 consumer is indifferent between the original situation 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{0},w)$
\end_inset

 and the new situation 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{1},w+\Delta w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
compensating variation 
\series default
is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CV(p^{0},p^{1},w)=e(p^{1},v(p^{1},w))-e(p^{1},v(p^{0},w))=w-e(p^{1},v(p^{0},w)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How much must I compensate you to make you as well off as you were before
 the price change? Willingness to accept (compensation).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Homothetic and Quasilinear Utility Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Homothetic Prefereces.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x\sim\alpha y$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if that is the case 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\alpha x)=\alpha u(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Examples: Cobb-Douglas 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=x_{1}^{\alpha}x_{2}^{1-\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Quasilinear Preferences.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x+e_{L}\alpha\succeq y$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{L}=(0,\cdots,0,\cdots1)'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utility function for quasilinear cases are 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=V(x_{1},\cdots,x_{L-1})+x_{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Behavioral Economics: The Sparse-Max Consumer (Xavier Gabaix, QJE 2014)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a generalization of the rational consumer model and most of
 the theory we have developed so far.
 Why we need this? There is evidence that the rationality assumption is
 not the best assumption to make.
 Thus it is an important question how relaxing this property affects our
 main results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main ingredient is a perceived price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s}$
\end_inset

 that may be different from actual prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Sparse max consumer.
 
\begin_inset Formula $smax_{x|p^{s}}u(x)$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sparse max operator is the given by the following process:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $max_{x}\mathcal{L}(x,p^{s},w,\lambda^{s})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}(x,p^{s},w,\lambda^{s})=u(x)+\lambda^{s}(w-p^{s\prime}x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p^{s},\lambda^{s})=argmax_{x}\mathcal{L}(x,p^{s},w,\lambda^{s})$
\end_inset

 for unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Find 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{s}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\prime}x(p^{s},\lambda^{s})=w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, this implies the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla_{x}u(x)=\lambda^{s}p^{s}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial_{x_{i}}u(x)}{\partial_{x_{j}}u(x)}=\frac{p_{j}^{s}}{p_{i}^{s}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Output: Solve the FOC above for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(p^{s},\lambda^{s})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p^{\prime}x(p^{s},\lambda^{s})=w.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies that there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $w'>0$
\end_inset

 such that the solution to the smax 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}(p,p^{s},w)=arg(smax)_{x|p^{s}}u(x)$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{s}(p,p^{s},w)=x^{r}(p^{s},w'),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x^{r}(p^{s},w')=w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{r}(\cdot)=argmax_{x}u(x)$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

, this is the solution to the UMP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{r}$
\end_inset

 is linear in wealth then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}(p,p^{s},w)=\frac{x^{r}(p^{s},w)}{p'x^{r}(p^{s},1)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x^{r}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is linear in wealth means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{r}(p,w)=x^{r}(p,1)w$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x^{r}(p^{s},w')=p\cdot x^{r}(p^{s},1)w'=w$
\end_inset

, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $w'=\frac{w}{p\cdot x^{r}(p^{s},1)}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, by our previous result we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,p^{s},w)=x^{r}(p^{s},w')$
\end_inset

, by linearity in wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,p^{s},w)=x^{r}(p^{s},1)w'=\frac{x^{r}(p^{s},1)w}{p\cdot x^{r}(p^{s},1)}$
\end_inset

, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,p^{s},w)=\frac{x^{r}(p^{s},w)}{p\cdot x^{r}(p^{s},1)}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have an important example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rational Cobb-Douglas demand: 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}(p,w)=\frac{\alpha w}{p_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Cobb-Douglas Sparse Max.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}^{s}(p,p^{s},w)=\frac{\alpha_{l}w}{p_{l}^{s}}\frac{1}{(\sum_{l}(\alpha_{l}p_{l})/p_{l}^{s})}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Verify Walras' law: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{l=1}^{L}p_{l}x_{l}^{s}(p,p^{s},w)=\sum_{l=1}^{L}\frac{\alpha_{l}w}{p_{l}^{s}}\frac{p_{l}}{(\sum_{l}(\alpha_{l}p_{l})/p_{l}^{s})}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=w\sum_{l=1}^{L}\frac{\alpha_{l}p_{l}}{p_{l}^{s}}\frac{1}{(\sum_{l}(\alpha_{l}p_{l})/p_{l}^{s})}=w.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s}=p$
\end_inset

 then we are back to the rational case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sparse max:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{s}=\alpha_{1}Lnx_{1}+\alpha_{2}Lnx_{2}+\lambda^{s}(w-p_{1}^{s}x_{1}-p_{2}^{s}x_{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FOC with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\alpha_{1}}{x_{1}}=\lambda^{s}p_{1}^{s}\implies x_{1}=\frac{1}{\lambda^{s}}\frac{\alpha_{1}}{p_{1}^{s}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\alpha_{2}}{x_{2}}=\lambda^{s}p_{2}^{s}\implies x_{2}=\frac{1}{\lambda^{s}}\frac{\alpha_{2}}{p_{2}^{s}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Look for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{s}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}(p^{s},\lambda^{s})+p_{2}x_{1}(p^{s},\lambda^{s})=w$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\lambda^{s}}\frac{\alpha_{1}}{p_{1}^{s}}p_{1}+\frac{1}{\lambda^{s}}\frac{\alpha_{2}}{p_{2}^{s}}p_{2}=w
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{s}=\frac{1}{w}(\sum_{l}(\alpha_{l}p_{l})/p_{l}^{s})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plug back 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{s}$
\end_inset

on the demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p^{s},\lambda^{s})$
\end_inset

 to obtain the sparse maximizer demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(p,w)=x_{l}^{s}(p,p^{s},w)=\frac{\alpha_{l}w}{p_{l}^{s}}\frac{1}{(\sum_{l}(\alpha_{l}p_{l})/p_{l}^{s})}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I can also use the proposition above and compute the sparse max CD:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w'=\frac{w}{p_{1}\frac{\alpha_{1}}{p_{1}^{s}}+p_{2}\frac{\alpha_{2}}{p_{2}^{s}}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{s}(p^{s},w')=\frac{\alpha w'}{p_{1}^{s}}=\frac{\alpha_{l}w}{p_{l}^{s}}\frac{1}{(\sum_{l}(\alpha_{l}p_{l})/p_{l}^{s})}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Perceived Price and Limited Attention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The perceived price is going to be modeled as an average of actual prices
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and default prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 Default prices, are what the consumer has in mind, maybe a forecast about
 prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{d}=E[\mathbf{p}]$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 is the distribution of prices in the market.
 More formally 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 can be the history of prices or the memory of the consumer about prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The linear model of perceived prices is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{l}^{s}(m,p,p^{d})=m_{l}p_{l}+(1-m_{l})p_{l}^{d},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{l}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 an attention parameter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer is rational when 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{l}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and he becomes more behavioral when 
\begin_inset Formula $m<1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=diag(\{m_{l}\}_{l=1}^{L})$
\end_inset

, the diagonal matrix of all attention parameters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have the following result.
 If we have any demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 then we can find a 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s}$
\end_inset

 and a 
\begin_inset Formula $w'$
\end_inset

 such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{r}(p^{s},w')=x(p,w).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s}$
\end_inset

 without restrictions is too general.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The Slutsky matrix of the sparse max is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{s}(p,w;p^{d})|_{p=p^{d}}=S^{r}(p,w)M$
\end_inset

 (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ij}^{s}=s_{ij}^{r}m_{j}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}(p,w)=x^{r}(\{p_{l}^{d},+m_{l}(p_{l}-p_{l}^{d})\}_{l=1}^{L},w'(p,p^{d}))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we derive with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}$
\end_inset

 and evaluate everything to 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p^{d}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{p_{l}}x^{s}(p,w)=\partial_{p_{l}}x^{r}(p,w)m_{l}+\partial_{w}x^{r}(p,w)\frac{\partial w'(p,p^{d})}{\partial p_{l}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x^{r}(p^{s},w'(p))=w$
\end_inset

, we differentiate with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $0=x_{l}^{r}+p\cdot\partial_{p_{l}}x^{r}m_{l}+p\cdot\partial_{w}c^{r}\partial_{p_{l}}w'$
\end_inset

.
 As, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x^{r}(p,w)=w$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}^{r}+p\cdot\partial_{p_{l}}x^{r}=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot\partial_{w}x^{r}=1$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $0=x_{l}^{r}-x_{l}^{r}m_{l}+\partial_{p_{l}}w'$
\end_inset

 thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{p_{l}}w'=(m_{l}-1)x_{l}^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{p_{l}}x^{s}(p,w)=\partial_{p_{l}}x^{r}m_{l}+\partial_{w}x^{r}(m_{l}-1)x_{l}^{r}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{w}x^{s}(p,w')=\partial_{w}x^{r}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p^{d}$
\end_inset

 and also we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}(p^{d},w'(p^{d},p^{d}))=x^{r}(p^{d},w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies that at 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p^{d}$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $w'(p^{d},p^{d})=w$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{p_{l}}x_{k}^{s}(p,w)+\partial_{w}x_{l}^{s}(p,w)x_{k}^{s}(p,w)=[\partial_{p_{l}}x_{k}^{r}(p,w)+\partial_{w}x_{l}^{r}(p,w)x_{k}^{r}(p,w)]m_{l}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S^{s}(p,w)|_{p=p^{d}}=S^{r}(p,w)|_{p=p^{d}}M.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S^{s}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is not singular in prices that is 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{s}(p,w)p\neq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a consequence of failures of homogeneity of degree zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S^{s}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is also not necessarily NSD, in fact the model 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 fails WARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{CB}(p,w)=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
s_{11} & s_{12}\\
s_{21} & s_{22}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{G,CB}(p,w,p^{s})|_{p=p^{d}}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
s_{11} & s_{12}\\
s_{21} & s_{22}
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
m_{1} & 0\\
0 & m_{2}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine that the consumer is fully inattentive to 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}=0$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{G,CB}(p,w,p^{s})|_{p=p^{d}}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
s_{11} & 0\\
s_{21} & 0
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Endogenizing Attention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that there is a true value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 distributed with normal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}(x^{d},\sigma_{x}^{2})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{d}$
\end_inset

 is the default value and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The agent does not know the true value and observes the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s=x+\epsilon$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is drawn from an independent distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The agent takes the action 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, the objective function is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(a,x)=-\frac{1}{2}(a-x)^{2},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rational
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{a}\mathbb{E}[-\frac{1}{2}(a-x)^{2}|s].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FOC are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\mathbb{E}[-(a-x)|s]=E[x|s]-a,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so the rational action is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{*}=E[x|s]=ms+(1-m)x^{d},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=\frac{\sigma_{x}^{2}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}+\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows from the Bayesian updating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Endogenizing attention means that I will pick the precision of the signal
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

, what is the value of the precision of the signal?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\sigma_{\epsilon})=\mathbb{E}_{N(0,\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2})}[\mathbb{E}[-\frac{1}{2}(a^{*}-x)^{2}|s]].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost is 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\sigma_{\epsilon})$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $C'(\cdot)<0$
\end_inset

 more precision more cost (i.e., more variance less cost).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the consumer chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 by solving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{\sigma_{\epsilon}}V(\sigma_{\epsilon})-C(\sigma_{\epsilon}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's simplify 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{d}=0$
\end_inset

, so we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[\max_{a}\mathbb{E}[-\frac{1}{2}(a-x)^{2}|s]]=-\frac{1}{2}(1-m)\sigma_{x}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that the agent's problem is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{m}-\frac{1}{2}(1-m)\sigma_{x}^{2}-C(m)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\frac{\sigma_{x}^{2}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}+\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and we can redefine the problem to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example of cost 
\begin_inset Formula $C(m)=\frac{1}{2}\log\frac{1}{1-m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2(1-m)}=\frac{\sigma_{X}^{2}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=\frac{-1+\sigma_{X}^{2}}{\sigma_{X}^{2}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this means that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}=\frac{\sigma_{x}^{2}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}^{2}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}$
\end_inset

=1 (De L'Hopitals rule).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another different model with a constrained attention capacity is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{m}-\frac{1}{2}(1-m)\sigma_{x}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}log(\frac{1}{1-m})\leq K.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to this problem is very different:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=1-e^{-2K},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
as the capacity becomes infinity then attention converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discrimination with rational inattention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine a firm looking to recruit someone for a job.
 You see the name of the applicant at the top of the CV and this tells you
 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clue
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to which 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

group
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the applicant belongs to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Red vs.
 Blue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You have some prior belief about the abilities of each of these groups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Red people are better than Blue people.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do you spend more time looking at the CVs of Red or Blue people?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, you will end up hiring an applicant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An applicant is of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, that the firms do not observe.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you hire the applicant the firm gets payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 otherwise you get 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Initially you see a signal telling you to which group the participant belongs
 to R vs.
 B.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If R (red applicant) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q\sim N(q_{R},\sigma^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 (blue applicant)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q\sim N(q_{B},\sigma^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{R}<q_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is your bias:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before deciding who to hire, you receive a signal 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=q+\epsilon
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\sim N(0,\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Importantly, 
\series default
the firm gets to choose the precision of the signal, and this precision
 is costly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C(\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}):C'(\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2})<0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The firms posterior beliefs after seeing the signal are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q'=\alpha y+(1-\alpha)q_{G},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in\{R,B\}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{\sigma^{2}+\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The more precise the signal, more weight is put on the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, else you put more weight on the average of the group (bias).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If attention was costless then the bias would not matter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hire if 
\begin_inset Formula $q'=\alpha y+(1-\alpha)q_{G}>0$
\end_inset

, otherwise not hire and earn 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected value over the distribution of signals is 
\begin_inset Formula $max\{\alpha y+(1-\alpha)q_{G},0\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the firm solves the following System 1 problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}}V(\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2})-C(\sigma_{\epsilon}^{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 the solution is hire the worker if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha y+(1-\alpha)q_{G}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cherry picking: 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{R}<q_{B}<0$
\end_inset

, only candidates with good signals are hired (job application).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lemon dropping: would hire the average candidate from either group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $0<q_{R}<q_{B}$
\end_inset

, only candidates with bad signals are not hired (renting an apartment).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
In Cherry Picking markets, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

worse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 group 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 gets less attention.
 Rational inattention hurts the worst group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Cherry Picking 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is smaller the bigger the group mean because 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{G}<0$
\end_inset

, so information is collected more precisely for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 than for 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If so, it's more likely that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is hired than under the situation where both groups get the same attention.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
In Lemon dropping markets, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

worse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 group 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 gets more attention.
 Rational inattention hurts the worst group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Lemon dropping 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is higher the smaller the group mean because 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{G}>0$
\end_inset

, so information is collected less precisely for 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 than for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If so, it's more likely that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is hired.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Choice under Uncertainty (Ch.
 6)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Dataset or Primitives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 to be a set of finite alternatives.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $p:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a probability distribution on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p(z)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{z\in Z}p(z)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 be the set of probability distributions on 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{z}\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 be the Dirach distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{z}(z)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This is also called degenerate lotteries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any two probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 and a number 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 we define a third probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula $[\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q](z)=\alpha p(z)+(1-\alpha)q(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We observe a choice structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B},C$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}\subseteq\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a choice correspondence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 has a expected utility representation if there exists a (Bernoulli) utility
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p):=\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)p(z)$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli utility is bounded and continuous and is defined over prices
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $p=(\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\{10,0\}=\{z_{1},z_{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula $V^{CD}(p)=p_{1}^{\alpha}p_{2}^{(1-\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 Cobb-Douglas is non-expected utility.
 Expected Utility: 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p)=p_{1}u(10)+p_{2}u(0)=\frac{1}{2}u(10)+\frac{1}{2}u(0)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preferences that are not rational.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stochastic dominance:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F_{Y}(y)=Pr(y\leq Y)=\sum_{z\in Z}1(z\geq y)p(z)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is going be distributed with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F_{X}(y)=\sum_{z\in Z}1(z\geq y)q(z)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is going to be distributed with 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\{10,0\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p=(1,0)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $q=(0,1)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 first order stochastic dominant to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\iff p\geq_{FOD}q$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F_{Y}(y)\leq F_{X}(y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\geq_{FOD}$
\end_inset

 is a binary relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 that is incomplete but transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Independence Axiom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are rational.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Independence Axiom) For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q,r\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p+(1-\alpha)r\succeq\alpha q+(1-\alpha)r.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other axiom that we need is more technical 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Mixture continuity) For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q,r\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ q\succ r$
\end_inset

, then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha\in[0,1]|\alpha p+(1-\alpha)r\succ q\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha\in[0,1]|q\succ\alpha p+(1-\alpha)r\}$
\end_inset

 are open in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Representation Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The rational preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Independence Axiom and Mixture continuity if and only if
 there exists a (Bernoulli) utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)p(z)\geq\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)q(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we prove that there is a linear representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
If the preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Independence Axiom and Mixture continuity then there is a
 linear function 
\begin_inset Formula $U:\Delta(Z)\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First find 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2}\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}\succeq p\succeq r_{2}$
\end_inset

 for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 To ensure that this 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2}$
\end_inset

 exists we use continuity and finiteness of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 The second step is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p)=\alpha_{p}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim\alpha_{p}r_{1}+(1-\alpha_{p})r_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 1.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q\succ q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows from the independence axiom, note that if we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ q$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q\succ\alpha q+(1-\alpha)q$
\end_inset

, finally notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q$
\end_inset

 by definition.
 Now by transitivity 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succ\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q\succ q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 2.
 Define the best lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{+}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{+}\succeq p$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and the worst lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{-}$
\end_inset

 (these two lotteries exists because 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 is transitive and complete and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 is a compact set).
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta p^{+}+(1-\beta)p^{-}\succ\alpha p^{+}+(1-\alpha)p^{-}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 3.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 there is a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}p^{+}+(1-\alpha_{p})p^{-}\sim p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Existence is a consequence of Mixture continuity.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{+}\succeq p\succeq p^{-}$
\end_inset

 then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha\in[0,1]|\alpha p^{+}+(1-\alpha)p^{-}\succeq p\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha\in[0,1]|p\succeq\alpha p^{+}+(1-\alpha)p^{-}\}$
\end_inset

 are closed thus there is a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{n}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 in the intersection of this sets that converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}p^{+}+(1-\alpha_{p})p^{-}\sim p$
\end_inset

.
 We know that a bounded sequence in a closed interval converges, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}$
\end_inset

 exists and is between 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Uniqueness comes due to Step 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 4.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p)=\alpha_{p}$
\end_inset

 represents the preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By step 3, we have that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\succeq q$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}p^{+}+(1-\alpha_{p})p^{-}\succeq\alpha_{q}p^{+}+(1-\alpha_{q})p^{-}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{p}\geq\alpha_{q}$
\end_inset

 by step 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 5.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p)=\alpha_{p}$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\beta p+(1-\beta)q)=\beta U(p)+(1-\beta)U(q)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim U(p)p^{+}+(1-U(p))p^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\sim U(q)p^{+}+(1-U(q))p^{-}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the independence axiom:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\beta p+(1-\beta)q\sim\beta[U(p)p^{+}+(1-U(p))p^{-}]+(1-\beta)q$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\beta[U(p)p^{+}+(1-U(p))p^{-}]+(1-\beta)[U(q)p^{+}+(1-U(q))p^{-}]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta p+(1-\beta)q\sim[\beta U(p)+(1-\beta)U(q)]p^{+}+[1-[\beta U(p)+(1-\beta)U(q)]]p^{-},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\beta p+(1-\beta)q)=\beta U(p)+(1-\beta)U(q)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second step of the proof is to show that a linear representation leads
 to an expected utility representation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U:\Delta(Z)\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is linear if and only if there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p)=\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)p(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is linear on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 and continuous, then it is a continuous and linear operator.
 The Riesz representation theorem guarantees that we can always represent
 it as an inner product of the dual of the linear operator and the object
 itself, 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p)=u'p$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the dual.
 We let 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a Bernoulli utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Recoverability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U:\Delta(Z)\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U':\Delta(Z)\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be linear maps that represent 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

, then there exist real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U'(p)=\alpha U(p)+b$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 are Bernoulli utilities such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u'p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v'p$
\end_inset

 represent 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 then there are real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v'p=\alpha u'p+b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Think about this.
 How it differs from the recoverability result of the common rational preference
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Attitudes towards Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Expected value certainty equivalent.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\overline{z}}$
\end_inset

 degenerate lottery is an expected value certainty equivalent of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}=\sum_{z\in Z}zp(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A decision maker is risk averter if for any expected utility certainty equivalen
t of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\overline{z}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}=\sum_{z\in Z}zp(z)$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\overline{z}}\succeq p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the Expected Utility framework.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
The expected utility consumer is risk averter if 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is concave,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{x\in Z}u(x)p(x)\leq u(\sum_{x\in Z}xp(x))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof is simply an application of Jensen's inequality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given a Bernoulli utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 we define the following concepts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i) Certainty equivalent.
 
\begin_inset Formula $CE(p,u)=u(\delta_{z})=\sum_{z\in Z}u(z)p(z)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii) Probability premium.
 For a fixed prize 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and a positive number 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 (small) 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x,\epsilon,u)$
\end_inset

 is the probability premium if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)=(\frac{1}{2}+\pi(x,\epsilon,u))u(x+\epsilon)+(\frac{1}{2}-\pi(x,\epsilon,u))u(x-\epsilon).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
This is the excess probability over fair-odds that make the individual indiffere
nt between the certain outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a lottery over 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x-\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 It can be negative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose a consumer is an expected utility maximizer, with a Bernoulli utility
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Then the following are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) The decision maker is risk averse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is concave.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) The expected certain equivalent of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $CE(p,u)\leq\sum xp(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iv) 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x,\epsilon,u)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Expected Utility for Infinite Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a set of prizes, we say that the collection of subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\subseteq2^{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra when
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\in\Sigma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{c}\in\Sigma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{A_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a countable collection of sets such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{n}A_{n}\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 is a measurable space whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

algebra.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $p:\Sigma\mapsto[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is a probability measure if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p(Z)=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{A_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a countable collection of pairwise disjoint sets such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\cup_{n}A_{n})=\sum_{n}p(A_{n})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call the collection of probabililities 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z,\Sigma)$
\end_inset

 for short 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is fixed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q)(E)=\alpha p(E)+(1-\alpha)q(E)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We fix a topology on this pace 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\rightarrow^{w*}p$
\end_inset

 under the weak
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 topology if 
\begin_inset Formula $\int fdp^{n}\rightarrow\int fdp$
\end_inset

 for continuous and bounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(w*-Continuity) For any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q\in\Delta(Z):q\succ p\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q\in\Delta(Z):p\succ q\}$
\end_inset

 are open in the weak* topology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A rational preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the Independence Axiom and w*-Continuity if and only if
 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $u:Z\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 bounded and continuous such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U(p)=\int u(z)dp(z)$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Application: Demand for a risky asset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An asset is a divisible claim to a financial return in the future.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 denote the amounts of money invested in a risky and safe asset respectively.
 The risky asset pays a random return of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 dollars per dollar invested and the safe asset pays 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 dollar with certainty per dollar invested.
 The random return has a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z)$
\end_inset

 (CDF).
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int zdF(z)>1$
\end_inset

, or that the risky asset expected return exceeds the return of the safe
 asset.
 Then the total return is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha Z+\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, we must have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta=w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{\alpha,\beta\geq0}\int u(\alpha z+\beta)dF(z)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad\alpha+\beta=w.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalently we want to solve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{0\leq\alpha\leq w}\int u(w+\alpha(z-1))dF(z).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first order conditions are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(\alpha^{*})=\int u'(w+\alpha^{*}[z-1])[z-1]dF(z)\begin{cases}
\leq0 & if\quad\alpha^{*}<w\\
\geq0 & if\quad\alpha^{*}>0.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int zdF(z)>1$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(0)>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows from 
\bar under

\begin_inset Formula $u'(w)>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(0)=\int u'(w)[z-1]dF(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{*}=0$
\end_inset

 cannot satisfiy the first order conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a risk is actuarially favorable then a risk averter will always accept
 at least a small amount of it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Dominance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\succeq^{FOD}G$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $U(F)\geq U(G)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is expected utility (
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ$
\end_inset

 and increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F\succeq^{FOD}G$
\end_inset

 FOSD means that 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)\leq G(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in Z$
\end_inset

 with strict inequality for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../WesternAP/FirstYear/MicroI/notes/figures/fosd.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First order stochastic dominance.
 Option A dominates Option B.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Allais Paradox
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is finite in fact 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

