\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two choice sets:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}=(0,1,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}'=(0.10,0.89,0.01)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Fei: 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}'$
\end_inset

) (Eduardo: 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}'$
\end_inset

) (Niko: 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}=(0,0.11,0.89)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}'=(0.10,0,0.90)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Fei: 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}'$
\end_inset

) (Eduardo: 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}'$
\end_inset

) (Niko: 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}'$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some individuals choose 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}\succ L_{1}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}'\succ L_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is inconsistent with expected utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}\succ L_{1}'$
\end_inset

 then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{0.5}>(0.10)u_{2.5}+(0.89)u_{.5}+(0.01)u_{0}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding, 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.89)u_{0}-(0.89)u_{0.5}$
\end_inset

 to both sides we get,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(0.11)u_{0.5}+(0.89)u_{0}>(0.1)u_{2.5}+(0.9)u_{0},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}\succ L_{2}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Revealed Preference of Expected Utility under Concavity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the problem of maximizing expected utility subject to a budget.
 The consumption space is state-contingent commodities paying 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 in state 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 There is a lottery defined over the states of the world 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in\Delta(S)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{s}\geq0$
\end_inset

 is the probability that state 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 happens and the consumer gets 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}$
\end_inset

 units of consumption.
 The problem is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x\in\mathbb{R}^{|S|}}\sum_{s\in S}\pi_{s}u(x_{s})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
s.t.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{s\in S}p_{s}x_{s}=w.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to devise a nonparametric test of expected utility on the basis
 of the first order conditions.
 The Bernoulli utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, is assumed to be for this subsection continuous, increasing, and 
\series bold
concave.
 
\series default
We do not need it to be differentiable but for simplicity assume it is.
 Then, let's obtain the FOC of this problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{s}u'(x_{s})=\lambda p_{s},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that a consumption vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1}\cdots x_{S})'$
\end_inset

 is expected utility maximizing if and only if it satisfies the FOC.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, consider a finite data set of prices and consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{T}=\{p^{t},x^{t}\}_{t=1}^{T}$
\end_inset

 and a known probability over states 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, where each observation is a different trial.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}^{t},p_{s}^{t},\pi_{s}$
\end_inset

 denote the state contingent quantities, prices and probabilities respectively.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We say a data set 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{T}$
\end_inset

 is rationalized by a risk averse expected utility function if there is
 a continuous, concave, increasing utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{s\in S}\pi_{s}^{t}u(x_{s}^{t})\geq\sum_{s\in S}\pi_{s}^{t}u(y_{s})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{s\in S}p_{s}^{t}x_{s}^{t}\geq\sum_{s\in S}p_{s}^{t}y_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{T}$
\end_inset

 is rationalized by a risk averse expected utility function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) If there are numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{s}^{t}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\{1,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

 such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(1) if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}^{t}>x_{s'}^{t'}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{s}^{t}\leq\beta_{s'}^{t'}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(2) for every 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\{1,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\pi_{s}\beta_{s}^{t}}{p_{s}^{t}}=\frac{\pi_{s'}\beta_{s'}^{t}}{p_{s'}^{t}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Necessity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the FOC, we have that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{s}u'(x_{s}^{t})=\lambda^{t}p_{s}^{t},\forall s\in S,\forall t.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{t}=\frac{\pi_{s}u'(x_{s}^{t})}{p_{s}^{t}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\pi_{s}\beta_{s}^{t}}{p_{s}^{t}}=\frac{\pi_{s'}\beta_{s'}^{t}}{p_{s'}^{t}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{s}^{t}=u'(x_{s}^{t})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conditions in (1), are implied by the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is concave and increasing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experimental Evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Polisson and Quah develop a revealed preferences test for expected utility.
 They apply their framework to the famous Choi, Fisman, Gale and Kariv (2007)
 dataset and find the following passing rates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-GARP is already known to us.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-RDEU is an alternative model to expected utility called rank dependent
 expected utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-EU is the expected utility model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-EU* is the expected utility with the restriction that the Bernoulli utility
 is concave.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

drop
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 column corresponds to how much observations I dropped from the sample.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

