\begin_layout Section
Measuring Risk Aversion in the Lab
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Holt and Laury price list method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../WesternAP/FirstYear/MicroI/notes/figures/holt_laury.png
	lyxscale 150
	scale 150

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Price list method for eliciting risk aversion
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals choose between 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in each of the ten rows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two outcomes for each option 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1},B_{2}$
\end_inset

 with changing probabilities for each row.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected outcome of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is higher for the firt 4 rows, and it switches to lower for the last six
 rows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-A risk neutral subject will choose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\cdots,4$
\end_inset

 switch at 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 and remain there.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Option 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has higher variance:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-An individual who switches to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 between row 6 and row 10 is classified as being risk-averse and the more
 risk-averse individual the switch will be later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At random you pay one of the rows.
 To incentivize decision making.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Aggregate Demand (Ch.
 4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When can aggregate demand be expressed as a function of prices and aggregate
 wealth? (Macro-Econometrician).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When does aggregate demand satisfy the weak axiom? (Positive theorist)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When does aggregate demand have welfare significance? (Welfarist Theorist)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Aggregate Demand) Aggregate demand is a mapping from prices (common to
 all consumers) and the wealth distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,\{w_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I})=\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we tackle the first question.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
We can write aggregate demand as a function of aggregate wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,\{w_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I})=x(p,\sum_{i=1}^{I}w_{i})$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}\partial_{w_{i}}x_{l,i}(p,w_{i})dw_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}dw_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, this in turn can happen if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{w_{i}}x_{l,i}(p,w_{i})=\partial_{w_{j}}x_{l,j}(p,w_{j})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in\{1,\cdots,I\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we need to define a class of preferences that admit this possibility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Gorman Form) A preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Gorman Form property if they allow an indirect utility of
 the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{i}(p,w_{i})=a_{i}(p)+b(p)w_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
A necessary and sufficient condition for the set of consumers to exhibit
 parallel, straight wealth expansion paths is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{w_{i}}x_{l,i}(p,w_{i})=\partial_{w_{j}}x_{l,j}(p,w_{j})$
\end_inset

 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in\{1,\cdots,I\}$
\end_inset

, at any price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is that preferences admit indirect utility functions of the Gorman form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Roy's identity we notice that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p,w_{i})=-\frac{\nabla_{p}a_{i}(p)+\nabla_{p}b(p)w_{i}}{b(p)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{w_{i}}x_{i}(p,w_{i})=-\frac{\nabla_{p}b(p)}{b(p)}$
\end_inset

 that does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,\cdots,I\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Examples of Gorman form are identical homothetic preferences or quasi-linear
 preferences with respect to the same good.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
We can write the aggregate demand as a function of aggregate wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,\{w_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I})=x(p,\sum_{i=1}^{I}w_{i})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 are generated by a Gorman form utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof follows from the previous results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
We can write aggregate demand as a function of aggregate wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,\{w_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I})=x(p,\sum_{i=1}^{I}w_{i})$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a wealth distribution rule based on prices or 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=\omega_{i}(p,w)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is aggregate wealth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Aggregate Demand and the Weak Axiom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For illustration purposes, we can suppose that the wealth rule is simple
 and that there is a distribution rule vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{L}\alpha_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 So that 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=\omega_{i}(p,w)=\alpha_{i}w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have then: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(p,w)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}(p,\alpha_{i}w).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(WARP) The aggregate demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Weak Axiom (WA) if 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x(p^{*},w^{*})\leq w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)\neq x(p^{*},w^{*})$
\end_inset

 imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*\prime}x(p,w)>w^{*}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{*},w^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../WesternAP/FirstYear/MicroI/notes/figures/MGWfig4c1_violationsofWA.pdf
	scale 50
	scaleBeforeRotation
	rotateAngle -90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Violations of Weak Axiom by the Aggregate Demand
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Aggregate demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 may not satisfy the WA even when 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p,\alpha_{i}w)$
\end_inset

 satisfy the WARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main reason is that the WA requires that the wealth compensation is
 done at the aggregate level, this may not imply that individuals are compensate
d.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Restrictions on Behavior to Guarantee WA on the Aggregate Demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Uncompensated Law of Demand ULD) The individual demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

 satisfies the ULD property if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(p^{*}-p)'[x_{i}(p^{*},w_{i})-x_{i}(p,w_{i})]\leq0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
for any 
\begin_inset Formula $p,p^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

, with strict inequality if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p^{*},w_{i})\neq x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
The 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the ULD if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

 is negative definite for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In differential terms the ULD means that 
\begin_inset Formula $dpdx_{i}<0$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $dp$
\end_inset

 big enough to make 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p+dp,w_{i})\neq x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because it is uncompensated then 
\begin_inset Formula $dw_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that: 
\begin_inset Formula $dpD_{p}x_{i}(p,w_{i})dp<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,\cdots,I\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

 satisfies the ULD, so does the aggregate demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 As a consequence the aggregate demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Weak Axiom.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{*}-p)'[x_{i}(p^{*},w_{i})-x_{i}(p,w_{i})]\leq0$
\end_inset

 (by ULD).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{*}-p)'[\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}(p^{*},w_{i})-\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}(p,w_{i})]\leq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{*}-p)'[x(p^{*},w)-x(p,w)]\leq0$
\end_inset

 (this is ULD for 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because this works for any 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p,p^{*}$
\end_inset

 it also works for compensated wealth levels.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the WA also holds.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 is homothetic, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

 satisfies the ULD property.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 homothetic preferences the elasticity of quantity of wealth is 1 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{w_{i}}x_{i}(p,w_{i})w_{i}=x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{w^{i}}x_{i}(p,w_{i})\frac{w_{i}}{x_{i}(p,w_{i})}=1$
\end_inset

 , this implies that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}x_{i}(p,w_{i})=S_{i}(p,w_{i})-\frac{1}{w_{i}}x_{i}(p,w_{i})x_{i}(p,w_{i})'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}(p,w_{i})=D_{p}x_{i}(p,w_{i})+D_{w_{i}}x_{i}(p,w_{i})x_{i}(p,w_{i})'$
\end_inset

, we replace,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $D_{w_{i}}x_{i}(p,w_{i})w_{i}=x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{1}{w_{i}}x_{i}(p,w_{i})x_{i}(p,w_{i})'$
\end_inset

 is ND and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

 is NSD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $dpD_{p}x_{i}(p,w_{i})dp\leq0$
\end_inset

, because 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $dpS_{i}(p,w_{i})dp\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conditions for UDL to Arise from Aggregation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose we have a continuum of consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and preferences are identical and defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 with individual demands 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 where individual wealth is uniformly distributed on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\overline{w}]$
\end_inset

.
 Then the average demand 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}(p,\overline{w})=\int_{0}^{\overline{w}}x(p,w)dw$
\end_inset

 satisfies ULD.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v\neq0$
\end_inset

, under regularity conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 we can interchange derivatives and integrals and we obtain: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $v'D_{p}\overline{x}(p,\overline{w})v=\int_{0}^{\overline{w}}v'D_{p}x(p,w)vdw$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}x(p,w)=S(p,w)-D_{w}x(p,w)x(p,w)'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is the individual Slutsky matrix then,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $v'D_{p}\overline{x}(p,\overline{w})v=\int_{0}^{\overline{w}}v'S(p,w)vdw-\int_{0}^{\overline{w}}(v'D_{w}x(p,w))(v'x(p,w))dw$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d(v'x(p,w))^{2}}{dw}=2\frac{(v'x(p,w))(v'D_{w}x(p,w))dw}{dw}$
\end_inset

, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $-\int_{0}^{\overline{w}}(v'D_{w}x(p,w))(v'x(p,w))dw=-\frac{1}{2}\int_{0}^{\overline{w}}\frac{d(v'x(p,w))^{2}}{dw}dw=-\frac{1}{2}(v'x(p,w))^{2}\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $v'D_{p}\overline{x}(p,\overline{w})v\leq0$
\end_inset

, or the ULD property.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous result depends on the fact that the distribution of wealth
 is uniform and that preferences are identical.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
The Slutsky matrix of the aggregate demand is 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}S_{i}(p,w)-C(p,w)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $C(p,w)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}[D_{w_{i}}x_{i}(p,\alpha_{i}w)-D_{w}x(p,w)][\frac{1}{\alpha_{i}}x_{i}(p,\alpha_{i}w)-x(p,w)]'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we can write a sufficient conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $S(p,w)$
\end_inset

 to be NSD as 
\begin_inset Formula $C(p,w)$
\end_inset

 being positive semidefinite, roughly, on average we require there is a
 positive correlation across consumers between consumption in one commodity
 and the wealth effect for that commodity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The aggregate demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the WA if 
\begin_inset Formula $C(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is positive semidefinite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Welfare Content of Aggregate Demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A positive representative consumer exists if there is a rational preference
 relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that the aggregate demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is precisely the Walrasian demand function generated by the preference
 relation.
 That is 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)\succ x$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The existence of a positive representative consumer is not enough to assign
 welfare significance at the aggregate demand.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first need to define a Social Welfare Function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A (Bergson-Samuelson) social welfare function is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\mathbb{R}^{I}\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that assigns a utility value of each possible vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{1},\cdots,u_{I})\in\mathbb{R}^{I}$
\end_inset

 of utility levels for the I consumers in the economy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now going to pose a problem, from the point of view of fictional
 central planner.
 The central planner can redistribute wealth for any given price to maximize
 social welfare.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
The fictional central planner solves:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Max_{\{w_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I}}W(\{v_{i}(p,w_{i})\}_{i=1}^{I})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad\sum_{i=1}^{I}w_{i}\leq w.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As usual the 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 functions represent the individual indirect utilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $v(p,w)=Max_{\{w_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I},\sum_{i=1}^{I}w_{i}\leq w}W(\{v_{i}(p,w_{i})\}_{i=1}^{I})$
\end_inset

 is an indirect utility function for a positive representative consumer
 for the aggregate demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}(p,w_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof is left for the reader.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The positive representative consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 for the aggregate demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is a normative representative consumer relative to the social welfare function
 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

 the distribution of wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $\{w_{i}(p,w)\}_{i=1}^{I}$
\end_inset

 solves the fictional central planner problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If all 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 admit a Gorman form then the aggregate demand resulting of this admits
 a normative representative consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Discrete Choice and Logit 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 alternatives in the market, indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\cdots,J$
\end_inset

.
 Each purchase occasion, each consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 divides her income 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 on at most one alternative and on an outside good.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{j,z}u_{i}(x_{j},z)\quad s.t.\quad p_{j}+p_{z}z=y_{i},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 are characteristics of the brand 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

 the price, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the quantity of the outside good and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{z}$
\end_inset

 its price.
 The outside good, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0$
\end_inset

 is the non-purchase of any alternative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $z=(y_{i}-p_{z})/p_{j}$
\end_inset

 to derive the conditional indirect utility function for each brand:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{ij}^{*}(x_{j},p_{j},p_{z},y_{i})=U_{i,j}(x_{j},y_{i}-p_{j}/p_{z}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the outside good is bought then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{i0}^{*}(0,y_{i}/p_{z}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Usually, we normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i0}^{*}(0,y_{i}/p_{z})=0$
\end_inset

 for all individuals.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer chooses the brand yielding the highest conditional indirect
 utility:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{j}U_{ij}^{*}(x_{j},p_{j},p_{z},y_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Result of this maximizing is discrete choice individual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, will choose 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{ij}^{*}(x_{j},p_{j},p_{z},y_{i})>U_{ij'}^{*}(x_{j},p_{j},p_{z},y_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j'\neq j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually we let the utility to be random:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{ij}^{*}(x_{j},p_{j},p_{z},y_{i})=V_{j}(x_{j},p_{j},p_{z},y_{i})+\epsilon_{ij},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is a random shock observed by 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 but not to the researcher (unobservable attributes, preference shock, preferenc
e heterogeneity).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually we let 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}(\cdot)=0$
\end_inset

 as a normalization of the utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have now the probability of choice:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{ij}(p_{1},\cdots,p_{J},p_{z},y_{i})=Prob\{\epsilon_{i0},\cdots,\epsilon_{i,J}:U_{ij}^{*}>U_{ij'}^{*}\forall j'\neq j\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=Prob\{\epsilon_{i0},\cdots,\epsilon_{i,J}:V_{j}-V_{j'}>\epsilon_{ij}-\epsilon_{ij'}\forall j'\neq j\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually, in order to model a population market share I assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\epsilon_{ij}\sim^{i.i.d.}F(\cdot)}.}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{j}(p_{1},\cdots,p_{J},p_{z},y)=Prob\{\epsilon_{0},\cdots,\epsilon_{,J}:V_{j}-V_{j'}>\epsilon_{j}-\epsilon_{j'}\forall j'\neq j\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually I observe in data from finite samples are the relative frequencies
 of choice:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{P}_{ij}=\frac{1}{K}\sum_{k=1}^{K}1(Choice_{i,k}=j|0,\cdots,j,\cdots J),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we have 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 trials from the same individual, and they converge to the true stochastic
 choice rule in the limit as the number of experiments becomes infinite:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
lim_{K\rightarrow\infty}\hat{P}_{ij,K}=_{p}P_{ij}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Shares instead are computed as the sample average:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{s}_{j}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}1(Choice_{i}=j|0,\cdots,j,\cdots J).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Multinomial Logit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{ij},j=0,\cdots,J$
\end_inset

 is distributed 
\begin_inset Formula $i.i.d.$
\end_inset

 type 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 extreme value across 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, with CDF:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\epsilon}(x)=exp(-exp(-\frac{x-\eta}{\mu}))=Pr(\epsilon\leq x)
\]

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=0.577$
\end_inset

 (Euler's constant) and the scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=1$
\end_inset

, then we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{ij}=\frac{exp(V_{ij})}{\sum_{j'=0,\cdots,J}exp(V_{ij'})}=\int_{\xi\in supp(\boldsymbol{\xi})}1(V_{ij}-V_{ij'}\geq\epsilon_{ij}-\epsilon_{ij'}\forall j\neq j')F_{\xi}(d\xi).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=(\epsilon_{ij}-\epsilon_{ij'})_{i\neq j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example is the Probit model which assumes that the difference in
 shocks 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{i,j}-\epsilon_{i,j'}\sim^{i.i.d.}N(0,\sigma).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Independence of Irrelevant Alternatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You may be asking what are the empirical implications of the Mutinomial
 Utility Model.
 The most important implication is the Independence of Irrelevant Alternatives
 (IIA).
 Before defining it we allow 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 to change, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ij,J}=\frac{exp(V_{ij})}{\sum_{j'=0,\cdots,J}exp(V_{ij'})}$
\end_inset

 so that the probability of choice depends on the number of alternatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(IIA) 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{P_{ij,J}}{P_{ik,J}}=\frac{P_{ij,J'}}{P_{ik,J'}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $J'$
\end_inset

 possibly is different from 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j,k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is very easy to check that Multinomial Logit satisfy the IIA condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{P_{ij,J}}{P_{ik,J}}=\frac{exp(V_{ij})}{exp(V_{ik})}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Red bus/blue bus problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Say you have two options 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 for walking and 
\begin_inset Formula $RB$
\end_inset

 for a red bus.
 Now, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{W,2}=0.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{RB,2}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 The odds ratio is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p_{W,2}}{p_{RB,2}}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Now the city transportation corporation introduced a Blue Bus 
\begin_inset Formula $BB$
\end_inset

, that is identical to the red bus in all attributes, (except for color),
 in fact, it is a (nearly) perfect substitute while not being a substitute
 for walking.
 Given this, we should expect that the probability under this situation
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $J=3$
\end_inset

, we have probabilities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{W,3}=0.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{RB,3}=0.25$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{BB,3}=0.25$
\end_inset

.
 The odds ratio here is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p_{W,3}}{p_{RB,3}}=2$
\end_inset

, but the IIA requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p_{W,3}}{p_{RB,3}}=1$
\end_inset

 is the same independently of the other alternatives.
 This limits a lot the capabilites of the multinomial logit to capture substitut
ion patterns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's be more formal about Luce with choice set variation.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a finite choice set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=2^{X}\setminus\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Now, take a menu 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{A}\in\Delta(A)$
\end_inset

.
 We go back to the environment of the first chapters where we allowed menu
 variation.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{a\in A}\rho_{A}(a)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{A}(a)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=(\rho_{A})_{A\in\mathcal{M}}$
\end_inset

, this is a 
\series bold
stochastic choice data set.
 
\series default
Since it has complete domain we can also call it 
\series bold
stochastic choice function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
(Luce's IIA) For any 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A\cap B$
\end_inset

 it must be that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\rho_{A}(a)}{\rho_{A}(b)}=\frac{\rho_{B}(a)}{\rho_{B}(b)},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
whenever the probabilities are positive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(Luce,McFadden) The following are equivalent, if the probabilities are positive:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 satisfies Luce's IIA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 admits a Logit representation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $(i)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(ii)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=exp(v(x))=\rho_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 And
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Then we have to verify that it generates the dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 for all other menus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}\in A$
\end_inset

, by IIA 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(x)=\rho_{X}(x)\frac{\rho_{A}(x^{*})}{\rho_{X}(x^{*})}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Notice that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(x)=w(x)\frac{\rho_{A}(x^{*})}{w(x^{*})}\forall x\in A,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{y\in A}\rho_{A}(y)=\sum_{y\in A}w(y)\frac{\rho_{A}(x^{*})}{w(x^{*})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\frac{\rho_{A}(x^{*})}{w(x^{*})}\cdot\sum_{y\in A}w(y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This means that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(x)=\frac{exp(v(x))}{\sum_{y\in A}exp(v(y))}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Random Utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take a choice set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Consider a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P})$
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}-$
\end_inset

 measurable random utility function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{U}:\Omega\to\mathbb{R}^{X}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Random CD utility: 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,y)=x^{\alpha}y^{1-\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\sim\text{Uniform}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 For this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C(x,A)$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

event
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in which the agent chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C(x,A):=\{\omega\in\Omega:\boldsymbol{U}_{\omega}(x)>\boldsymbol{U}_{\omega}(y)\quad\text{for all\ensuremath{\quad}}b\in A/\{x\})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has a random utility (RU) representation if there exists a random utility
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(x)=\mathbb{P}(C(x,A)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 be distribution of random utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{U}$
\end_inset

, then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(x)=\mu(\boldsymbol{U}|\boldsymbol{U}(a)>\boldsymbol{U}(b)\quad\text{for all\ensuremath{\quad}}b\in A/\{x\}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Random Expected Utility (REU)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's consider consider the setup of choice under risk.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a finite set of prizes and 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

 the choice set is the set of lotteries.
 Tipical items are denotes 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q,r\in X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has a REU representation if it has a Random Utility representation where
 the random utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{U}$
\end_inset

 is such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{U}_{\omega}(p)=\sum_{z\in Z}\boldsymbol{u}_{\omega}(z)p(z),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
for some random Bernoulli utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}:\Omega\to\mathbb{R}^{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need some preliminaries:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Menu expansion:
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha A+(1-\alpha)q:=\{\alpha p'+(1-\alpha)q:p'\in A\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we define the main behavioral inmplication of this model.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Linearity.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in X$
\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(p)=\rho_{\alpha A+(1-\alpha)q}(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other axioms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Regularity.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{A}(x)\geq\rho_{B}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have to define extremes of a choice set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Ext(A)$
\end_inset

 are the extremes of a choice set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\Delta(Z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/ExtremenessREU.png
	lyxscale 50
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Axiom
Extremeness.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{A}(Ext(A))=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we have the following characterization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(Gul and Pesendorfer, 2006) 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has a REU representation if and only if it satisfies: -Regularity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
-Extremeness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
-Linearity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
-Continuity* (not defined here, and technical).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will show just neccesity of the axioms.
 Linearity, follows from the fact that almost surely 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{U}_{\omega}(p)=\sum_{z\in Z}\boldsymbol{u}_{\omega}(z)p(z),$
\end_inset

which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{A}(p)=\mathbb{P}(C(p,A))=\mathbb{P}(C(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q,\alpha A+(1-\alpha)q))=\rho_{\alpha A+(1-\alpha)q}(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)q)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Regularity follows from the fact that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(a)=\mathbb{P}(C(a,A)))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
and since 
\begin_inset Formula $C(a,A)\geq C(a,B)$
\end_inset

 almost surely when 
\begin_inset Formula $B\supseteq A$
\end_inset

 then: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{\ensuremath{\rho_{B}(a)=\mathbb{P}(C(a,B))}}\leq\rho_{A}(a).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have some notable examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Random CRRA: Consider now that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and it's interpreted as the degree of risk aversion then the random Bernoulli
 utility is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{u}_{\omega}(z)=\frac{z^{1-\omega}}{1-\omega}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
In this case randomness comes from random relative risk aversion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(p)=\mathbb{P}(\omega|\sum_{z\in Z}p(z)\frac{z^{1-\omega}}{1-\omega}>\sum_{z\in Z}q(z)\frac{z^{1-\omega}}{1-\omega}\quad\forall q\in A\setminus\{p\})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\sim F(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{A}(p)=\int_{\omega\in\Omega}1(\sum_{z\in Z}p(z)\frac{z^{1-\omega}}{1-\omega}>\sum_{z\in Z}q(z)\frac{z^{1-\omega}}{1-\omega}\quad\forall q\in A\setminus\{p\})dF(\omega).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{\ensuremath{\omega=\overline{\omega}+\epsilon}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
General Random Utility 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a finite choice set.
 Consider the set of linear orders (strict preferences) on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subset X\times X$
\end_inset

.
 There is a distribution over linear orders 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in\Delta(R)$
\end_inset

 that captures preference variability, heterogeneity or preference shocks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\succ_{1}b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\succ_{2}a$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in\Delta(R)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\succ_{1})+\pi(\succ_{2})=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\succ_{j})\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

, we have six of them 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,\cdots,6\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a menu 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in2^{X}\setminus\emptyset$
\end_inset

, the probability of choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(a,A)=\rho_{A}(a)=\sum_{\succ\in R}\pi(\succ)\mathbb{I}(a\succ b\forall b\in A\backslash\{a\})=\mathbb{E}[\mathbb{I}(a\boldsymbol{\tilde{\succ}}b\forall b\in A\backslash\{a\})].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\int_{\omega\in\Omega}\mathbb{I}(a\tilde{\succ}_{\omega}b\forall b\in A\backslash\{a\})\mathbb{P}(d\omega)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Random preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\succ}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}(a\succ b\forall b\in A\backslash\{a\})=1$
\end_inset

 when the argument is true, else 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}(a\succ b\forall b\in A\backslash\{a\})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ASRP) Axiom of Stochastic Revealed Preference.
 The choice probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 satisfy the ASRP if and only for every sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{k},D_{k})_{k=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{n}\rho_{D_{k}}(a_{k})\leq max_{r\in R}\sum_{k=1}^{n}\mathbf{\mathbb{I}}(a_{k}rb\forall b\in D_{k}\backslash\{a_{k}\}).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a,b\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{a,b,c\}$
\end_inset

, let's define the following sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $((a_{1}=a,D_{1}=A),(a_{2}=a,D_{2}=B))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{D_{1}}(a_{1})+\rho_{D_{2}}(a_{1})\leq\max_{\succ\in R}(\mathbb{I}(a_{1}\succ a_{2})+\mathbb{I}(a_{1}\succ a_{j},j\in\{2,3\}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}=\rho_{D_{1}}(a_{1})<\rho_{D_{2}}(a_{1})=\frac{3}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{5}{4}\leq2,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
this passes, but there should be another sequence for which the ASRP fails
 because this dataset violates regularity (ASRP 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

 regularity).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:ASRPRandomUtility"

\end_inset

The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 satisfy the ASRP 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(ii) The following system of linear equations has a solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{n\times S}\pi_{S\times1}=\rho_{n\times1},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbf{\mathbb{I}}(a_{k}r^{s}b\forall b\in D_{k}\backslash\{a_{k}\})_{k=1,s=1}^{k=n,s=S}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=(\pi(r^{s}))_{s=1}^{S}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=(\rho_{D_{k}}(a_{k}))_{k=1}^{K}$
\end_inset

, and the unknown is a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in\Delta(R)$
\end_inset

 is in the simplex of the linear orderings over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $S=|X|!$
\end_inset

 when we assume full support).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(iii) There is random utility that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in\Delta(R)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(a,A)=\sum_{r\in R}\pi(r)\mathbb{I}(arb\forall b\in A\backslash\{a\}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(iv) The mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{C}(a)=\sum_{D\in\mathbf{B}(C)}(-1)^{|D\backslash C|}\rho(a,D)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}(C)=\{D\in2^{X}|C\subseteq D\}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{C}(a)\ge0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 (this is called total monotonicity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We prove that (iii) implies ASRP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if (iii) holds then for any sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{k},D_{k})_{k=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{n}\rho_{D_{k}}(a_{k})=\sum_{k=1}^{n}\sum_{r\in R}\pi(r)\mathbf{\mathbb{I}}(a_{k}rb\forall b\in D_{k}\backslash\{a_{k}\})$
\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\in\Delta(R)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{n}\sum_{r\in R}\pi(r)\mathbf{\mathbb{I}}(a_{k}rb\forall b\in D_{k}\backslash\{a_{k}\})\leq max_{\pi\in\Delta(R)}\sum_{r\in R}\pi(r)\mathbf{\mathbb{I}}(a_{k}rb\forall b\in D_{k}\backslash\{a_{k}\})=max_{r\in R}\sum_{r\in R}\mathbf{\mathbb{I}}(a_{k}rb\forall b\in D_{k}\backslash\{a_{k}\})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{n}\rho_{D_{k}}(a_{k})\leq max_{r\in R}\sum_{k=1}^{n}\mathbf{\mathbb{I}}(a_{k}rb\forall b\in D_{k}\backslash\{a_{k}\}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If ASRP this implies that there is a solution for (ii).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This actually is a corollary of Farkas' Lemma (Theorem of the Alternative).
 For every linear system of equations 
\begin_inset Formula $M\pi=\rho$
\end_inset

, there is an associated linear system of inequalities 
\begin_inset Formula $M'y\geq0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, such that if 
\begin_inset Formula $M'y\geq0$
\end_inset

 has a solution if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M\pi=\rho$
\end_inset

 does not have a solution.
 ASRP means that the inequality cannot have a solution, which implies that
 
\begin_inset Formula $M\pi=\rho$
\end_inset

 has a solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) implies RU (i).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a surprising result about random utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The aggregate probability of choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 for a population of agents with different random utilities supported in
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in\Delta(\Pi)$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{M}(a,A)=\sum_{\pi\in\Pi}\mu(\pi)p_{\pi}(a,A)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
There exist a representative random consumer, i.e., there exist a random utility
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{rep}\in\Delta(R)$
\end_inset

 such that (market share) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{M}(a,A)=\sum_{r\in R}\pi^{rep}(r)\mathbb{I}(arb\forall b\in A\backslash\{b\}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p^{M}(a,A)=\sum_{\pi\in\Pi}\mu(\pi)p_{\pi}(a,A)$
\end_inset

, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f_{C,\pi}(a)=\sum_{D\in\mathbf{B}(C)}(-1)^{|D\backslash C|}p_{\pi}(a,D)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}(C)=\{D\in2^{X}|C\subseteq D\}$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{C,\pi}(a)\ge0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 by assumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f_{C}(a)=\sum_{D\in\mathbf{B}(C)}(-1)^{|D\backslash C|}p^{M}(a,D)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}(C)=\{D\in2^{X}|C\subseteq D\}$
\end_inset

, I want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{C}(a)\ge0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replace:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f_{C}(a)=\sum_{D\in\mathbf{B}(C)}(-1)^{|D\backslash C|}\sum_{\pi\in\Pi}\mu(\pi)p_{\pi}(a,A)=\sum_{\pi\in\Pi}\mu(\pi)\sum_{D\in\mathbf{B}(C)}(-1)^{|D\backslash C|}p_{\pi}(a,A)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f_{C}(a)=\sum_{\pi\in\Pi}f_{C,\pi}(a)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the previous theorem this implies that there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{rep}\in\Delta(R)$
\end_inset

 that generates the aggregate probability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p^{M}(a,A)=\sum_{r\in R}\pi^{rep}(r)\mathbb{I}(arb\forall b\in A\backslash\{b\}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discrete Choice with Attributes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In econometric applications, usually the choice set is unobserved.
 Econometricians usually assume that the choice set is the grand choice
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (assume it is finite).
 The utility of 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, depends on attributes 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}\in\Xi$
\end_inset

 of observable attributes of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{a})_{a\in A}$
\end_inset

 be the profile of attributes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer random utility equals, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{U}(a,x)=v(a,x_{a})+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}(a,x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of the random utility interpretation using states we can update
 the definition of states to have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\omega,x)\in\Omega\times\Xi^{A}$
\end_inset

 (defining a joint measure over states (unobservable) and observable attributes).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\Xi^{A}\to\Delta(A)$
\end_inset

 has a DC (discrete choice) with attributes representation if there exists
 a deterministic utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $v:A\times\Xi\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega\times\Xi^{A},\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P})$
\end_inset

 as well as random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 with values on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{A}$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is smooth and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(a,x)=\mathbb{P}\left(\omega\in\Omega:v(a,x_{a})+\epsilon_{\omega}(a,x)=\max_{b\in A}v(b,x_{b})+\epsilon_{\omega}(b,x)\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common assumption is that the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is independent from the observable attributes 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this assumption can fail if the attributes include price and the
 firms in a market where the consumers live adjust prices as a response
 to shocks to preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applications assume that the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is fixed, and that we observe the mean utility 
\begin_inset Formula $v(a,x_{a})=x_{a}'\beta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 usually is estimated, but here for simplicity we will assume it is known.
 In that case, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(a,x_{a})=v(x_{a})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v:\mathbb{\Xi}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\mathbb{R}^{A}\rightarrow\Delta(A)$
\end_inset

 has a DC with simple attributes representation if there exists random variable
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 with values on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{A}$
\end_inset

 distributed smoothly and independently of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(a,x)=\mathbb{P}(x_{a}'\beta+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{a}=\max_{b\in A}x_{b}'\beta+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{b}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With variation in attributes, and parametric assumptions on the distribution
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

, econometricians usually estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Consumer Surplus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under RU we can estimate the welfare of a consumer in a choice set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by her consumer surplus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(A):=\mathbb{E}\left[\max_{a\in A}\boldsymbol{U}(x)\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the average or expected utility from the best item in the menu (due
 to McFadden, 1973).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In discrete choice, given attributes 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(x):=\mathbb{E}\left[\max_{a\in A}(x_{a}'\beta+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{a})\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula only makes sense if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as unobservable preference shocks.
 If they are decision errors then 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)$
\end_inset

 is not a surplus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Roy's identity for DC.
 (Williams-Daly-Zachary) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a DC with simple attributes and 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 has finite first moments
\series default
, also assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(x_{a})=x_{a}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is scalar), then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(i) For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 the associated consumer surplus 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(ii) The function 
\begin_inset Formula $V:\mathbb{R}^{A}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $V(x))$
\end_inset

 is differentiable and convex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=\nabla V(x)$
\end_inset

 (Roy's identity)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuition of the proof for (iii), by the Envelope's theorem we have that
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{a}}V(x)=\partial_{x_{a}}\mathbb{E}\left[\max_{a\in A}x_{a}+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{a}\right]=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[1(x_{a}+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{a}=\max_{b\in A}x_{b}+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}_{b})\right]=\rho(a,x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have comparative statics and an analogue of the Slutsky matrix result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(Williams-Daly-Zachary) Suppose that a stochastic choice function with attribute
s 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\mathbb{R}^{A}\to\Delta(A)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|$
\end_inset

-times continously differentiable.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has a simple DC with attributes representation (as in the previous lemma)
 if and only if it satisfies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) Translation invariance: 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=\rho(x+\boldsymbol{1}\cdot k)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) Zero limit demand: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x_{a}\rightarrow-\infty}\rho(a,x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{-a}\in(x_{b})_{b\in A\setminus\{a\}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(iii) Symmetric partials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho_{a}}{\partial x_{b}}(x)=\frac{\partial\rho_{b}}{\partial x_{a}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(iv) gross substitutes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\rho_{a}}{\partial v_{b}}(x)<0
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq b$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(v) Alternating signs of partials:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-1)\frac{\partial^{k}\rho_{a_{0}}}{\partial x_{a_{1}}\cdots\partial_{a_{k}}}(x)>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2,\cdots,|A|-1$
\end_inset

 and each set of 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 distinct elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{0},\cdots,a_{k}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Translation invariance says that what matters are utility differences, not
 absolute levels.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Theory of the Firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
firm 
\series default
represents the production possibilities of household, individuals, corporations
 or other businesses.
 The firm may represent actual production or potential of production.
 The theory of the firm is concerned with the question of: What can a firm
 do? The firm for us, is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

black box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that is able to transform inputs into outputs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Production Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We fix 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq1$
\end_inset

 commodities, a 
\series bold
production vector or plan
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},\cdots,y_{L})\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 describes the (net) outputs of the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 commodities.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{l}\geq0$
\end_inset

 denotes output and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{l}<0$
\end_inset

 denotes input.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all production plans that are technologically feasible is called
 the 
\series bold
production set, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subset\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 is feasible, any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin Y$
\end_inset

 is not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production set is the data or the primitive of the theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes it is useful to describe the production set, using a function
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 called the 
\series bold
transformation function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\{y\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:F(y)\leq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F(y)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is an element of the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{y\in\mathbb{R}^{L}|F(y)=0\}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
transformation frontier.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The Marginal Rate of Transformation MRT of any two goods 
\begin_inset Formula $l,k$
\end_inset

 is the ratio:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MRT_{lk}(\overline{y})=\frac{\partial F(y)/\partial y_{l}}{\partial F(y)/\partial y_{k}},\quad F(\overline{y})=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MRT measures how much the net output of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 can increase if the firm decreases the net output of 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 by one marginal unit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Technologies with Different Inputs and Outputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 denote the number of outputs and 
\begin_inset Formula $L-M$
\end_inset

 the number of inputs, usually the vector of outputs is denotes as 
\begin_inset Formula $q=(q_{1},\cdots,q_{M})\geq0$
\end_inset

 and the vector of used inputs is 
\begin_inset Formula $z=(z_{1},\cdots,z_{L-M})\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Here, we eliminate the negative sign for inputs as they stand separate
 from outputs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A particular case of interest is when 
\begin_inset Formula $M=1$
\end_inset

, in that case we can write the production set using a 
\series bold
production function, 
\series default
that gives the maximum amount of output one can reach with a level of input
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\leq f(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production set is then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=\{(-z',q)'\in\mathbb{R}^{L}|q-f(z)\leq0\quad z\geq0,z\in\mathbb{R}^{L-1}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Marginal rate of technical substitution -MRTS-.
 The MRTS of goods 
\begin_inset Formula $l,k$
\end_inset

 is the ratio:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MRTS_{lk}(\overline{z})=\frac{\partial f(\overline{z})/\partial z_{l}}{\partial f(\overline{z})/\partial z_{k}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a fixed level 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{q}=f(\overline{z})$
\end_inset

, the MRTS of 
\begin_inset Formula $l,k$
\end_inset

 measures by how much the input of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 must be increased for a reduction of a marginal unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 to keep the production at the maximum level 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is analogous to the Marginal Rate of Substitution in consumer theory,
 where we asked by how much the demand of one good changed with respect
 to other to keep the utility constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Properties of the Production Set (a list)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) (Always assumed) 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is non-empty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) (Always assumed) 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 The limit of feasible production plans is also feasible 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{n}\rightarrow y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{n}\in Y$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) No free lunch.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

.
 (
\begin_inset Formula $Y\cap\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}\subset\{0\})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iv) Possibility of inaction.
 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(v) Free disposal.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\leq y$
\end_inset

 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 produces the same amount of outputs using at least the same amount of inputs),
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 (
\begin_inset Formula $Y\backslash\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}\subset Y$
\end_inset

).
 Additional amounts of input (that produces at least the same output) can
 be disposed at no cost.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(vi) Irreversibility.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $-y\notin Y$
\end_inset

.
 It is technologically impossible to transform an amount of output into
 the same required amount of input.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Returns to Scale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(viii) Nonincreasing returns to scale.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 exhibits nonincreasing returns to scale if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha y\in Y$
\end_inset

 for all scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(viii) Nondecreasing returns to scale.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha y\in Y$
\end_inset

 for any scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ix) Constant returns to scale.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha y\in Y$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

 (in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a cone).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(x) Additivity (free entry).
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\in Y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $y+y'\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(xi) Convexity.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The production set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is additive and satisfies the nonincreasing returns conditions if and only
 if it is a convex cone.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The convex cone property of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is convex and that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Convexity and the cone property imply noincreasing returns and additivity
 properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, we want to show that if nonincreasing returns hold and additivity
 then the convex cone property follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y,y'\in Y$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha y+\beta y'\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 an integer be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k>max\{\alpha,\beta\}$
\end_inset

.
 By additivity 
\begin_inset Formula $ky\in Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ky'\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\alpha}{k}<1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha y=(\frac{\alpha}{k})ky$
\end_inset

 the nonincreasing returns condition implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta y'\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, by additivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha y+\beta y'\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that if we want to assume non-increasing returns and free entry
 we need the convexity assumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
For any convex production set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subset\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in Y$
\end_inset

, there is a constant returns convex production 
\begin_inset Formula $Y'\subset\mathbb{R}^{L+1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y'=\{y'\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:y'=(y,-1),y\in Y\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y'=\{y'\in\mathbb{R}^{L+1}:y'=\alpha(y,-1)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

}.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
One output.
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the output, one input 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=z^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\alpha<1$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 efficiency, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}(z,\omega)=z^{\alpha}\omega^{1-\alpha}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(z\quad\omega)$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda q$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}(\lambda z,\lambda\omega)=\lambda\hat{f}(z,\omega)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda q=\lambda\hat{f}(z,\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Profit Maximization and Cost Minimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
profit maximization problem
\series default
 PMP, is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{y}\quad p'y=\max_{q,z}(p_{q}'q-p_{z}'z)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad y\in Y.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the transformation function we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Max_{y}p'y
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad F(y)\leq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
profit function 
\series default
is the value function or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p)=max\{p'y:y\in Y\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximizer is the 
\series bold
supply correspondence
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $y(p)=argmax\{p'y:y\in Y\}$
\end_inset

 given prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The profit function may be infinite 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p)=+\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FOC:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}\in y(p)$
\end_inset

 then for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy the FOC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{l}=\lambda\frac{\partial F(y^{*})}{\partial y_{l}}\quad for\quad l=1,\cdots,L
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or equivalently in matrix notation, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\lambda\nabla F(y^{*}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For single output technologies we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{z\geq0}pf(z)-w'z.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 a production function and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 a vector of inputs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $l\in\{1,\cdots,L-1\}$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{l}\frac{\partial f(z^{*})}{\partial z_{l}}\leq w_{l},\quad z_{l}^{*}>0\quad equality\quad holds.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Or in matrix notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p'\nabla f(z^{*})\leq w,\quad[p\nabla f(z^{*})-w]'z^{*}=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is convex then the FOC are necessary and sufficient for optimality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(Properties of the profit function) Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p)=max_{y}\{p'y|y\in Y\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(p)=argmax_{y}\{p'y|y\in Y\}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Assume also 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is closed, and satisfies the free disposal.
 Then,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p)$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p)$
\end_inset

 is convex
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is convex then 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\{y\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:p'y\leq\pi(p)\forall p>>0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iv) 
\begin_inset Formula $y(p)$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(v) If 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is convex then 
\begin_inset Formula $y(p)$
\end_inset

 is convex set for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is strictly convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $y(p)$
\end_inset

 is singled-valued.
 (if non-empty).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(vi) Hotelling's lemma.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y(p)$
\end_inset

 consists of a single point then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\pi(p)=y(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(vii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $y(p)$
\end_inset

 is a differentiable function at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $Dy(p)=D^{2}\pi(p)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive semidefinite matrix with 
\begin_inset Formula $Dy(p)p=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a convex function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $y\in y(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p^{*})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Convexity means 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p^{*})\leq\alpha\pi(p)+(1-\alpha)\pi(p^{*})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p^{*})=\alpha p\cdot y(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p^{*})+(1-\alpha)(p^{*})\cdot y(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p^{*})\leq$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha\pi(p)+(1-\alpha)\pi(p^{*}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p)=p\cdot y(p)=p\cdot y'$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y'\geq p\cdot y(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in y(\alpha p+(1-\alpha)p^{*})$
\end_inset

 may not be optimal at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and at 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is convex then 
\begin_inset Formula $p'y\leq p'y^{*}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}\in y(p)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 by definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(vi) Follows from the Envelope's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}=p'y+\lambda(F(y))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{p}\mathcal{L=}y(p)=\nabla_{p}\pi(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(viii) Given (ii) we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is convex, and by (vi) 
\begin_inset Formula $Dy(p)=D^{2}\pi(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $Dy(p)$
\end_inset

 is PSD and symmetric.
 The singularity property 
\begin_inset Formula $Dy(p)p=0$
\end_inset

 follows from (i).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Property (viii) can also be stated in non-differentiable terms as the 
\series bold
law of supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(p-p^{*})'(y-y^{*})\geq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cost Minimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A property of profit-maximizing firms is that there is no way to produce
 the same amount at a lower cost.
 A necessary condition for profit-maximization is cost minimization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes firms are not price takers, or there are increasing returns to
 scale, in that cases the use of the profit functions is limited and we
 can use instead the cost function.
 The 
\series bold
cost minimization problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Min_{z\geq0}w'z
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t\quad f(z)\geq q.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimized value is the cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $c(w,q)$
\end_inset

.
 The optimizing set is 
\begin_inset Formula $z(w,q)$
\end_inset

 is known as the conditional factor demand correspondences.
 The produced level 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}_{++}$
\end_inset

 is fixed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FOC, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{l}\geq\lambda\frac{\partial f(z^{*})}{\partial z_{l}},\quad\text{equality holds }z_{l}>0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In matrix notation, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w\geq\lambda\nabla f(z^{*})\quad[w-\lambda\nabla f(z^{*})]'z=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 Lagrange multiplier can be interpreted as the marginal value of relaxing
 the constraint.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial c(w,q)}{\partial q}=\lambda$
\end_inset

 the marginal cost of production.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The properties of the 
\begin_inset Formula $c(w,q)$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $z(w,q)$
\end_inset

 are,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is HD1 in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and nondecreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a concave function on 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) If the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z\geq0:f(z)\geq q\}$
\end_inset

 are convex for every 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(q)=\{(-z,q):w'z\geq c(w,q)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w\geq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iv) 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (intermediate supply) is HD0 in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(v) If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z\geq0:f(z)\geq q\}$
\end_inset

 is convex then 
\begin_inset Formula $z(w,q)$
\end_inset

 is a convex set.
 Moreover if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z\geq0:f(z)\geq q\}$
\end_inset

 is strictly convex then 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p,q)$
\end_inset

 is singled valued.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(vi) Sheppard's lemma.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\overline{w},q)$
\end_inset

 consists of a single point then 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is differentiable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{w}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{w}c(\overline{w},q)=z(\overline{w},q)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(vii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{w}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{w}z(\overline{w},q)=D_{w}^{2}c(\overline{w},q)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and NSD with 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{w}z(\overline{w},q)\overline{w}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ix) If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is concave then 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a convex function of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 (in particular, marginal costs are nondecreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof of this properties are very similar the expenditure case in the
 consumer part of this course.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can state the firm's problem with the cost function as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Max_{q\geq0}pq-c(w,q).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The necessary and first-order conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

 to be profit maximizing is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p-\frac{\partial c(w,q^{*})}{\partial q}\leq0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with equality if 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Aggregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there are 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 production units (firms) and each production set is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 (non-empty and closed also satisfies the free-disposal).
 The individual profit function and supply functions are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aggregate supply function is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(p)=\sum_{j=1}^{J}y_{j}(p).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $Dy(p)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and PSD because 
\begin_inset Formula $Dy_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

 are also symmetric and PSD for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aggregate production set is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=\sum_{j=1}^{J}Y_{j}=\{y\in\mathbb{R}^{L}|y=\sum_{j}y_{j}\quad for\quad some\quad y_{i}\in Y_{j},j=1,\cdots,J\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}(p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}(p)$
\end_inset

 be the profit function and supply function of the aggregate production
 set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}(p)=\sum_{j}\pi_{j}(p)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}(p)=\sum_{j}y_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the first equality note that if we take any feasible plan 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 and note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}(p)\geq p'(\sum_{j}y_{j})$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}(p)$
\end_inset

 is maximum then this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}(p)\geq\sum_{j}p'y_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

, but this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}(p)\geq\sum_{j}\pi_{j}(p).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 feasible in the aggregate, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p'y=p'(\sum_{j}y_{j})=\sum_{j}p'y_{j}\leq\sum_{j}\pi_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

, but this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}(p)\leq\sum_{j}\pi_{j}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result implies that we can decentralize the aggregate firm profit maximizat
ion problem into maximizing the profit of each firm separately.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Efficiency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have a definition of efficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A production vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 is efficient if there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\in Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\geq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\neq y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An efficient plan has to be on the boundary but not all boundary points
 are efficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 is profit maximizing for some 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is efficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose otherwise, i.e., there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\in Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq y'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\geq y$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y'>p\cdot y$
\end_inset

, but that means that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is not profit maximizing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
If a collection of firms 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 independently maximizes profits for a given price 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

, then the aggregate production is socially efficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a consequence of the aggregation result and the previous result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 Then every efficient production 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 is a profit-maximizing production for some nonzero price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 is efficient, and define the set 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{y}=\{y'\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:y'>>y\}$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{y}$
\end_inset

 is convex, and given that 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is efficient 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{y}\cap Y=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 We can invoke the 
\series bold
separating hyperplane theorem
\series default
 to establish that there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y'\geq p\cdot y''$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\in P_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y''\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 In particular this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y'\geq p\cdot y$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $y'>>y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

 because if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}<0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, then we should have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y'<p\cdot y$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y'>>y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{l}'-y_{l}$
\end_inset

 sufficiently large.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, since 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y'\geq p\cdot y''$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y'\in P_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y''\in Y$
\end_inset

 and I can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $y'>>y$
\end_inset

 to be as close as possible to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y\geq p\cdot y''$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is profit maximizing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../WesternAP/FirstYear/MicroI/notes/figures/separatinghyperplanes.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Source:Border
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Competitive Markets and Partial Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Competitive Equilibria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a market.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This market has 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 consumers and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 firms.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq1$
\end_inset

 goods.
 Consumer's 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 preferences over 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=(x_{i,l})_{l=1}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

.
 The initial amount of the goods that are in the economy or 
\series bold
endowment 
\series default
is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}=(\omega_{i.l})_{l=1}^{L}$
\end_inset

 with the restriction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i,l}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 The firms may transform some of the endowment of a good into additional
 amounts of other goods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 has available to it the production possibilities summarized by the production
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}\subset\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 An element 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a production plan 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}=(y_{j,l})_{l=1}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The net amount of good on the economy is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{l}+\sum_{j=1}^{J}y_{l,j}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{l}=\sum_{i\in I}\omega_{li}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Economic allocation) An economic allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\cdots,x_{I};y_{1},\cdots,y_{J})$
\end_inset

 is a specification of a consumption vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,I$
\end_inset

 and a production vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 for each firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\cdots,J$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we define the main property of any allocation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Feasibility) The allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\cdots,x_{I};y_{1},\cdots,y_{J})$
\end_inset

 is feasible if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{l,i}\leq\omega_{l}+\sum_{j=1}^{J}y_{l,j}\quad\forall l=1,\cdots,L.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are ready to define a competitive equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\cdots,x_{I};y_{1},\cdots,y_{J})$
\end_inset

 and price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 constitute a competitive (or Walrasian) equilibrium if the following conditions
 are satisfied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i) Profit maximization: For each firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 solves 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{y_{j}\in Y_{j}}p\cdot y_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii) Utility maximization: For each consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 solves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x\in X_{i}}u_{i}(x_{i})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad p\cdot x_{i}\leq p\cdot\omega_{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{J}\theta_{ij}(p\cdot y_{j}),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{ij}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 a share of firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 owned by 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}\theta_{ij}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(iii) Market clearing: For each good 
\begin_inset Formula $l=1,\cdots,L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{l,i}=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\omega_{l,i}+\sum_{j=1}^{J}y_{l,j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Some Preliminary Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
If the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x;y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

 constitute a competitive equilibrium then so does 
\begin_inset Formula $(x;y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha p\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that we can always normalize prices and fix 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}=1$
\end_inset

 for a fixed commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
If the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x;y)$
\end_inset

 and the price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 satisfies the market clearing condition for all goods 
\begin_inset Formula $l\neq k$
\end_inset

 for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and if the consumers' budget constraints so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}=p\cdot\omega_{i}+\sum_{i=1}^{I}\theta_{ij}p\cdot y_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then the market for good 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 also clears.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Partial Equilibrium Competitive Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study an economy with two goods, good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

, and a numeraire 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 each consumer has a quasilinear utility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{i}(m_{i},x_{i})=m_{i}+\phi_{i}(x_{i}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumption set is 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}\times\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 so that the numeraire may be negative (no boundary problems).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above and twice differentiable, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}'(x_{i})>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}''(x_{i})<0$
\end_inset

 at all 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 We normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numeraire 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a composite good of all other goods.
 The key idea is that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is small relatively to the whole expenditure and thus the wealth effects
 are close to null.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We normalize the price of the numeraire to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the price of good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\cdots,J$
\end_inset

 produces good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 The cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

 captures how much input of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 do the firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 needs to produce 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}\geq0$
\end_inset

 of good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 (efficiently) recall that the price of the numeraire is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 The intermediate or 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 demand of firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Its production set is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{j}=\{(-z_{j},q_{j}):q_{j}\geq0\quad and\quad z_{j}\geq c_{j}(q_{j})\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost function is twice continuously differentiable 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}'(q_{j})>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c''_{j}(q_{j})>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}\geq0$
\end_inset

 (strictly convex technology).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that there is no initial endowment of good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 Consumers' initial endowment of the numeraire is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{mi}>0$
\end_inset

 and the total endowment is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{m}=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\omega_{mi}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Partial Competitive Equilibrium) We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\cdots,x_{I};q_{1},\cdots,q_{J})$
\end_inset

 and the price 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 constitute a (partial) competitive equilibrium if and only if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\leq c_{j}'(q_{j}),\quad\text{with equality if}\quad q_{j}>0\quad\forall j\in\{1,\cdots,J\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{i}'(x_{i})\leq p\quad\text{with equality if}\quad x_{i}>0\quad\forall i\in\{1,\cdots,I\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{J}q_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a system of equations of 
\begin_inset Formula $I+J+1$
\end_inset

 that determines 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 consumption levels, 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 production levels and one price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use here the fact that we can check that the market clears for 
\begin_inset Formula $L-1$
\end_inset

 goods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be understood that the consumer's i equilibrium consumption of
 the numeraire is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{i}=\omega_{mi}+\sum_{j=1}^{J}\theta_{ij}(pq_{j}-c_{j}(q_{j}))-px_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j's$
\end_inset

 equilibrium usage of the input is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{j}=c_{j}(q_{j}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long as 
\begin_inset Formula $Max_{i}\phi'_{i}(0)>Min_{j}c_{j}^{'}(0)$
\end_inset

 the aggregate consumption and production of good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 must be strictly positive in a competitive equilibrium.
 We will assume this is the case in what follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that the (partial) competitive equilibrium definition does not involve
 the endowments or the ownership shares of the consumers.
 This is a consequence of the use of quasi-linear preferences and the defining
 feature of partial equilibrium analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Existence of the Partial Competitive Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Max_{i}\phi_{i}'(0)>Min_{j}c_{j}^{'}(0)$
\end_inset

 , then there is always a 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(x;q)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the condition of the (partial) competitive equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we notice that to find prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

, we only need to find 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 at which aggregate supply equals aggregate demand.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}(p)=q^{*}(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Under the assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $Max_{i}\phi_{i}'(0)>Min_{j}c_{j}^{'}(0)$
\end_inset

 at any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq Max_{i}\phi_{i}'(0)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q(p)>0$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly at any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\leq Min_{j}c_{j}'(0)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The existence of an equilibrium price 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in(Min_{j}c_{j}'(0),Max_{i}\phi_{i}'(0))$
\end_inset

 follows from the continuity of the aggregate demand and the aggregate supply.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is strictly decreasing at all 
\begin_inset Formula $p<Max_{i}\phi_{i}'(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing at all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 After finding 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

, the individual level of consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}=x_{i}(p^{*})$
\end_inset

 and the individual level of production is given likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}^{*}=q_{j}(p^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Pareto Optimality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 economic outcome for most economists is the Pareto Optimality or Pareto
 Efficiency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Pareto Optimal) A 
\series bold
feasible
\series default
 allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\cdots,x_{I};y_{1},\cdots,y_{J})$
\end_inset

 is Pareto optimal (or Pareto efficient) if there is no other 
\series bold
feasible
\series default
 allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1}',\cdots,x_{I}';y_{1}',\cdots,y'_{J})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(x_{i}')\geq u_{i}(x_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(x_{i}')>u_{i}(x_{i})$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Fundamental Welfare Theorems in Partial Equilibrium Contexts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(The First Fundamental Theorem of Welfare Economics) If the price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 and allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1}^{*},\cdots,x_{I}^{*},q_{1}^{*},\cdots,q_{J}^{*})$
\end_inset

 constitute a competitive equilibrium, then this allocation is Pareto optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove this we need some preliminaries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We imagine that there is a central planner that wants to maximize aggregate
 surplus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{\begin{array}{c}
(x_{1},\cdots,x_{I})\geq0\\
(q_{1},\cdots,q_{J})\geq0
\end{array}}\sum_{i=1}^{I}\phi_{i}(x_{i})-\sum_{j=1}^{J}c_{j}(q_{j})+\omega_{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}-\sum_{j=1}^{J}q_{j}=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}\phi_{i}(x_{i})-\sum_{j=1}^{J}c_{j}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

 is the Mashallian aggregate surplus.
 It can be though as the total utility generated by the consumption of good
 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 less the cost of production in terms of the numeraire.
 It is clear that an allocation that solves the central planner problem
 is Pareto Optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now notice the first order conditions, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 a Lagrange multiplier associated with the only constraint.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\leq c_{j}'(q_{j}),\quad\text{with equality if}\quad q_{j}>0\quad\forall j\in\{1,\cdots,J\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{i}'(x_{i})\leq\mu\quad\text{with equality if}\quad x_{i}>0\quad\forall i\in\{1,\cdots,I\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{J}q_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that if the price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 and allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1}^{*},\cdots,x_{I}^{*},q_{1}^{*},\cdots,q_{J}^{*})$
\end_inset

 constitute a partial competitive equilibrium then 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1}^{*},\cdots,x_{I}^{*},q_{1}^{*},\cdots,q_{J}^{*})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=p^{*}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the FOC of the central planner problem.
 Moreover given the convexity assumptions we have made the FOC are also
 sufficient.
 We conclude that the partial equilibrium allocation is Pareto optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(The Second Fundamental Theorem of Welfare Economics) For any Pareto optimal
 levels of utility 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{1},\cdots,u_{I})$
\end_inset

 there are transfers of the numeraire commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{1},\cdots,T_{I})$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}T_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, such that a competitive equilibrium reached from the endowments 
\begin_inset Formula $(\omega_{m1}+T_{1},\cdots,\omega_{nI}+T_{I})$
\end_inset

 yields precisely the utilities 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{1},\cdots,u_{I}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
General Equilibrium Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Pure Exchange Economies: The Edgeworth Box
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that there are two consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 and two commodities 
\begin_inset Formula $l=1,2$
\end_inset

.
 Consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i's$
\end_inset

 consumption vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=(x_{1i},x_{2i})$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{li}$
\end_inset

 denotes the consumption of good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and individual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 defined over 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Each consumer has an endowment of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{li}\geq0$
\end_inset

 of good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 Consumer's i endowment vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}=(\omega_{1i},\omega_{2i})$
\end_inset

.
 The total endowment of good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is the endowment vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{l}=\omega_{l1}+\omega_{l2}$
\end_inset

.
 This quantity is strictly positive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An allocation is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},x_{2})=((x_{11},x_{21}),(x_{12},x_{22}))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that an allocation is feasible if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{l1}+x_{l2}\leq\omega_{l}\quad\forall1,2.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main feature of general equilibrium is that wealth is given endogenously.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have for any given vector of prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},p_{2})$
\end_inset

, consumer's 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 wealth equals the market endowment of commodities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\cdot\omega_{i}=p_{1}\omega_{1i}+p_{2}\omega_{2i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer's 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 budget constraint is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{i}(p)=\{x_{i}\in X:p\cdot x_{i}\leq p\cdot\omega_{i}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an Edgeworth box, the budget constraint of both consumers can be captured
 by the 
\series bold
budget line, 
\series default
that is the line that goes through the market endowment and has slope 
\begin_inset Formula $-(p_{1}/p_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Walrasian Equilibrium) A Walrasian (or competitive) equilibrium for an
 Edgeworth box economy is a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 an allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=(x_{1}^{*},x_{2}^{*})$
\end_inset

 in the Edgeworth box such that for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}^{*}\succeq_{i}x_{i}\quad\forall x_{i}\in B_{i}(p^{*}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
(Cobb-Douglas Exchange Economy) Suppose that each consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has the Cobb-Douglas utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(x_{1i},x_{2i})=x_{1i}^{\alpha}x_{2i}^{1-\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, endowments are 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}=(1,2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}=(2,1)$
\end_inset

.
 At prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},p_{2})$
\end_inset

, consumer's 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 wealth is 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{1}+2p_{2})$
\end_inset

 and his demand lie on the offer curve:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
OC_{1}(p)=\left(\frac{\alpha(p_{1}+2p_{2})}{p_{1}},\frac{(1-\alpha)(p_{1}+2p_{2})}{p_{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The consumer's 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 OC is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
OC_{2}(p)=\left(\frac{\alpha(2p_{1}+p_{2})}{p_{1}},\frac{(1-\alpha)(2p_{1}+p_{2})}{p_{2}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
To determine the Walrasian equilibrium prices, note that at these prices
 the total amount of good 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 consumed by the two consumers must equal 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\omega_{11}+\omega_{12}=3)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\alpha(p_{1}^{*}+2p_{2}^{*})}{p_{1}^{*}}+\frac{\alpha(2p_{1}^{*}+p_{2}^{*})}{p_{1}^{*}}=3.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Solving this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{p_{1}^{*}}{p_{2}^{*}}=\frac{\alpha}{1-\alpha}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Pareto Optimality/Edgeworth Box) An allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the Edgeworth box is Pareto optimal (or Pareto efficient) if there is
 no other allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 in the Edgeworth box with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\succeq_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\succ_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pareto Set: In the Edgeworth Box a Pareto Set is the set of allocations
 that are Pareto Optimal for all possible endowments (that add up to the
 fixed market endowment).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Pareto set has the property that any element has to be the in the tangency
 of the preferences curves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Any Walrasian Equilibrim allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 necessarily belongs to the Pareto Set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Under convexity assumptions a planner can achieve any desired Pareto optimal
 allocation by appropriately redistributing wealth in a lump-sum fashion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Equilibrium with Transfers) An allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 in the Edgeworth box is supportable as an equilibrium with transfers if
 there is a price system 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 and a wealth transfers 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}+T_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, such that for each consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}^{*}\succeq x_{i}'\quad\forall x_{i}'\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{2}\quad s.t.\quad p^{*}\cdot x_{i}'\leq p^{*}\cdot\omega_{i}+T_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
If the preferences of the consumers in the Edgeworth box are continuous,
 convex, and strongly monotone, then any Pareto optimal allocation is supportabl
e as an equilibrium with transfers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The One-Consumer, One-Producer Economy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a consumer and a technology.
 The consumer has continuous, convex, and strongly monotone preferences
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 defined over his consumption of leisure 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the consumption of good 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The endowment is time 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{L}$
\end_inset

 (leisure) (e.g.
 24 hours) and no endowment of the consumption good.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer can produce the consumption good by means of labor according
 to the production function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the firm's labor input.
 Thus to produce output, the firm must hire the consumer, effectively purchasing
 some of the consumer's leisure from him.
 We assume that the firm seeks to maximize profits taking prices as given.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be the price of its output and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 be the price of labor, the firm solves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{z\geq0}pf(z)-wz.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given prices 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

, the firm's optimal labor demand is 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p,w)$
\end_inset

, its output is 
\begin_inset Formula $q(p,w)$
\end_inset

, and its profits are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer is the sole owner of the firm and receives all profits earned
 by the firm 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})$
\end_inset

 be a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

, the consumer's problem given prices 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{\{x_{1},x_{2}\}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}}u(x_{1},x_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad px_{2}\leq w(\overline{L}-x_{1})+\pi(p,w).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The budget constraint of the consumer is 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\overline{L}-x_{1})+\pi(p,w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumer optimal demand at prices 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w)$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{1}(p,w),x_{2}(p,w)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Walrasian equilibrium in this economy involves a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{*},w^{*})$
\end_inset

 at which the consumption and labor markets clear, that is, at which
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}(p^{*},w^{*})=q(p^{*},w^{*})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z(p^{*},w^{*})=\overline{L}-x_{1}(p^{*},w^{*}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
A particular consumption-leisure combination can arise in a competitive
 equilibrium if and only if it maximizes the consumer's utility subject
 to the economy's technological and endowment constraints (Pareto Optimal).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Central planner:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{x_{1},x_{2}}u(x_{1},x_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}=f(\overline{L}-x_{1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Claim 10 is saying is that the descentralized problem stated before has
 the same solution as the central planner problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Equilibrium and Its Basic Welfare Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $I>0$
\end_inset

 consumers, 
\begin_inset Formula $J>0$
\end_inset

 firms and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 commodities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,I$
\end_inset

 is characterized by a consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\subset\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and a preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The preferences are rational.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\cdots,J$
\end_inset

 is characterized by a technology or production set, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}\subset\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 is non-empty and closed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The initial resources in the economy are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=(\omega_{1},\cdots,\omega_{L})\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\{X_{i},\succeq_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I},\{Y_{j}\}_{j=1}^{J},\omega).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An economy is pure exchange if the only technology disposable is free disposal,
 that is, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{j}=-\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\cdots,J$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)=(x_{1},\cdots,x_{I},y_{1},\cdots,y_{J})$
\end_inset

 is a specification of a consumption vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,I$
\end_inset

 and a production vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\cdots,J$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A feasible allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is Pareto optimal if there is no other feasible allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x',y')$
\end_inset

 that Pareto dominates it, that is, if there is no feasible allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x'y')$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\succeq_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\succ_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Private Ownership Economies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consumers have ownership claims (shares) to the profit of firms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has initial endowment vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and a claim to a share 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{ij}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 of the firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\sum_{i}\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}\theta_{ij}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{1,\cdots,J\}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given a private ownership economy specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\{X_{i},\succeq_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I},\{Y_{j}\}_{j=1}^{J},\{\omega_{i},\theta_{i1},\cdots,\theta_{iJ}\}_{i=1}^{I})$
\end_inset

 and allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

 and a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{L})$
\end_inset

 constitutes a Walrasian equilibrium if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\cdot y_{j}\leq p\cdot y_{j}^{*}\forall j\in\{1,\cdots,J\},\forall y_{j}\in Y_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}^{*}\succeq_{i}x_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall i,\forall x_{i}\in\{x_{i}:p\cdot x_{i}\leq p\cdot\omega_{i}+\sum_{j}\theta_{ij}p\cdot y_{j}^{*}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(iii)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i,l}^{*}=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\omega_{i,l}+\sum_{j=1}^{J}y_{j,l}^{*}\forall l\in\{1,\cdots,L\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Price Equilibria with Transfers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given an economy specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\{X_{i},\succeq_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I},\{Y_{j}\}_{j=1}^{J},\omega)$
\end_inset

 and allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

 an a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{L})$
\end_inset

 constitute a price equilibrium with transfers if there is an assignment
 of wealth levels 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{1},\cdots,w_{I})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}w_{i}=p\cdot\omega+\sum_{j}p\cdot y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

 maximizes profits in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 that is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\cdot y_{j}\leq p\cdot y_{j}^{*}\forall y_{j}\in Y_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}^{*}\succeq_{i}x_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall i,\forall x_{i}\in\{x_{i}:p\cdot x_{i}\leq w_{i}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(iii)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*}=\omega+\sum_{j}y_{j}^{*}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The First Fundamental Theorem of Welfare Economics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 on the consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is locally nonsatiated if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $||x_{i}'-x_{i}||\leq\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\succ_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(First Fundamental Theorem of Welfare Economics) If preferences are locally
 nonsatiated and if 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*},p)$
\end_inset

 is a price equilibrium with transfers, then the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

 is Pareto optimal.
 In particular, any Walrasian Equilibrium allocation is Pareto Optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*},p)$
\end_inset

 is a price equilibrium with transfers and that the associated wealth levels
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{1},\cdots,w_{I})$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}w_{i}=p\cdot\omega+\sum_{j}p\cdot y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preference maximization part of the notion of price equilibrium with
 transfers requires that if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}\succ x_{i}^{*}\quad then\quad p\cdot x_{i}>w_{i}=p\cdot x_{i}^{*}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under local non-satiation we also have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
If\quad x_{i}\succeq x_{i}^{*}\quad then\quad p\cdot x_{i}\ge w_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We verify this by contradiction, consider that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succeq x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}<w_{i}$
\end_inset

 then there is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\succ x_{i}$
\end_inset

 that is affordable thus making 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 non-optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider an allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\succ_{PD}(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

 that dominates the given allocation in the Pareto sense.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succeq_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the previous arguments we have that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\cdot x_{i}\geq w_{i}\forall i\quad and\quad p\cdot x_{i}>w_{i}\quad\exists i
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}p\cdot x_{i}>\sum_{i}w_{i}=p\cdot\omega+\sum_{j}p\cdot y_{j}^{*}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By profit maximization we know that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{j}p\cdot y_{j}^{*}\geq\sum_{j}p\cdot y_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}p\cdot x_{i}>p\cdot\omega+\sum_{j}p\cdot y_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is not feasible.
 There is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

 must be Pareto optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Second Fundamental Theorem of Welfare Economics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second welfare theorem gives conditions under which a Pareto Optimum
 can be supported as a price equilibrium with transfers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need some preliminaries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Price 
\series bold
quasi-equilibrium
\series default
 with transfers) Given an economy specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\{X_{i},\succeq_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I},\{Y_{j}\}_{j=1}^{J})$
\end_inset

 an allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

 and a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{L})\neq0$
\end_inset

 constitutes a price quasi-equilibrium with transfers if there is an assignment
 of wealth levels 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{1},\cdots,w_{I})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}w_{i}=p\cdot\omega+\sum_{j}p\cdot y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y_{j}\leq p\cdot y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in Y_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}\geq w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*}=\omega+\sum_{j}y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the price quasi-equilibrium differs from the price equilibrium
 notion with the part (ii) of the definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preferences maximization imply (ii) but (ii) does not implies preference
 maximization.
 Hence, any price equilibrium with transfers is a price quasi-equilibrium
 with transfers but the converse is not true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under local non-satiation we can write (ii) as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}\geq p\cdot x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(Second Fundamental Theorem of Welfare Economics) Consider an economy specified
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\{X_{i},\succeq_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I},\{Y_{j}\}_{j=1}^{J},\omega)$
\end_inset

 and suppose that every 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 is convex and every preference relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 is convex and locally non-satiated.
 Then for every Pareto optimal allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

 there is a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{L})\neq0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*},p)$
\end_inset

 is a price quasiequilibrium with transfers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}=\{x_{i}\in X_{i}:x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}\}\subset\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then define:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\sum_{i}V_{i}=\left\{ \sum_{i}x_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:x_{1}\in V_{1},\cdots,x_{I}\in V_{I}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=\sum_{j}Y_{j}=\left\{ \sum_{j}y_{j}\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:y_{1}\in Y_{1},\cdots,y_{J}\in Y_{J}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y+\{\omega\}$
\end_inset

 is the shifted production function by the endowments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 1.WTS that every set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 This follows from the preferences being rational and convex.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Take a mixing parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x_{i}+(1-\alpha)x_{i}'\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given completeness of preferences, without loss of generality we can assume
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succeq_{i}x_{i}'$
\end_inset

.
 By convexity we have, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x_{i}+(1-\alpha)x_{i}'\succeq_{i}x_{i}'$
\end_inset

, which by transitivity yields the desired conclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x_{i}+(1-\alpha)x_{i}'\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 2.
 The sets 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y+\{\omega\}$
\end_inset

 are convex.
 The sum of convex sets is also a convex set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cap(Y+\{\omega\})=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 This is a consequence of Pareto Optimality of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 4.
 There is 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{L})\neq0$
\end_inset

 and a number 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot z\geq r$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot z\leq r$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Y+\{\omega\}$
\end_inset

.
 This follows directly from the 
\series bold
separating hyperplane theorem.

\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 5.
 WTS If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succeq_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\sum_{i}x_{i})\geq r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succeq_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 By local non-satiation for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 close to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x_{i}}\in V_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\hat{x}_{i}\in V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\sum_{i}\hat{x}_{i})\geq r$
\end_inset

, taking limits 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}_{i}\rightarrow x_{i}$
\end_inset

we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\sum_{i}x_{i})\geq r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 6.
 WTS 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*})=p\cdot(\omega+\sum_{j}y_{j}^{*})=r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given Step 5 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*})\geq r$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*}=\sum_{j}y_{j}^{*}+\omega\in Y+\{\omega\}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*})\leq r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*})=r$
\end_inset

.
 Since, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*}=\omega+\sum_{j}y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

, we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\omega+\sum_{j}y_{j}^{*})=r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 7.
 WTS For every 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y_{j}\leq p\cdot y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in Y_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}+\sum_{h\neq j}y_{h}^{*}\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\cdot(\omega+y_{j}+\sum_{h\neq j}y_{h}^{*})\leq r
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given Step 6:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=p\cdot(\omega+y_{j}^{*}+\sum_{h\neq j}y_{h}^{*}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y_{j}\leq p\cdot y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 8.
 WTS For every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}\geq p\cdot x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider any 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Because of steps 5 and 6 we have.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\cdot(x_{i}+\sum_{h\neq i}x_{h}^{*})\geq r=p\cdot(x_{i}^{*}+\sum_{h\neq i}x_{h}^{*}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}\geq p\cdot x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 9.
 WTS The wealth levels 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=p\cdot x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,I$
\end_inset

 support 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*},p)$
\end_inset

 as a price quasi-equilibrium with transfers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Suppose that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is convex, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Then any price quasiequilibrium with transfers that has 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{1},\cdots,w_{I})>>0$
\end_inset

 is a price equilibrium with transfers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof requires the following result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is convex and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Suppose also that the consumption vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

, the price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and the wealth level 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}\geq w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then if there is a consumption vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}'<w_{i}$
\end_inset

 (a cheaper consumption for 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,w_{i}$
\end_inset

)), it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}>w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider only the case 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}=w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose to the contrary that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}=w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the cheaper consumption assumption, there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}'\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

 such tht 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}'<w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x_{i}+(1-\alpha)x_{i}'\in X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\alpha x_{i}+(1-\alpha)x_{i}')<w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 the continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x_{i}+(1-\alpha)x_{i}'\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction because we have found a consumption bundle that
 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and cost less than 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
General Equilibrium (Pure Exchange) with inattention: back to the Sparse
 max.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have as before an endowment 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{i,s}(p,M^{i})=x_{M^{i}}^{i,s}(p,p\cdot\omega^{i})-\omega^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The aggregate excess demand is 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{s}(p)=\sum_{i}z^{i,s}(p,M^{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equilibrium prices are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{s}(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Assume Pareto Efficient Interior Allocations.
 Consumers are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{i}=M^{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in\{1,\cdots,I\}$
\end_inset

 if and only if the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=\sum_{i}(x^{i,*}(p,p\cdot\omega)-\omega^{i})=0$
\end_inset

 is Pareto Efficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{x}u^{i}(x)=\lambda^{i}p^{s}(m_{i})$
\end_inset

, in a PE interior equilibrium we have for any two goods 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{u_{l}^{i}(x)}{u_{k}^{i}(x)}=\frac{u_{l}^{j}(x)}{u_{k}^{j}(x)}$
\end_inset

, and we have also 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{u_{l}^{i}(x)}{u_{k}^{i}(x)}=\frac{p_{l}}{p_{k}}$
\end_inset

 due to utility maximization, however say that for any two goods 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{l}^{i}\neq m_{l}^{j}$
\end_inset

, for some two goods and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p_{l}^{s}(m^{i})}{p_{k}^{s}(m^{i})}<\frac{p_{l}^{s}(m^{j})}{p_{k}^{s}(m^{j})}$
\end_inset

 which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{u_{l}^{i}(x)}{u_{k}^{i}(x)}<\frac{u_{l}^{j}(x)}{u_{k}^{j}(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, we have that this is not a PE (interior) allocation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also the Second Welfare Theorem does not hold either, because WARP does
 not hold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Offer curves are not longer lines.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../WesternAP/FirstYear/MicroI/notes/figures/OfferCurves.emf
	lyxscale 40
	scale 20

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the offer curve is 
\begin_inset Formula $OC^{i}(p_{1},p_{2})=\{p:x^{i}(p_{1},p_{2},p\cdot\omega^{i})\}$
\end_inset

 because HD0 fails then we cannot normalize, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $OC^{i}(p_{1},p_{2})$
\end_inset

 has two parameters not only one as in the rational case, this means that
 it is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ribbon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
