\begin_layout Chapter
Positive Theory of Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we study the Walrasian Equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Walrasian Equilibrium) Given a private ownership economy specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\{X_{i},\succeq_{i}\}_{i=1}^{I},\{Y_{j}\}_{j=1}^{J},\{\omega_{i},\theta_{i1},\cdots,\theta_{iJ}\}_{i=1}^{I})$
\end_inset

 and allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},y^{*})$
\end_inset

 and a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{L})$
\end_inset

 constitutes a Walrasian equilibrium if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\cdot y_{j}\leq p\cdot y_{j}^{*}\forall j,\forall y_{j}\in Y_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}^{*}\succeq_{i}x_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall i,\forall x_{i}\in\{x_{i}:p\cdot x_{i}\leq p\cdot\omega_{i}+\sum_{j}\theta_{ij}p\cdot y_{j}^{*}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(iii)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*}=\omega+\sum_{j}y_{j}^{*}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Pure Exchange Economies and Excess Demand Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We recall pure exchange is the situation where the only technology available
 is free disposal, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $J=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1}=-\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 We take 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and we assume that the consumers' preferences are continuous, strictly
 convex and locally nonsatiated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\omega_{i}>>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Walrasian Equilibrium can be redefined here as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Pure Exchange Walrasian Equilibrium) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i)' 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}^{*}\leq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y^{*}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $J=1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1}=-\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\in Y_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii)' 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}=x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is the Walrasian demand function).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(iii') 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*}-\sum_{i}\omega_{i}^{*}=y_{1}^{*}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: Say there is a a demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}=(2\quad2)'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}=(2\quad2)'$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{apples}=5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{oranges}=5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}=(3\quad2)'$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}=(2\quad3)'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,apples}^{*}=4-5=-1,y_{1,oranges}^{*}=4-5=-1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}^{*}=(-1\quad-1)'$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(0\quad0)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We verify:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i)', 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}^{*}\leq0$
\end_inset

 (checked) 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y_{1}^{*}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii)' 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(x_{apples},x_{oranges})=-(x_{apples}-2)^{2}-(x_{oranges}-2)^{2}$
\end_inset

, they maximize utility at 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,2)'$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii') Holds by construction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can state the first result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
In a pure exchange economy in which consumer preferences are continuous,
 strictly convex and locally non-satiated, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

 is a Walrasian equilibrium price vector if and only if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}(x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})-\omega_{i})\leq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

 is a Walrasian equilibrum price vector then (i)'-(iii)' imply 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}(x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})-\omega_{i})\leq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}(x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})-\omega_{i})\leq0$
\end_inset

 holds then we let 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}^{*}=\sum_{i}(x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})-\omega_{i})$
\end_inset

, we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot\sum_{i}(x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})-\omega_{i})=0$
\end_inset

, this follows from local non-satiation and we let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}=x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})$
\end_inset

 so (i)'-(iii)' holds.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the difference (vector) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})-\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the consumer's 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 net or excess demand for each good according to what he had in terms of
 endowments of the given good.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Excess demand function of consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

) The excess demand function of consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{i}(p)=x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})-\omega_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})$
\end_inset

 is consumer's 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's Walrasian demand function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this in hand we define the aggregate excess demand:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The aggregate excess demand function of the economy is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z(p)=\sum_{i}z_{i}(p).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula $z:\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}\mapsto\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

, is a mapping from non-negative prices to the euclidean space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can then write the following corollary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 is an equilibrium price vector if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)\leq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{l}(p)=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}>0$
\end_inset

, thus at equilibrium a good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 can be in excess supply 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{l}(p)<0$
\end_inset

 only if it is free 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can add additional assumptions in terms of preferences to strengthen
 the previous definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We require all preferences to be strongly monotone.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
If consumers preferences are strongly monotone (continuous, strictly convex),
 a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 is a Walrasian equilibrium price vector if and only if it clear markets,
 that is, if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{l}(p)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now study the properties of the excess demand.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}=\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 is continuous, strictly convex and strongly monotone.
 Suppose also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\omega_{i}>>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then the aggregate excess demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)$
\end_inset

, defined for all price vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 satisfies the properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot z(p)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (Walras' law).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iv) (Bounded below) There is an 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{l}(p)>-s$
\end_inset

 for every commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(v) If 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\rightarrow p$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{l}\{z_{l}(p^{n})\}\rightarrow\infty.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the properties follow from the demand properties.
 The last item follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and strong monotonic preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Consider the system 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}(p)=\{z_{l}(p)\}_{l=1}^{L-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This follows from Walras' law and Homogeneity of degree zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Existence of Walrasian Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)$
\end_inset

 is a function defined for all strictly positive price vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and satisfying conditions (i)-(v) in the previous proposition.
 Then the system of equations 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=0$
\end_inset

 has a solution.
 Hence a Walrasian equilibrium exists in any pure exchange economy in which
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\omega_{i}>>0$
\end_inset

 and every consumer has continuous, strictly convex, and strongly monotone
 preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We normalize prices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta=\{p\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}:\sum_{l}p_{l}=1\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the unit simplex in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Because the function 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree zero, we can restrict ourselves, in our search
 for an equilibrium, to price vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is well-defined for the interior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
interior\Delta=\Delta^{I}=\{p\in\Delta:p_{l}>0\forall l\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
boundary\Delta=\Delta^{B}=\Delta\setminus\Delta^{I}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof's plan:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we construct a mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\Delta\mapsto2^{\Delta}$
\end_inset

.
 Second, we show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\in f(p^{*})$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p^{*})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Third, we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is convex valued and UHC (closed graph).
 Finally, we apply Kakutani's fixed point theorem to show that at 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\in f(p^{*})$
\end_inset

 necessarily exists.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=\{q\in\Delta:z(p)\cdot q\geq z(p)\cdot q'\forall q'\in\Delta\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(p)=\{q\in\Delta:q_{l}=0\quad if\quad z_{l}(p)<Max_{l}\{z_{l}(p)\}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also notice that if 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)=\Delta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 2: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in Boundary(\Delta)$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(p)=\{q\in\Delta:p\cdot q=0\}=\{q\in\Delta:q_{l}=0\quad if\quad p_{l}>0\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this construction no price at the boundary can be a fixed point, there
 is no 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in Boundary(\Delta)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in f(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 3: A fixed point of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a Walrasian equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\in f(p^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 It is the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\in\Delta^{I}$
\end_inset

 (interior) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}>>0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p^{*})\neq0$
\end_inset

, then according to the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p^{*})\subset Boundary(\Delta)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p>>0$
\end_inset

 because of Walras' law, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{l}(p)<0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{l}(p)>0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l'\neq l$
\end_inset

.
 Then for such 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 any 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in f(p^{*})$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{l}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in f(p)$
\end_inset

 cannot occur because 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot p>0$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot q=0$
\end_inset

 is the requirement for 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in f(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus it must be the case that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in f(p)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 4.
 The fixed point correspondence is convex-valued and upper hemi-continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case I: If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta^{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\Delta^{B}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 is a level set of linear functions defined on the convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q\in\Delta:\lambda\cdot q=k\}$
\end_inset

 for some scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

, and thus it is convex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of cases are easy to verify.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To establish upper hemi continuity consider sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\rightarrow p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{n}\rightarrow q$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{n}\in f(p^{n})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 We have to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in f(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case I: 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta^{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\Delta^{B}$
\end_inset

.
 If that is the case, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}>>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 large, using the definition 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{n}\cdot z(p^{n})\geq q'\cdot z(p^{n})$
\end_inset

 using the continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and limits we get 
\begin_inset Formula $q\cdot z(p)\ge q'\cdot z(p)$
\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in f(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case II: 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta^{B}$
\end_inset

, take any 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}>0$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{l}^{n}=0$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{l}=0$
\end_inset

 follows, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in f(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}>0$
\end_inset

 there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}^{n}>\epsilon$
\end_inset

 for sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If in addition 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\in\Delta^{B}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{l}^{n}=0$
\end_inset

 by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If instead 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}>>0$
\end_inset

 then the properties of excess demand (iv) and (v) are used:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{l}(p^{n})<max_{l}\{z_{l}(p^{n})\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and then again we have 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{l}^{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RHS goes to 
\begin_inset Formula $+\infty$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta^{B}$
\end_inset

 but the LHS is bounded above because if it is positive:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{l}(p^{n})\leq\frac{1}{\epsilon}p_{l}^{n}z_{l}(p^{n})=\frac{1}{\epsilon}\sum_{l'\neq l}p_{l}^{n}z_{l}(p^{n})<\frac{s}{\epsilon}\sum_{l'\neq l}p_{l}^{n}<\frac{s}{\epsilon},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the bound in excess supply given in condition (iv).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary for 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 close enough to the Boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, the maximal demand corresponds to some of the commodities whose price
 is close to zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, any 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{n}\in f(p^{n})$
\end_inset

 will put nonzero weight only on commodities whose price approach zero But
 this guarantees 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot q=0$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in f(p)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 5: Existence of Fixed Point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kakutani's fixed point theorem says that a convex-valued, upper hemicontinuous
 correspondence from a non-empty, compact, convex set into itself has a
 fixed point.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 (is a simplex) thus nonempty, convex and compact set, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is convex-valued upper hemi-continuous correspondence from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 then we conclude that there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\in\Delta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\in f(p^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Local Uniqueness and Regularity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that under certain conditions on preferences there exists a Walrasian
 equilibrium.
 The next question is whether the solution is unique.
 The quick answer is that in general the equilibrium is not unique.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next best thing is to have local uniqueness.
 This is important because we would like to make stable predictions.
 An equilibrium is expected to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A Walrasian equilibrium price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\in\Delta$
\end_inset

 is locally unique if there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that any other 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)\leq0$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $||p-p^{*}||>\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sufficient condition for locally uniqueness is that the economy is regular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Regular Economy) An equilibrium price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{L-1})$
\end_inset

 is regular if the matrix of price effects 
\begin_inset Formula $D\hat{z}(p)\in\mathbb{R}^{L-1\times L-1}$
\end_inset

 is non-singular, that is, has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $L-1$
\end_inset

.
 If every normalized equilibrium price vector is regular, we say that the
 economy is regular.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can state the first result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Any regular (normalized) equilibrium price vector is locally isolated (or
 locally unique).
 That is, there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p'\neq p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{L}'=p_{L}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $||p'-p||<\epsilon$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p')\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if the economy is regular, then the number of normalized equilibrium
 price vectors is finite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The local uniqueness of a regular solution is a direct consequence of the
 inverse function theorem.
 For any infinitesimal change in normalized prices, 
\begin_inset Formula $dp\neq0$
\end_inset

 , the nonsingularity of 
\begin_inset Formula $D\hat{z}(p)$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $D\hat{z}(p)dp\neq0$
\end_inset

, thus we cannot remain in equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continuity of the excess demand and the properties that it blows up when
 prices are close to zero and the incompatibility of zero prices with equilibriu
m following form strongly montone preference, imply that the set of equilibrium
 prices is a closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{L-1}.$
\end_inset

 Any set that is closed and bounded and discrete (by the regularity part)
 is necessarily finite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, we can say a bit more, the number of equilibria in regular economies
 is 
\series bold
odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, we need some preliminaries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Index of an Economy) Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{L-1},1)$
\end_inset

 is a regular equilibrium of an economy.
 Then we denote
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
index(p)=(-1)^{L-1}sign|D\hat{z}(p)|,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
where 
\begin_inset Formula $|D\hat{z}(p)|$
\end_inset

 is determinant of the 
\begin_inset Formula $(L-1)\times(L-1)$
\end_inset

 matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $D\hat{z}(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can state the following result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(The Index Theorem) For any regular economy, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{\{p:z(p)=p,p_{L}=1\}}index(p)=+1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This basically means that the number of equilibria is odd.
 In particular, it cannot be zero, so existence is implied by this theorem.
 The equilibrium with positive sign are more fundamental because all economies
 have at least one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we conclude this section with a genericity analysis, most of the
 formalities of this part are going to be omitted, but the main point is
 that non-regular economies are very unlikely to exists because we can always
 perturb a bit the endowments and get a regular economy, thus empirically
 non-regular economies are of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

little
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We state (without proof) the Theorem of Debreu (1970):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
For almost every vector of initial endowments 
\begin_inset Formula $(\omega_{1},\cdots,\omega_{L})\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

 the economy defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\succeq_{i},\omega_{i})\}_{i=1}^{I}$
\end_inset

 is regular.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Everything Goes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we provide a local negative result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice before that thanks to Walras' law and HD0 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}z(p)p=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot Dz(p)=-z(p)$
\end_inset

.
 These are the only implications we have.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Given a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $L\times L$
\end_inset

 matrix satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot z=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Ap=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot A=-z$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a collection of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 consumers generating an aggregate excess demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Dz(p)=A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nature of the impossibility result is stronger, in fact, it is of a
 global nature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function defined on 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{\iota}=\{p\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}:p_{l}/p_{l\prime}\geq\epsilon\quad\forall l,l'\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
and with values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $z:P_{\iota}\mapsto\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

).
 Assume that in addition, 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is HD0 and satisfies Walras' law.
 Then there is an economy of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 consumers whose aggregate excess demand function coincides with 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)$
\end_inset

 in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\iota}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 satisfying the assumptions that we are given.
 We fix 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2$
\end_inset

.
 We pick an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 that also satisfies the assumptions above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The continuity and homogeneity of degree zero of 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 imply the existence of a number 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|z_{1}(p)|<r$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P_{\iota}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we specify two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{1}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 with domain 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\iota}$
\end_inset

, and values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which are also continuous and homogeneous of degree zero, and satisfy
 Walras' law.
 In particular, we let 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{1}^{1}(p)=\frac{1}{2}z_{1}(p)+r;\quad z_{2}^{1}(p)=-(p_{1}/p_{2})z_{1}^{1}(p).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{1}^{2}(p)=\frac{1}{2}z_{1}(p)-r;\quad z_{2}^{2}(p)=-(p_{1}/p_{2})z_{1}^{2}(p).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By construction 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=z^{1}(p)+z^{2}(p)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P_{\iota}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{i}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 coincides in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\iota}$
\end_inset

 with the excess demand function of a consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{i}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

, continuity homogeneous of degree zero, Walras' law and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{i}(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P_{\iota}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Choose 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}>>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}+z^{i}(p)>>0$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P_{\iota}$
\end_inset

.
 We notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}+z^{i}(p)$
\end_inset

 is the intersection point of the offer curve with the budget line perpendicular
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Because any preference 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 indifference curve is tangent to the budget line perpendicular to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../WesternAP/FirstYear/MicroI/notes/figures/SMD.pdf
	scale 50
	rotateAngle -90

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Uniqueness of Equilibria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In applications we usually want to impose uniqueness of equilibria.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Given an economy specified by the constant returns to technology 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and the aggregate excess demand function of the consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

, a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a Walrasian equilibrium price vector if and only if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y\leq0$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)$
\end_inset

 is a feasible production, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)\in Y.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a Walrasian equilibrium price vector, then (ii) follows from market
 clearing and (i) is a necessary condition for profit maximization with
 a constant returns technology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If (i) and (ii) hold, then consumptions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}=x_{i}(p,p\cdot\omega_{i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,I$
\end_inset

, the production vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}=z(p)\in Y$
\end_inset

 is profit maximizing, and price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 constitute a Walrasian equilibrium.
 To verify this, the only thing that is not automatic is profit maximizing,
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}\cdot y\leq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y^{*}=p\cdot z(p)=0$
\end_inset

 from Walras' law).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the weak axiom for excess demand functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(The Weak Axiom for Excess Demand Functions) The excess demand function
 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the weak axiom of revealed preference (WA) if for any pair or
 price vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z(p)\neq z(p')\quad and\quad p\cdot z(p')\leq0\implies p'\cdot z(p)>0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose that the excess demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is such that, for any constant returns convex technology 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, the economy formed by 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 has a unique (normalized) equilibrium price vector.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the weak axiom.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the weak axiom then, for any constant returns convex technology
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, the set of equilibrium price vectors is convex (and so, if the set of
 normalized price equilibria is finite, there can be at most one normalized
 price equilibirum).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that the WA was violated, that is suppose for some 
\begin_inset Formula $p,p'$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)\neq z(p')$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot z(p')\leq0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'\cdot z(p)\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 then we claim that both 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 are equilibrium prices for the convex, constant returns production set
 given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y^{*}=\{y\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:p\cdot y\leq0\quad and\quad p'\cdot y\leq0\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)\in Y^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y\leq0$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is an equilibrium, the same is true for 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)\neq z(p')$
\end_inset

, we conclude that the equilibrium is not unique for the economy formed
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and the production set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Gross Substitutes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sufficient condition different from the WA that is also used for ensuring
 uniqueness is the gross substitutes property.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 has the gross substitutes (GS) property if whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are such that, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}'>p_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}'=p_{k}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq l$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{k}(p')>z_{k}(p)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq l$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover if 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is HD0 we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{l}(p')<z_{l}(p)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
An aggregate excess demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $z(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the gross substitute property has at most one exchange equilibri
um, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=0$
\end_inset

 has at most one normalized solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $z(p)=z(p')$
\end_inset

 cannot occur whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 are price vectors that are not collinear.
 By homogeneity of degree zero, we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'\geq p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}=p_{l}'$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 Now, consider altering the price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

 to obtain the price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L-1$
\end_inset

 steps, lowering the price of every commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq l$
\end_inset

 one at a time.
 By gross substitution, the excess demand of good 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 cannot decrease in any step, and, because 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq p'$
\end_inset

, it will actually increase in at least one step.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{l}(p)>z_{l}(p')$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Core
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally consider an economy wth 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 consumers.
 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 consumer has consumption set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

, and endowment vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

, and a continuous, strictly convex, strongly monotone preference relation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 There is also a publicly available constant returns convex technology 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subset\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, we could have 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=-\mathbb{R}_{+}^{L}$
\end_inset

, that is a pure exchange economy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that an allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{LI}$
\end_inset

 is feasible if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}=y+\sum_{i}\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Coalition.
 A coalition 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq I$
\end_inset

 (nonempty) improves upon, or blocks, the feasible allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in S$
\end_inset

 we can find a consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 with properties: (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in S$
\end_inset

, (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in S}x_{i}\in Y+\{\sum_{i\in S}\omega_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This definition means that a coalition 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 can improve upon a feasible allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 if there is some way that, by using only their endowments 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in S}\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the publicly available technology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(The core property) We say that the set of feasible allocations 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 has the core property if there is no coalition of consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq I$
\end_inset

 that can improve upon 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are able to define the core.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(The core) The core is the set of allocations that have the core property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $I=2$
\end_inset

, the Core is equivalent to the Contract Curve of the Edgeworth box.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Any Walrasian equilibrium allocation has the core property.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 be a Walrasian allocation with corresponding equilibrium price 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Consider an arbitrary coalition 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subset I$
\end_inset

 and suppose that the consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in S}$
\end_inset

 are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\succ_{i}x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in S$
\end_inset

.
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot x_{i}>p\cdot\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in S$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot(\sum_{i\in S}x_{i})>p\cdot(\sum_{i\in S}\omega_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{i}\}_{i\in S}$
\end_inset

 is not feasible.
 So coalition 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 cannot block 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However, not all allocations in the Core are Walrasian allocations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When 
\begin_inset Formula $I\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 (achieved by replica economies) then the Core converges to the Walrasian
 allocations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Testable restrictions on the equilibrium manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Brown Matzkin (BM) present a finite system of polynomial inequalities in
 unobservable variables and market data that observations on market prices,
 individual incomes, and aggregate endowments must satisfy to be consistent
 with the equilibrium behavior of some pure trade economy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantifier elimination is used to derive testable restrictions on finite
 data sets for the pure trade model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A characterization for aggregate endowment economy Robinson Crusoe's economy
 is also provided.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem is that due to Sonnenschein-Debreu-Mantel theorem SDM, the Slutsky
 restrictions on individual excess demand functions do not extend to market
 excess demand functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mas-Collel (1977) shows that utility maximization subject to a budget constraint
 imposes no testable restrictions on the set of equilibrium prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The setting.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Market excess demand function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\hat{w}}(p)$
\end_inset

 where the profile of individual endowments 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{w}$
\end_inset

 is fixed but market prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 may vary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Equilibrium manifold, we denote the market excess demand as 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\hat{w},p)$
\end_inset

 where both 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{w}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 may vary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The equilibrium manifold is defined as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\hat{w},p)|F(\hat{w},p)=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Contrary to the result of Mas-Colell, BM show that utility maximization
 subject to a budget constraint does impose testable restrictions on the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equilibrium manifold
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Afriat's theorem (1967) is the key for the result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Afriat's theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Afriat use the Theorem of Alternatives, proved the equivalence of a finite
 family of linear inequalities that contains unobservable utility levels
 with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

observable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cyclical consistency or GARP.
 And the existence of a concave, continuous monotonic utility function rationali
zing the observed data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Afriat's theorem is an instance of a deep theorem in model theory, Tarski-Seid
enberg theorem or quantifier elimination.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Tarski-Seidenberg theorem proves that any finite system of polynomial
 inequalities can be reduced to an equivalent finite family of polynomial
 inequalities in the coefficients of the given system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The Tarski-Seidenberg theorem provides and algorithm which in principle
 can be used to carry out the elimination of the unobservable in a finite
 number of steps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Each time a variable is eliminated an equivalent system of polynomial
 inequalities is obtained, which contains all the variables except those
 that have been eliminated up to that point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ALGORITHM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Algorithm ends if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) 1=0 the original system of polynomial inequalities is never satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) 1=1 the original system is always satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) an equivalent finite family of polynomials inequalities in the coefficient
s of the original system which is satisfied only by some parameters values
 of the coefficients.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The plan is to apply the Tarski-Seidenberg theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Step 1: Express the structural conditions of the pure trade model as a
 finite family of polynomial inequalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Step 2: To derive equivalent conditions on the data, the coefficients
 in this family of polynomial must be market observables - individual endowments
 and market prices-.
 The unknowns must be the unobservables in the theory.
 (Utility level of individuals, marginal utilities of income, and consumption
 bundles).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DATA:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prices and endowments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unknowns:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Utility level.
 Consumption can be derived using Roy and marginal utility of income is
 derived form the primitive 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
INEQUALITIES.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- For every agent the Afriat's inequalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The budget constraint of each agent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Market clearing equations for each observation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TARSKI-SEIDENBERG ALGORITHM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) 1=0 the given equilibrium conditions are inconsistent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) 1=1 there is no finite data set that refutes the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(iii) the equilibrium conditions are testable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- THE ALGORITHM IS NON POLYNOMIAL AND DOUBLE EXPONENTIAL.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
HOWEVER, for the case of pure trade model it suffices to show that the algorithm
 cannot terminate in 1=0 and 1=1, to show that it must end in (iii) and
 therefore it has testable implications.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This does not solve the problem of actually testing the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PROOF:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From Arrow-Debreu existence Tarski-Seidenberg algorithm will not terminate
 in 1=0 (i).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They construct an example of Pure trade model where no values of the unobservabl
es are consistent with the values of the observables.
 Hence the algorithm will not stop 1=1 (ii).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CONCLUSION.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore the Tarski-Seidenberg theorem implies for any finite family of
 profiles of individual endowments 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{w}$
\end_inset

 and market prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 that these observations lie on the equilibrium manifold of a pure trade
 economy, for some family of concave, continuous, an monotonic utility functions
, if an only if they satisfy the derived family of polynomial inequalities
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{w}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- This family of polynomial inequalities constitute the testable restrictions
 of the Walrasian model of pure trade.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- They derive restrictions for two observations.
 For more than two the conditions are necessary not sufficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- WARE weak axiom of revealed equilibrium.
 Even if pairwise it is fulfilled, a third observation may violate the condition
s then this conditions are not sufficient, but certainly necessary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Key assumption: The authors do not assume that individual consumptions
 are observed as did Afriat.
 As a consequence the Afriat inequalities in our model are nonlinear in
 the unknowns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Restriction in the pure trade model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 commodities 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 traders, under pure trade model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Commodity space 
\begin_inset Formula $X=R^{K}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Each agent has 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{+}^{K}$
\end_inset

 as the consumption set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Traders characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}\in R_{++}^{K}$
\end_inset

 and a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}:R_{+}^{K}\rightarrow R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 are assumed to be continuous, monotone and concave.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Allocation: consumption vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}\in R_{+}^{K}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{t=1}^{T}x_{t}=\sum_{t=1}^{T}w_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- The price simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\{p\in R_{+}^{K}|\sum_{i=1}^{K}p_{i}=1\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Only positive prices 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{p\in\Delta|p_{i}>0\quad\forall i\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Competitive equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{t}\}_{t=1}^{T}$
\end_inset

 and prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- Each 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 is utility maximizing for 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 to budget constraint.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equilibrium prices
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DATA:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we observe 
\begin_inset Formula $\{w^{r}\}_{r=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 and prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We observe the Walrasian correspondence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Map from endowment profiles to equilibrium prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
