\begin_layout Subsection
The pure trade model is testable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (1) The pure trade model is testable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system of equilibrium inequalities is a finite family of polynomial
 inequalities.
 Then this is a consequence of Tarski-Seidenberg algorithm.
 BM have shown cannot terminate in 1=0 or 1=1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When income is observable.
 Only aggregate endowment is observed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $I_{t}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is the income of consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 a in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{r}$
\end_inset

 the aggregate endowment in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (2) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $<p^{r},\{I_{t}^{r}\}_{t=1}^{T},w^{r}>$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

 be given.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then there exists a set of continuous, concave, and monotone utility functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{V_{t}\}_{t=1}^{T}$
\end_inset

 such that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

 is an equilibrium price vector for the exchange economy 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $<\{V_{t}\}_{t=1}^{T},\{I_{t}^{r}\}_{t=1}^{T},w^{r}>$
\end_inset

 if and only if there exists numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\overline{V}_{r}^{r}\}_{t=1,\cdots,T;r=1,\cdots,N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\lambda_{t}^{r}\}_{t=1,\cdots,T;r=1,\cdots,N}$
\end_inset

 and vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{t}^{r}\}_{t=1,\cdots,T;r=1,\cdots,N.}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2.1) 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{r}^{t}-\overline{V}_{s}^{t}-\lambda_{r}^{t}p_{r}^{t}\cdot(x_{r}^{t}-x_{s}^{t})\leq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $r,s\in\{1,\cdots,N\};t\in\{1,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2.2) 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}^{r}>0,x_{t}^{r}\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\{1,\cdots,N\};t\in\{1,\cdots,T\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2.3) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}\cdot x_{t}^{r}=I_{t}^{r}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2.4) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{t=1}^{T}x_{t}^{r}=w^{r}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2.1)-(2.3) by Afriat's theorem imply that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, there exists a continuous concave, monotone utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}:R_{+}^{K}\rightarrow R$
\end_inset

 such that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $r,x_{t}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is one of the maximizers of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}\cdot y\leq I_{t}^{r}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2.4.) Guarantees that this maximization is a feasible allocation and therefore
 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}$
\end_inset

 is an equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The converse is immediate, by Arrow Debreu and Kuhn-Tucker theorem that
 assure the existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\lambda^{r}\}_{t=1}^{T}$
\end_inset

 such that (2.1) and (2.2) hold where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}^{r}=V_{t}(x_{t}^{r})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Revealed Equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For two observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2$
\end_inset

 and Chiappori-Rochet version of the Afriat's theorem we use in the proof
 of Theorem 3 below, quantifier elimination to derive testable restrictions
 for a pure trade model with two consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a,b$
\end_inset

 from the equilibrium inequalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
WEAK AXIOMS OF REVEALED EQUILIBRIUM.
 WARE.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Most expensive bundle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}_{t}^{r}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2;t=a,b$
\end_inset

, is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{z}_{t}^{r}\in argmax_{x}\{p^{s}\cdot x|p^{r}\cdot x=I_{t}^{r},0\leq x\leq w^{r}\}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq s$
\end_inset

.
 Hence among all the bundles that are feasible in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and are on the budget hyperplane of consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}_{t}^{r}$
\end_inset

 is any of the bundles that cost the most under prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{s}(s\neq r)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 WARE.
 We say that observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p^{r}\}_{r=1,2};\{I_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b};\{w^{r}\}_{r=1,2}$
\end_inset

 satisfy WARE if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(I) 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall r=1,2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{a}^{r}+I_{b}^{r}=p^{r}\cdot w^{r}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(II) 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall r,s=1,2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(r\neq s)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall t=a,b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $[(p^{s}\cdot\overline{z}_{t}^{r}\leq I_{t}^{s})\implies(p^{r}\cdot\overline{z}_{t}^{s}>I_{t}^{r})],$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(III) 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall r,s=1,2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(r\neq s)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $[(p^{s}\cdot\overline{z}_{a}^{r}\leq I_{a}^{s})\wedge(p^{s}\cdot\overline{z}_{b}^{r}\leq I_{b}^{s})]\implies(p^{r}\cdot w^{s}>p^{r}\cdot w^{r}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(I) Condition for income and aggregate endowment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(II) WARP in this setting.
 This applies when all bundles in the budget hyperplane of consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 that are feasible in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 can be purchased with the income and prices faced by consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(s\neq r)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then it must be the case that some of the bundles that are feasible in observati
on 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and are in the budget hyperplane of consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 cannot be purchased with the income and prices faced by consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(p^{r}\cdot\overline{z}_{t}^{s}>I_{t}^{r})$
\end_inset

.
 The consumer A does not satisfy this conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(III) This guarantees that at least one of the pairs of consumption bundles
 in observation 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 that contain for each agent feasible and affordable bundles that could
 not be purchased with the income and price of observation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 are such that they add up to the aggregate endowment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (3) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p^{r}\}_{r=1,2};\{I_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b};\{w^{r}\}_{r=1,2}$
\end_inset

 be given such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1}$
\end_inset

 is not a scalar multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the equilibrium inequalities for strictly monotone, strictly concave,
 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 utility functions have a solution, i.e.
 the data lies on the equilibrium manifold of some economy whose consumers
 have strictly monotone, strictly concave 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 utility functions, if an only if the data satisfy WARE.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the Tarski-Seidenberg theorem, we need to show WARE can be derived
 by quantifier elimination from the equilibrium inequalities for strictly
 monotone, strictly concave 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 utility functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Making use of Chiappori and Rochet (1987) these inequalities are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\{\overline{V}_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b},\{\lambda_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b},\{x_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b}$
\end_inset

 such that.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.1) 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{1}^{2}-\overline{V}_{t}^{1}-\lambda_{t}^{1}p^{1}\cdot(x_{t}^{2}-x_{t}^{1})<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a,b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.2) 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{t}^{1}-\overline{V}_{t}^{2}-\lambda^{2}p^{2}\cdot(x_{t}^{1}-x_{t}^{2})<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a,b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.3) 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}^{r}>0,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2;t=a,b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We eliminate 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\lambda_{t}^{r}\}_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\{\overline{V}_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b},\{x_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.1)' 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1}\cdot(x_{t}^{2}-x_{t}^{1})\leq0\implies\overline{V}_{t}^{2}<\overline{V}_{t}^{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a,b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.2)' 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}\cdot(x_{t}^{1}-x_{t}^{2})\leq0\implies\overline{V}_{t}^{1}<\overline{V}_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a,b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.4) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}\cdot x_{t}^{r}=I_{t}^{r}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall r,t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.5) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1}\neq p^{2}\implies x_{t}^{1}\neq x_{t}^{2},t=a,b;$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.6) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}^{r}\geq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2;t=a,b;$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.7) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}^{r}+x_{b}^{r}=w^{r}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Necessity is trivial.
 Sufficiency follows by noticing that 
\begin_inset Formula $(C,1)'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(C.2)'$
\end_inset

 imply 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\{\lambda_{t}^{1}\}_{t=a,b}$
\end_inset

 satisfying C.1 and C.3 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\{\lambda_{t}^{2}\}$
\end_inset

 satisfying C.2 and C.3.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Elimination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\overline{V}_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b}$
\end_inset

 yields the equivalent expression.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\{x_{t}^{r}\}_{r=1,2;t=a,b}$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.1'') 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1}\cdot(x_{t}^{2}-x_{t}^{1})\leq0\implies p^{2}\cdot(x_{t}^{1}-x_{t}^{2})>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a,b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.4) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{r}\cdot x^{r}=I_{t}^{r},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $t=a,b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.5) 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{1}\neq p^{2}\implies x_{t}^{1}\neq x_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $t=a,b$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.6) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}^{r}\geq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2;t=a,b;$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C.7) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}^{r}+x_{b}^{r}=w^{r}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is Afriat's theorem for two observations.
 Strong SARP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next elimination is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{b}^{r}\}_{r=1,2}$
\end_inset

, using (C.7) yield the equivalent expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists x_{a}^{1},x_{a}^{2}$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next reduce 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and let everything in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}_{t}^{r}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Sequential Trade
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 consumers, 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 firms, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 states of the world each of them with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{is}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 of being realized according to 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $LS$
\end_inset

 state-contingent commodities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For every physical commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $l=1,\cdots,L$
\end_inset

 and states 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,\cdots,S$
\end_inset

, a unit of (state-)contingent commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $ls$
\end_inset

 is a title to receive a unit of the physical commodity 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 occurs.
 Accordingly, a (state-)contingent commodity vector is specified by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=(x_{11},\cdots,x_{L1},\cdots,x_{1S},\cdots,x_{LS})\in\mathbb{R}^{LS},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
and is understood as an entitlement to receive commodity vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1s},\cdots,x_{Ls})$
\end_inset

 if state 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 occurs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The state-contingent endowments for consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,I$
\end_inset

 be a contingent commodity vector: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{i}=(\omega_{11i},\cdots,\omega_{L1i},\cdots,\omega_{1Si},\cdots,\omega_{LSi})\in\mathbb{R}^{LS}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preferences are defined over 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\subset\mathbb{R}^{LS}$
\end_inset

, and denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 and are of the Expected Utility Form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}\succeq_{i}x_{i}'\iff\sum_{s}\pi_{si}u_{si}(x_{1si},\cdots,x_{Lsi})\geq\sum_{s}\pi_{si}u_{si}(x'_{1si},\cdots,x'_{Lsi}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly technological possibilities are represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}\subset\mathbb{R}^{LS}$
\end_inset

, or state-contingent production plan 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in\mathbb{R}^{LS}$
\end_inset

 is a member of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{j}$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 the plan 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{s}$
\end_inset

 of physical commodities is feasible for firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 when state 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 occurs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An allocation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{1}^{*},\cdots,x_{I}^{*},y_{1}^{*},\cdots,y_{J}^{*})\in\prod_{i=1}^{I}X_{i}\times\prod_{j=1}^{J}Y_{j}\subset\mathbb{R}^{LS(I+J)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
and a system of prices for the contigent commodities 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{11},\cdots,p_{LS})\in\mathbb{R}^{LS}$
\end_inset

 constitute an Arrow-Debreu equilibrium if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot y_{j}^{*}\geq p\cdot y_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}\in Y_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is maximal for 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the budget set 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{x_{i}\in X_{i}:p\cdot x_{i}\leq p\cdot\omega_{i}+\sum_{j}\theta_{ij}p\cdot y_{j}^{*}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{i}^{*}=\sum_{j}y_{j}^{*}+\sum_{i}\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
At 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

, if the economy is in Arrow-Debreu Eq.
 when uncertainty is realized there is no incentive to trade further.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason is that due to the first welfare theorem the allocations are
 efficient and thus there is no incentive to trade.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sequential Trade
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a case where there are not 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 markets, but only one good can be traded at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 consumers make predictions about spot prices for each 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\cdots p_{S})\in\mathbb{R}^{LS}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then the consumer trades the only state contingent commodity at prices
 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}^{S}$
\end_inset

.
 The problem of consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Max_{\begin{array}{c}
(x_{1i},\cdots,x_{Si})\in\mathbb{R}^{L}\forall s\in S\\
(z_{1i},\cdots,z_{Si})\in\mathbb{R}^{S}
\end{array}}U_{i}(x_{1i},\cdots,x_{Si})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad(i)\sum_{s}q_{s}z_{si}\leq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(ii)p_{s}\cdot x_{si}\leq p_{s}\cdot\omega_{si}+p_{1s}z_{si}\forall s\in S
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Restriction (i) corresponds to trade in 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Radner Equilibrium) A collection formed by a price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}^{S}$
\end_inset

 for state-contingent first good commodity at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 a spot price vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=(p_{1},\cdots,p_{S})\in\mathbb{R}^{SL}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
for every 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and for every consumer
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, consumption plans 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}^{*}=(z_{1i}^{*},\cdots,z_{Si}^{*})\in\mathbb{R}^{S}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}=(x_{1i}^{*},\cdots x_{Si}^{*})\in\mathbb{R}^{LS}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 constitutes a Rander equilibrium if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the consumption plans 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 solve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Max_{\begin{array}{c}
(x_{1i},\cdots,x_{Si})\in\mathbb{R}^{L}\forall s\in S\\
(z_{1i},\cdots,z_{Si})\in\mathbb{R}^{S}
\end{array}}U_{i}(x_{1i},\cdots,x_{Si})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t.\quad(i)\sum_{s}q_{s}z_{si}\leq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(ii)p_{s}\cdot x_{si}\leq p_{s}\cdot\omega_{si}+p_{1s}z_{si}\forall s\in S
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}z_{si}^{*}\leq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}x_{si}^{*}\leq\sum_{i}\omega_{si}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
We make two normalizations (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1s}=1$
\end_inset

 and (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) If the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}\in\mathbb{R}^{LSI}$
\end_inset

 and the contingent commodities price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in(p_{1},\cdots,p_{S})\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{LS}$
\end_inset

 constitue an Arrow-Debreu equilibrium, then there are prices 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{S}$
\end_inset

for contingent first good commodities and consumption plans for these commoditie
s 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}\in\mathbb{R}^{SI}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*},z^{*},q,p$
\end_inset

 constitute a Radner Equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) Conversely, if the consumption plans 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}\in\mathbb{R}^{LSI}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{*}\in\mathbb{R}^{SI}$
\end_inset

 and the price 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{S}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{1},\cdots,p_{S})\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{LS}$
\end_inset

 constitute a Rander equilibrium, then there are multipliers 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu_{1},\cdots,\mu_{S})\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{S}$
\end_inset

 such that the allocation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 and the contingent commodities price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu_{1}p_{1},\cdots,\mu_{S}p_{S})\in\mathbb{R}_{++}^{LS}$
\end_inset

 constitute an Arrow-Debreu equilibrium.
 (The multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{s}$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as the value at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 of a dollar at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

 and state 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) If we have an Arrow-Debreu equilibrium, we can let 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{s}=p_{1s}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 With this we claim that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the budget set for the Arrow-Debreu problem is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{i}^{AD}=\{x\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{LS}:\sum_{s}p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})\leq0\},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is identical to the budget set of Radner's.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{i}^{R}=\{x\in\mathbb{R}_{+}^{LS}:\exists z_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{S},s.t.\sum_{s}q_{s}z_{si}\leq0\quad and\quad p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})\leq p_{1s}z_{si}\forall s\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see this suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in B_{i}^{AD}$
\end_inset

.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $s,$
\end_inset

 denote 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{si}=(1/p_{1s})p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{s}q_{s}z_{si}=\sum_{s}p_{1s}z_{si}=\sum_{s}p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})\leq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})=p_{1s}z_{si}$
\end_inset

 fo all 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in B_{i}^{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reverse is also true, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in B_{i}^{R}$
\end_inset

, that is for some 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{s}q_{s}z_{si}\leq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})\leq p_{1s}z_{si}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Summing over 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{s}p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})\leq\sum_{s}p_{1s}z_{si}=\sum_{s}q_{s}z_{si}\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in B_{i}^{AD}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have established that the following sets are equal/equivalent: 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}^{AD}\equiv B_{i}^{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus AD is Radner with 
\begin_inset Formula $q=(p_{11},\cdots,p_{1S})\in\mathbb{R}^{S}$
\end_inset

, the spot prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},\cdots,p_{S}$
\end_inset

 and the contingent trades 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{1i}^{*},\cdots,z_{Si}^{*})\in\mathbb{R}^{S}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{si}^{*}=(1/p_{1s})p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}^{*}-\omega_{si})$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the contingent market clears since for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}z_{si}^{*}=(1/p_{1s})p_{s}\cdot(\sum_{i}(x_{si}^{*}-\omega_{si}))\leq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{s}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{s}p_{1s}=q_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write Radners budget set of every consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{i}^{R}=\{(x_{i1},\cdots,x_{si})\in\mathbb{R}^{LS}:\exists z_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{S},s.t.,\sum_{s}q_{s}z_{si}\leq0\quad and\quad\mu_{s}p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})\leq q_{s}z_{si}\forall s\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can rewrite this as the AD budget 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{i}^{R}=B_{i}^{AD}=\{x\in\mathbb{R}^{LS}:\sum_{s}\mu_{s}p_{s}\cdot(x_{si}-\omega_{si})\leq0\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence the consumption plan 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is also preference maximizing in the budget set 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}^{AD}$
\end_inset

.
 Since this is true for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, we conclude that the price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu_{1}p_{1},\cdots,\mu_{S}p_{S})\in\mathbb{R}^{LS}$
\end_inset

 clears the markets for the 
\begin_inset Formula $LS$
\end_inset

 contingent commodities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Matching
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
One-to-One Matching: Marriage Problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A marriage problem (Gale and Shapley 1962) is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $<M,W,\succeq>$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a finite set of men and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a finite set of women, 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq=(\succeq_{i})_{i\in M\cup W}$
\end_inset

 is a list of preferences.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{m}$
\end_inset

 denotes the preference relation of man 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $W\cup\{m\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq_{w}$
\end_inset

 denotes the preference of woman 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cup\{w\}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes the strict preference derived for agent 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in M\cup W$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider man 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $w\succ_{m}w'$
\end_inset

 means that man 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 prefers woman 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $w'$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $w\succ_{m}m$
\end_inset

 means that man 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 prefers 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 to remain single, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $m\succ_{m}w$
\end_inset

 means that woman 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is unacceptable to man 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
All preference are strict.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The outcome of a marriage problem is a matching.
 Formally, a matching is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:M\cup W\mapsto M\cup W$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(m)\notin W\implies\mu(m)=m\quad\forall m\in M,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(w)\notin M\implies\mu(w)=w\quad\forall w\in W$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(m)=w\iff\mu(w)=m\quad\forall m\in M,w\in M$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(i)=i$
\end_inset

 represents that the agent 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 remains single.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matching 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is Pareto efficient if there is no other matching 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(i)\succeq_{i}\mu(i)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in M\cup W$
\end_inset

 and at least some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in M\cup W$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(i)\succ_{i}\mu(i)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matching is blocked by an individual if 
\begin_inset Formula $i\succ_{i}\mu(i)$
\end_inset

.
 A matching is individually rational if it is not blocked by any individual.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matching 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is blocked by a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,w)\in M\times W$
\end_inset

 if they both prefer each other to their partners under 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w\succ_{m}\mu(m)\quad and\quad m\succ_{w}\mu(w).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matching is stable if it is not blocked by any individual pair.
 The next result follows inmediately.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Stability implies Pareto Efficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following is an algorithm and its versions played a central role for
 almost 50 years in ot only matching theory but also its application in
 real-life matching markets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Men-Proposing Deferred Acceptance Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 1.
 Each man 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 proposes to his first choice (if any).
 Each woman rejects any offer except the best acceptable proposal and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the most-preferred acceptable proposal (if any).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, at
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step k.
 Any man who was rejected at step 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

 makes a new proposal to his most-preferred acceptable potential mate who
 has not yet rejected him (if no acceptable choice remains, then he makes
 no proposal).
 Each woman 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 her most-preferred acceptable proposal to date and rejects the rest.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm terminates when there are not more rejections.
 Each woman is matched with a man she has been holding in the last step.
 Any woman who has not been holding an offer or any man who was rejected
 by all acceptable woman remains single.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(Thm.
 1,2 in Gale and Shapley, 1962) The men proposing deferred acceptance algorithm
 gives a stable matching for each marriage problem.
 Moreover, every man weakly prefers this matching to any other stable matching.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Improvement Lemma.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 proposes to 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 on the 
\begin_inset Formula $kth$
\end_inset

 day, then on 
\begin_inset Formula $k+i$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 has someone 
\begin_inset Formula $m'$
\end_inset

 that has proposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m'\succ_{w}m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose towards contradiction that on the 
\begin_inset Formula $jth$
\end_inset

 day 
\begin_inset Formula $j>k$
\end_inset

 we have the first counter-example, where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 has either nobody or some 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m\succ_{w}m^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 On 
\begin_inset Formula $j-1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $m'$
\end_inset

 that proposed to her and likes 
\begin_inset Formula $m'\succ_{w}m$
\end_inset

.
 According to the algorithm, 
\begin_inset Formula $m'$
\end_inset

 still proposes to 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $jth$
\end_inset

, since she hold his proposal the previous day.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 has the choice of at least one man on 
\begin_inset Formula $jth$
\end_inset

, moreover the best choice has to be at least as good as 
\begin_inset Formula $m'$
\end_inset

, there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $m''\succeq_{w}m'$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim_{w}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $m'=m''$
\end_inset

, according to the algorithm she will choose it over 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the initial statement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lemma.
 The algorithm terminates with a pairing.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $|M|=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|W|=n$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose for contradiciton that there is a man 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 who is left unpaired, at the end of the algorithm.
 He must have proposed to every single woman on his list.
 By the Improvement Lemma, each of these women thereafter has someone that
 has proposed to them.
 Thus when the algorithm terminates, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 women have 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 men proposing to them non including 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 So there must be at least 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 men.
 Contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lemma.
 The matching is stable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to prove that no man can be in a rouge couple, or in a blocking
 pair.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(m)=w$
\end_inset

 and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{*}\succ_{m}w$
\end_inset

.
 We will prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(w^{*})\succ_{w^{*}}m$
\end_inset

.
 So that 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,w^{*})$
\end_inset

 cannot be a rouge couple.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{*}\succ_{m}w$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 proposed to her first and 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{*}$
\end_inset

 rejected him for some other 
\begin_inset Formula $m'$
\end_inset

.
 By the improvement lemma and transitivity we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(w^{*})\succeq_{w^{*}}m'\succ_{w^{*}}m$
\end_inset

.
 Thus no man 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 can be involved in a rouge couple, and the pairing is stable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
One-Sided Matching: House Allocation and Housing Markets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A house allocation problem (Hylland and Zeckhauser 1979) is a triple 
\begin_inset Formula $<I,H,\succ>$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a set of agents, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a set of of indivisible objects (henceforth houses).
 Preferences are 
\begin_inset Formula $\succ=(\succ_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 Throughout this section we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=|I|$
\end_inset

 and the preference are strict.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The outcome of a house allocation problem is an assignment of houses to
 agents such that each agent receives a house.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A house matching is a mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:I\mapsto H$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one and onto from 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 (isomorphism).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matching 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 Pareto dominates another matching if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(i)\succeq_{i}\nu(i)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(i)\succ_{i}v(i)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 A matching is Pareto efficient if it is not Pareto dominated by any other
 matching.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A house allocation problem is simply a collective ownership economy where
 a number of houses shall be assigned to a number of agents.
 It is an economy where the grand coalition 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 owns the set of houses 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, but no subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 has any say over a house or set of houses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In constrast, the following economy is a private ownership economy, where
 each agent holds the property rights of a specific house.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A housing market (Shapley and Scarf 1974) is a four-tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $<I,H,\succ,\mu>$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is an initial endowment of houses.
 Formally a housing market is a set of houses.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}=\mu(i)$
\end_inset

 denote the initial endowment of agent 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Core of a Housing Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matching 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is individually rational if 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(i)\succeq_{i}h_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 A matching 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is in the core of the housing market 
\begin_inset Formula $<I,H,\succ,\mu>$
\end_inset

 if there is no coalition 
\begin_inset Formula $T\subseteq I$
\end_inset

 and matching 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(i)\in\{h_{j}\}_{j\in T}\forall i\in T$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(i)\succeq_{i}\eta(i)\forall i\in T$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v(i)\succ_{i}\eta(i)\exists i\in T.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following algorithm, along with the deferred acceptance algorithms,
 plays a key role in the matching literature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Gale's Top Trading Cycles (TTC) Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 1.
 Each agent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

points to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the owner of his favorite house.
 Since there is a finite number of agents, there is at least one cycle of
 agents pointing to one another.
 Each agent in a cycle is assigned the house of the agent he points to and
 removed from the market with his assignment.
 If there is at least one remaining agent, proceed with the next step.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, at
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Step 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Each remaining agent points to the owner of his favorite house among the
 remaining houses.
 Every agent in a cycle is assigned the house of the agent he points to
 and removed form the market with his assignment.
 If there is at least one remaining agent, proceed with the next step.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(Thm.
 2 in Roth and Postlewaite 1977): The outcome of Gale's TTC algorithm is
 the unique matching in the core of each housing market.
 Moreover, this matching is the unique competitive allocation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There exists a core matching for any housing market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 be the resulting matching from the TTC.
 Suppose there is a coalition 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 who deviates profitably from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, inducing 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, then each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in T$
\end_inset

 prefers 
\begin_inset Formula $v(i)\succ_{i}\mu(i)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be an agent that is matched first among this subset in the TTC algorithm.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $v(a)$
\end_inset

 is owned by an agent 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in T$
\end_inset

 who is removed by the TTC algorithm in a strictly early step (say cycle
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 obtains a house 
\begin_inset Formula $b'\in T\cap C_{m}$
\end_inset

 both in 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{k}\in T\cap C_{m}$
\end_inset

 obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $v(a)$
\end_inset

 both at 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matching produced by the TTC algorithm is unique.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an arbitrary matching 
\begin_inset Formula $v\neq\mu$
\end_inset

, and fix 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 to be one of the first agents with 
\begin_inset Formula $v(a)\neq\mu(a)$
\end_inset

 according to the order of being matched in TTC.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset

 be the set of agents that form a cycle that includes 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, any agents 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 who are matched before 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $v(b)=\mu(b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By construction of TTC, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(b)\succeq_{b}v(b)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in C_{m}$
\end_inset

 (because, in 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, all preferred goods are allocated to those who are matched before 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, since 
\begin_inset Formula $v(a)\neq\mu(a)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in C_{m}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(a)\succ_{a}v(a)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in C_{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(b)$
\end_inset

 is an initial house owned by some other agent in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset

, these facts imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{m}$
\end_inset

 can profitable deviate from 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Computable General Equilibrium (CGE)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Computable General Equilibrium (CGE) analysis is an ex-ante policy evaluatio
n tool that uses a mix of micro and macro data, calibration and estimation,
 to generate consistent escenarios for counterfactual policies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In sum, we write a parametric general equilibrium model that reproduces
 the sectorial macro-accounts of a country.
 Then we use the model to ask what would happen under a change of a policy,
 such that the macro accountability identities are respected and such that
 individual households and firms optimization principles are taken into
 account.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This tool is widely used by policy making institutions around the world.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I am going to use Erinc Yeldan's notes on a simple CGE for an open 2x2 Ricardo-V
iner General Equilibrium model with sector specific capital.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 Small Open Economy Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By small open economy we mean that the economy is price-taker for internationall
y traded goods.
 There are two goods and two factors of production, labor and capital (
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Labor is mobile across sectors, but capital is sector-specific.
 There are two households, workers and capitalists.
 Preferences are Cobb-Douglas.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Tabular
