\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Social Accounting Matrix (SAM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Social Accounting Matrix (SAM) is a comprehensive, economy-wide data framework
, typically representing the economy of a country.
 A SAM is a square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in which each account is represented by a row and a column.
 Each cell 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}$
\end_inset

 represents the payment from account 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to account 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Example: Consumption is given by the cells 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3,7}$
\end_inset

 for expenditure of households of type Worker to commodities of the rural
 type.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Wages are given by cells 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{5,1}$
\end_inset

 the payment of industry 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 Agriculture to labor factor 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Imports are in cell 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{9,3}$
\end_inset

(only rural good) and Exports are in cell 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4,9}$
\end_inset

 (only industrial good).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SAM is based on the double-entry accounting principle, that requires
 that for each column total (revenue) we have the same corresponding amount
 for expenditures of the same account.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="13" columns="12">
